<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Ambassadors 1stLd-Writethru a0770 06-21 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Ambassadors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0770, 660</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Gregg Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panel Postpones Action on Ambassadorial Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Ney's country from Turkey to Canada in 23rd graf, which
is 3rd bullet graf in group at bottom: ``_Edward N,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee
postponed action on three of President Bush's ambassadorial nominees
Tuesday after Democrats complained their only visible qualifications
are large GOP contributions.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., initiated the delay when he complained
that U.S. ambassadors should have at least some qualifications for
the job.
   The Senate is set to close down for the Independence Day recess,
so Sarbanes' request for a one-week delay effectively stops until
mid July at the earliest any action on the nominations to fill
ambassadorships in Spain, Australia and New Zealand.
   ``In the past we've had to hold our noses'' and let similar
nominees with political connections go through, Sarbanes said. ``But
eventually someone ought to say stop.''
   ``If it's going to be a bidding war ... at least we should put it
up for public bids so the money goes to the U.S. Treasury,''
Sarbanes said.
   Sarbanes targeted three. They are:
   _Joseph Zappala, a Florida land developer and national
co-chairman of Bush's fund raising committee who has been nominated
to be U.S. ambassador to Spain. Sarbanes said he contributed
$126,000 to the Bush campaign.
   _Marvin Sembler, a Florida shopping center tycoon who has been
named to be ambassador to Australia. Sarbanes said Sembler was a
$127,000 Bush contributor.
   _Della Newman, a Seattle, Wash., residential real estate broker
who has been nominated to be ambassador to New Zealand. She is a
long-time personal friend of Bush and was chairman of the Washington
State Bush For President Committee. Sarbanes said she had no
apparent qualifications except her personal and political ties.
   ``There seems to be a $100,000 threshhold'' for ambassadorships,
Sarbanes said.
   Sarbanes did ``reluctantly'' permit the committee to approve the
nomination of C. Howard Wilkins Jr., a $115,000 contributor to the
Bush campaign. Wilkins has been named to be ambassador to the
Netherlands and with the committee's action, an ambassador will be
in place when Bush visits the country next month.
   The full Senate later approved the Wilkins nomination on a voice
vote.
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., defended the records of the two
Floridians on Sarbanes' list saying, ``to imply they are not capable
is a disservice.''
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said: ``What we're doing is
delaying the appropriate representation this country should have
overseas.''
   And Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said the overall composition of
Bush's ambassadorial nominees to date is no different than the
choices of the Reagan administration's two-thirds Foreign Service
professionals and one third political appointees.
   ``These nominees are friends of the president, a part of the
organization of his coming to the presidency,'' Lugar said. ``They
share his ethos, his idealism and they will be so perceived in the
nations to which they are being sent.''
   Sarbanes said he has no objection to political nominees as such,
as long as they can claim some qualifications for the posts to which
they are named. He noted he did not object to Bush's nomination of
former Republican Gov. Robert D. Orr of Indiana to be ambassador to
Singapore.
   He said Orr had demonstrated his capabilities during his eight
years service as governor beginning in 1980.
   The committee did vote to recommend the Senate confirm Orr and a
list of other nominees.
   They are:
   _Thomas Niles, named to be U.S. representative to the European
Community.
   _Morton I. Abramowitz, to be ambassador to Turkey.
   _Edward N. Ney, to be ambassador to Canada.
   _Richard H. Solomon, to be assistant secretary of state for East
Asian and Pacific Affairs.
   _Melvyn Levitsky, to be assistant secretary of state for
international narcotics matters.
   _Jewel S. Lafontant, to be ambassador-at-large for refugee
affairs.
   _E. Patrick Coady, to be U.S. executive director for the
International Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
   _Mark L. Edelman, to be deputy administrator of the Agency for
International Development.
   _Fred M. Zeder II, to be president of the Overseas Private
Investment Corp.
</TEXT>
