<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Ascot     06-21 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Ascot,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ascot Race Goers Collapse Under Sweltering Sun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fashionably dressed race goers at the opening of
the four-day Royal Ascot meet sweltered in 88-degree heat and more
than 50 collapsed, first-aid workers reported.
   ``We've been very, very busy,'' said Patricia Gates of the St.
John Ambulance Brigade's volunteer corps. She said most of the
victims on Tuesday suffered mild sunstroke or fainted.
   It was the hottest June day in 13 years and the champagne stalls
were busy. The price of a bottle ranged from $33 to $70.
   Half a cold lobster cost $15.50, a serving of salmon $12.40 and
strawberries and clotted cream $3.10.
   Queen Elizabeth II, in a pink and turquoise silk-crepe dress and
straw hat, strolled through the crowds between the royal enclosure
where the elegant parade and the paddock where the horses are
paraded.
   Rules barring anyone under age 16 from the royal enclosure until
Friday, the closing day, were broken to admit the queen's 8-year-old
granddaughter, Zara Phillips, the daughter of Princess Anne.
   ``After all, the queen makes the rules,'' said a member of the
royal household. A spokesman for the Ascot Authority noted Ascot is
the monarch's racecourse.
   Prince Charles, the heir to the throne, left Ascot early to play
polo in nearby Windsor Great Park. Princess Diana went with him but
left after the first match.
</TEXT>
