<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Fence     06-21 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Fence,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Ministry Says Romania Builds Border Wire Fence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says Romania has nearly
completed construction of a 6-foot barbed wire fence along its
border with Hungary, but cast doubt on a foreign press report that a
brick wall is being built.
   The Times of London on Monday reported that Bucharest is building
a wall along its border with Hungary and Yugoslavia to prevent
defections.
   Hungary's official MTI news agency said Tuesday that its border
guards had reported ``no signs of wall construction.''
   ``Nevertheless, a 2{-meter wire fence is being set up on the
Romanian side of the border ... which has been completed along 90
percent of the border length,'' the agency said.
   ``Since it appears to be an ordinary wire fence, the (Hungarian)
border guards suppose that no electricity will be led into it,'' the
agency said. It added that the fence is about 80 feet inside
Romanian territory.
   ``The latest works indicate that ditches have been dug on both
sides of the fence to prevent breakthroughs by cars,'' MTI said.
   Romania's border with Hungary extends 275 miles.
   An estimated 30,000 Romanians, most of them ethnic Hungarians,
have fled to Hungary in the past few years seeking refuge from
chronic hardships under the regime of President Nicolae Ceausescu.
Ethnic Hungarians also claim discriminatory policies toward
minorities in Romania.
   During the first five months of this year, 3,231 Romanians
crossed ilegally into Hungary, deputy Interior Minister Zoltan Gal
said last week.
   He said the Cabinet would soon discuss plans to open three
refugees camps in eastern Hungary to cope with the influx.
</TEXT>
