<DOCNO> AP890621-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Palme-Press     06-21 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme-Press,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palme Trial Raises Questions About Unusual Swedish Press Ethics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedes may not learn the name or see the
face of the man accused of killing Prime Minister Olof Palme if they
read only their national newspapers.
   Carl Gustaf Christer Pettersson, who is on trial for the 1986
shooting, is known in Sweden only as ``the 42-year-old.''
   Under Swedish press law, the identity of a criminal suspect is
never published unless he is convicted and sentenced, and even then
it must clearly be in the public interest.
   The regulations are meant to protect the innocent, and a
newspaper and its senior editor can be fined for violating them.
   But the Palme murder trial has put the regulations under a
strain, and several provincial papers are disregarding them.
   ``Christer Pettersson is a historic person, whether guilty or
not,'' said Per Ahlstrom, editor of Nya Norrland, a daily with a
circulation of 20,000 in the northern town of Harnosand.
   ``I find that there is evident public interest that the name of
the person accused of the murder becomes public knowledge,'' he said.
   International news agencies and foreign newspapers published
Pettersson's identity and his police mug shot when he was charged in
December.
   Swedish papers ran into difficulty when Pettersson, known as
``the 41-year-old'' at the time, had a birthday in April. For a few
weeks he was referred to as ``the 42-year-old former 41-year-old.''
   About 20 newspapers have flouted the regulations, arguing it was
ridiculous to try to hide his identity when foreign newspapers
reporting the trial were available at major newsstands in Sweden.
   Other ironies also have become evident.
   Under Swedish freedom of information laws, Pettersson's name was
available after prosecutors filed the indictment last month. Anyone
who calls the Stockholm District Court can ask the court clerk to
read it over the telephone.
   Papers that have refrained from identifying Pettersson have, at
the same time, published every detail of his life, including his
police record, the location of his home and interviews with former
girlfriends.
   Kevin Boyle, director of the London-based ``Article 19,'' which
monitors press freedom in 50 countries, said the Swedish regulations
are ``highly exceptional'' if not unique.
   ``It is remarkable in that it contradicts the openness of
information in so many other areas where Sweden leads the world,''
Boyle said in an interview.
   He said the restrictions do not violate international law, but
they could inhibit the search for witnesses.
   Because of high public interest in the Palme case, the court let
Swedish Radio broadcast the trial with a one-second delay to allow a
technician to cover Pettersson's name with an electronic beep.
   The technician missed the beat the first time Pettersson's name
was mentioned, however.
   The broadcasts have been debated heatedly.
   Professor Carl Magnus Elwing of the University of Lund said they
have turned the trial into ``marketplace theater'' and diminished
the stature of the court. ``I would have acted forcefully to stop
it,'' Elwing said.
   Some critics said testimony heard on the radio could influence
subsequent witnesses.
   Presiding Judge Carl-Anton Spak ruled the broadcasts were in line
with the law and would be stopped only if they disturbed the trial
itself.
   Since then most of the witnesses, many of whom have criminal
records, have demanded that the broadcast be halted for their
testimony and the court has complied.
   Press Ombudsman Torsten Cars, who is employed by the newspaper
industry, said the caution regarding Pettersson's name goes beyond
the requirements of press ethics.
   ``It would not change much if the name were printed, considering
all the descriptions of his life that already have been published,''
he said. ``And there are thousands of Christer Petterssons in
Sweden. ... Publishing the picture is more serious.''
   Among those publishing the name is the newspaper Arbetet in
Malmo, a city across the Oregrund straits from Denmark, where such
restrictions do not apply.
   Arbetet was convicted of libel in 1987 and ordered to pay $27,000
in compensation to ``the 33-year-old,'' a suspect who earlier was
detained and released without charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-APainting'sValue     06-21 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-A Painting's Value,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canvas that Cost $8 in 1956 Sells for $150,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19th-century painting set in ancient Rome of a
young woman about to bathe has been sold at auction for $153,450 _
nearly 20,000 times its 1956 purchase price of $8.
   ``It certainly does reflect an extraordinary change in taste, but
that isn't unique in art,'' said Sotheby's Simon Taylor after the
sale Tuesday of ``Diadumene'' by Sir Edward Poynter.
   The auction house had expected more because of the vogue for
once-neglected Victorian works. It had estimated the painting would
fetch up to $232,500.
   Poynter, in 1885, had painted the young woman nude but he added
diaphanous drapery after it was exhibited at the Royal Academy of
Arts and provoked letters from shocked viewers.
   One letter to the press, signed ``British Matron,'' said the
writer had barred her daughters from going to the the exhibition.
Another letter said the painting would produce a ``burning sense of
shame'' in any ``modest woman on the arm of father, brother or
lover.''
   Poynter was known for such paintings but his most famous work,
reproduced in the tens of thousands in its day, was ``Faithful unto
Death.'' It depicted a Roman sentry staying at his post during the
destruction of Pompeii by the Vesuvius volcano.
   The seller and buyer of ``Diadumene'' were not identified.
   The painting had been auctioned in 1956 at a sale of the contents
of Ashley Manor, owned by Lady Agnes Chichester Dixon-Hartland.
   Top price at Tuesday's auction of 19th century European art was
$2.3 million _ more than double the estimate _ paid anonymously for
``Grandfather's Birthday,'' a family fireside scene by Austrian
artist Ferdinand Georg Waldmueller. It was a record for his work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
