<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     06-21 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Year at the Top for NBC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC completed a 52-week sweep of Nielsen ratings
despite CBS' broadcast of the final game of the Detroit Pistons'
sweep of the Los Angeles Lakers for the NBA championship.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' was the No. 1 show last week, but NBC had an
average, prime-time rating of 11.6. CBS had 10.2 and ABC 9.2.
   The last time NBC lost a week was to CBS, the week of the seventh
game of last year's National Basketball Association championship,
when the Lakers beat the Pistons. This year, game four ranked fourth
in the A.C. Nielsen Co. prime-time ratings, with a 17.4 rating and
31 share.
   NBC's average rating for the 52 weeks was 14.4. CBS and ABC tied
with 11.6.
   The top 10 shows during the past year were: ``Roseanne'' ABC,
``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``A Different World'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC,
``Golden Girls'' NBC, ``60 Minutes'' CBS, ``Empty Nest'' NBC, ``Dear
John'' NBC, ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC and ``Murder, She Wrote'' CBS.
   NBC has had eight of the top 10 shows 10 times during the past
year. ``Cosby'' was first in the Nielsens for 16 of the 52 weeks,
but ranked second behind ``Roseanne'' for the year _ and third
behind ``Roseanne'' and ``Cheers'' last week. ``Cosby'' had a lower
rating and higher share, because it is on at 8 p.m. EDT, when there
are fewer people watching TV than at 9 p.m., when ``Roseanne'' is on.
   The rating is a percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes in
the United States that have televisions. The share is a percentage
of sets in use. A show can have a lower rating and higher share than
another show by getting a larger percentage of a smaller available
audience.
   NBC said another reason ``Cosby'' fell behind ``Roseanne'' for
the year was because the newer ABC show did not have to factor in a
summer of reruns.
   The top 10 shows last week were: ``Roseanne'' ABC, ``Cheers''
NBC, ``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Detroit Pistons vs. Los Angeles
Lakers'' CBS, ``Perry Mason: The Case of the Murdered Madam'' NBC,
``A Different World'' NBC, ``Empty Nest'' NBC, ``Dear John'' NBC,
``Golden Girls'' NBC, and ``Unsolved Mysteries'' NBC, tied with
``Newhart'' on CBS.
   In a demonstration that time period makes the show, ABC's ``Have
Faith'' tied for 15th when it was on Tuesday behind ``Roseanne.''
But when it was moved into ABC's low-rated Sunday lineup, it fell to
76th and was the lowest-rated network show.
   ``NBC Nightly News'' continued to lag in news ratings, even with
anchorman Tom Brokaw in China. ``CBS Evening News'' and ``ABC World
News Tonight'' tied for first place with a 9.3 rating each and 20
share each. NBC had an average rating of 8.6 and a 19 share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
