<FIRST>r a PM-Names     06-21 0999</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,1040</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Fonda was unharmed after
becoming separated from companions in Sequoia National Park and
spending the night alone on a mountain, her spokesman said.
   Fonda didn't panic when she realized she was lost Sunday, said
her publicist, Steve Rivers. She wrapped herself in an insulated
blanket and ate a sandwich while she awaited help, he said.
   Fonda hiked ahead of her six companions and apparently took a
wrong turn, said Bill Tweed, a spokesman for the park 40 miles east
of Fresno.
   Her companions notified park officials when she failed to show up
at Moose Lake, their destination, or at their Pear Lake base camp,
Tweed said.
   A helicopter crew found Fonda on top of a mountain early Monday
and reunited her with her friends at the base camp. The group hiked
out together, Tweed said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN MATEO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rocker Bruce Springsteen donated $15,000
to a finacially strapped hospital where a relative was treated last
year.
   The donation by the ``Boss'' amounts to roughly half of the
$30,000 raised by employees at Chope Community Hospital.
   ``His agent called and asked us how much was in the fund and he
matched it,'' Tim McMurdo, the hospital's chief executive officer,
said Tuesday.
   Springsteen asked that his relationship to the former patient not
be disclosed.
   Employees started the fund-raising drive for capital improvements
and equipment in the wake of recent county budget shortfalls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vanessa Williams, the deposed Miss America who
appeared in Penthouse and went on to a successful recording career,
gave birth to a daughter this week.
   Jillian Kristin Hervey was born Monday at Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center, Miss Williams' husband, Ramon Hervey II, said Tuesday. The
mother and baby are healthy and doing well, said a spokesman in
Hervey's office.
   The couple's first daughter, Melanie Lynne, will be 2 on June 30.
   Miss Williams, the first black Miss America, was dethroned in a
1984 nude picture scandal. She currently has a hit single titled
``Darlin' I.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freddie Jackson says he almost didn't
take a chance on a singing career because he had a secure job as a
word processor.
   In 1982, Jackson's friend, songwriter Paul Laurence, suggested he
meet Melba Moore and try for a job as a background singer.
   ``I told him I think I should stay here and be the greatest word
processor in the world,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson went on to sing background for Moore, Lilo Thomas, Angela
Bofill and others on studio cuts and tours. Ms. Moore helped him
secure a contract with Columbia Records, which produced his 1985
debut album ``Rock Me Tonight.''
   The album and single ``Rock Me Tonight,'' both reached No. 1 on
Billboard's black charts. Jackson's follow-up, ``Just Like the First
Time,'' also was No. 1 on black charts with the hit singles, ``I
Don't Want to Lose Your Love,'' ``Look Around'', and ``Tasty Love.''
   His current album, ``Don't Let Love Slip Away,'' has landed the
single ``Crazy For Men'' in the pop Top 20.
   ``I'm going to stop singing when I'm not happy doing it
anymore,'' said Jackson. ``Right now, my ballads are things you want
when you want to dance romantically with someone, not pop songs.
Ballads live on and on.''

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music entertainer Lee Greenwood
will perform five shows for U.S. troops in Panama next week.
   Greenwood's USO tour Monday through June 29 includes performances
at Howard Air Base, Fort Clayton and Fort Espinar, World USO
President Chuck Hagel said Tuesday.
   ``Morale may be at a low point now in Panama since the U.S.
government sent families back to the States and moved the military
troops to the base,'' Greenwood said. ``So, when the USO asked me to
go to Panama and give the military community there a little taste of
home, I didn't hesitate.''
   Greenwood has won seven male vocalist of the year awards, the
Country Music Association's song of the year award for ``God Bless
the U.S.A.'' and a Grammy for best male country performance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adrienne Brown, wife of imprisoned soul
singer James Brown, will spend the next five years on probation as a
result of her guilty plea to a drug charge.
   She also was ordered Tuesday to pay a $5,000 fine and continue
with drug and alcohol screening.
   Mrs. Brown, 39, was arrested in May 1988 as she got off a plane
in Augusta and was charged with possessing the drug PCP. She had
been arrested on a similar charge six weeks earlier. One of two
charges was dropped when she pleaded guilty to the other.
   Brown, 56, is serving a six-year sentence at the State Park
Correctional Center near Columbia, S.C., for trying to run over two
policemen during an auto chase last fall.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Paterno says his autobiography will
be a lot more than a story about coaching football at Penn State.
   ``It's the story of my life and where I grew up and the things
that have influenced me,'' said the 62-year-old New York City native.
   ``Paterno: By The Book'' includes the coach's upbringing, his
thoughts on ethics in college sports and the Roman poet Virgil's
effect on his life.
   One lesson in the book due out in September: Winning is possible
without breaking the rules.
   ``It tells about some of the problems we've had and how we've
been able to succeed without intentionally breaking any rules,''
said Paterno, who co-authored the book with Penn State associate
English professor Bernard Asbell.
   In 23 years as Penn State's head coach, Paterno has won 212 games
and two national championships. Last year, the Nittany Lions
recorded their first losing season in 50 years.
   ``I'm not the goody-goody some people think,'' Paterno said
Tuesday. ``There are an awful lot of things about me I don't like.''
</TEXT>
