<FIRST>r a AM-BusShooting     06-21 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Shooting,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Refuses To Indict City Bus Driver In Slaying Of Passenger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dallas County grand jury on Tuesday declined to
indict a city bus driver accused of killing a passenger by shooting
him in the back after an argument.
   Chauncey J. Plummer, 37, a Dallas bus driver for 10 years, had
been charged with murder in the May 24 shooting of David Hayden, 25.
   Plummer picked up Hayden and a woman on a downtown street and
told authorities that, through his rearview mirror, he saw the woman
hand her bus pass to Hayden, who then tried to use it.
   The driver told Hayden he could not use the pass, an argument
ensued and Plummer ordered Hayden off the bus, police records show.
Hayden was shot once in the back with a handgun as he exited.
   Plummer told police that Hayden punched him in the jaw before he
stepped off the bus.
   Plummer had been assaulted twice on the bus route in the past two
years, once breaking his hand and the other time suffering a black
eye, Dallas Area Rapid Transit spokesman Ron Whittington said.
   DART authorities, meanwhile, have begun proceedings to dismiss
Plummer for violating company policy, which forbids drivers from
carrying firearms. A decision was expected by Friday.
</TEXT>
