<HEAD>Tornado Alert Didn't Stop Parking-Meter Monitors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When sirens sound a tornado warning, people
should take cover. And that's why David Ghilardi says he stayed in
the basement of his downtown office.
   That's also why he plans to fight the $5 parking ticket that was
placed on his wife's car as they took shelter during the two-hour
warning a week ago today.
   ``On one hand we have government officials telling us not to go
out because there's a tornado warning, and on the other hand we have
government officials saying go out and plug meters,'' said Ghilardi,
of Madison.
   During the warning, meter monitors carrying two-way radios were
told of the weather conditions but some without radios cotniued
writing tickets, said Police Capt. Richard Wallden.
   ``It was a problem of them not knowing how dangerous the
situation was,'' Wallden said.
