<DOCNO> AP890621-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-ChildCare-Politics     06-21 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care-Politics,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Failing to Highlight Family Issues, Consultant Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats are failing to capitalize on family
issues such as child care at the polls because they are ``afraid to
take on the tax consequences'' of programs that voters say they
support, a party consultant says.
   But a Republican strategist warned women's groups that even
though child care has emerged as an important campaign issue in
recent years, ``there are a lot of folks who just don't care about
the issue.''
   Celinda Lake, a Democratic expert on electing women candidates,
and Vince Breglio, a former campaign strategist for Senate
Republicans before becoming President Bush's chief pollster for the
1988 campaign, appeared on a panel at a meeting held by child care
advocates Tuesday.
   Panelist Ethel Klein, an associate professor of political science
at Columbia University, said a February poll by Louis Harris &amp;
Associates showed 87 percent approval for a joint government and
private effort to meet child care needs. She said 55 percent of
those responding to a CBS News poll in February said the federal
government had a responsibility to help parents pay for child care
if they couldn't afford it.
   Breglio, however, said the most recent White House polls show
that Bush's child care program, built around a tax credit, has about
5 percent to 6 percent more support than congressional legislation
calling for direct government financing.
   Ms. Lake told the group that family issues ``ought to work very
well for Democrats. They are policy issues where people want
spending and they want it now, not later. They want government
involvement.''
   ``We as Democrats have not drawn strong enough political lines on
this issue,'' the consultant said. ``Democrats have tended to talk
about small cost ... and all this has done is lose the punch of
these issues because we have been afraid to take on the tax
consequences, the regulatory consequences, of these programs, and in
fact voters think these issues are going to take big programs.''
   Breglio said such family issues as child care first surfaced in
political campaigns in 1986.
   ``I had candidates who were beaten on those kinds of issues,'' he
said. ``They were beaten because, with my stupid advice, they talked
about national themes and ideology. Well, national themes and
ideology didn't sell in 1986. Concern over nuclear waste and child
care did. We were wrong, they were right, and we lost many Senate
seats.''
   However, he cautioned the group, ``There are a lot of folks out
there who feel strongly about it, but I must tell you this: there
are a lot of folks who just don't care.''
   Both consultants agreed that family issues will have significant
impact in next year's congressional elections.
   ``I don't believe serious political candidates in 1990 can avoid
discussing the issue of child care,'' Breglio said. ``I don't
believe they can avoid discussing the issue of long-term health
care.'' However, he said he did not believe parental leave would be
an issue.
   Ms. Lake predicted all three would be major issues, particularly
if Congress passes child care and parental leave legislation and
Bush vetoes it on top of his veto of the recent bill raising the
minimum wage.
   Breglio said Bush is ``doing pretty well'' with women voters, but
``If there is a whole series of vetoes on legislation that is of
particular importance to women, that could be a different ballgame.''
   The panel was sponsored by the Child Care Action Campaign, a
coalition seeking a national system of child care combining public
and private resources; the Great American Family Tour, a non-profit,
non-partisan organization dealing with family policy issues, headed
by Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.; and Lifetime Television, a
venture of Hearst@ABC-Viacom Entertainment Services,
which produce a documentary entitled ``Hush Little Baby: The
Challenge of Child Care.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
