<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxPenalties     06-21 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Penalties,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan to Revamp Tax Penalties Aims at Willful Non-payers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill endorsed by the House Ways and Means
Committee tries to draw a distinction between careless taxpayers and
those who are out to beat the system.
   Taxpayers also would face less chance of being penalized two or
more times for the same mistake, under the measure passed by a voice
vote Tuesday.
   The bill would revamp the system of nearly 150 civil tax
penalties that may be imposed by the Internal Revenue Service, and
is intended to be part of the committee's share of deficit reduction
for the budget year that begins Oct. 1.
   Rep. J.J. Pickle, D-Texas, chairman of the committee's oversight
panel and chief author of the overhaul, said public hearings showed
``the current penalty structure is a confusing morass of complex,
overlapping penalties that are often unduly harsh or just plain
irrational.''
   Just 35 years ago, the IRS had only 13 penalties to enforce. The
growth is partly due to Congress' use of penalties to raise revenue,
authorities say.
   In 1988, the IRS assessed 26 million penalties totaling nearly $6
billion.
   The IRS supports overhauling the penalty structure. The rewriting
is based on the notion that penalties should be used only to
encourage compliance, not to raise money.
   An example of the changes: Present law imposes a 5 percent
penalty for underpayment of tax; the bill would raise that generally
to 20 percent.
   Most of the changes involve penalties on banks and other payers
that fail to file reports on interest and dividends paid, and on
employers that miss the deadline for turning over withheld taxes to
the Internal Revenue Service.
   In most cases, the revised penalties would be graduated so that
the longer the delay in paying or filing and the more blatant the
mistake, the higher the penalty.
   For example, the penalty for failing to file an information
return with the IRS _ such as a Form 1099 statement, on which a bank
reports interest paid to a depositor _ now is $50 for each failure
to file. The maximum is $100,000 a year. The bill would vary that
from $15 for a few days' tardiness (a maximum of $75,000 a year) to
$50 per failure, to a maximum of $250,000.
</TEXT>
