<FIRST>r w PM-SandratheDancer 650   06-21 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sandra the Dancer, 650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once Shy, Haitian Student Becomes Presidential Scholar in the Arts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Sandra Dupiton arrived from Haiti five
years ago, she was painfully shy but determined to become a dancer.
This week, she was good enough to perform at the Kennedy Center and
receive a medallion from President Bush at the White House.
   ``I always knew I could dance,'' she says. ``I always believed in
myself that I could do it.''
   Now 18 and shy no longer, Sandra was selected by a White House
commission as one of America's 20 most promising young artists. She
and 140 other high school seniors across the country traveled to
Washington as this year's Presidential Scholars for their academic
and artistic excellence.
   Sandra, who lives with her mother in Brooklyn, N.Y., will be
graduated next Tuesday from Julia Richman High School in Manhattan,
where she took her first dance lessons four years ago in the
school's Talent Unlimited arts program. She will enter Sarah
Lawrence College on a scholarship this fall.
   Greeting the Presidential Scholars on the White House South Lawn,
the president said Tuesday they were ``some of the best and
brightest students in American education,'' and had an obligation to
help others.
   ``While already you've done much, I know you will do more _ and
not for yourselves alone, but for nation and neighbors,'' Bush said.
   ``The definition of a successful life must include serving
others. That goes double for America's best,'' he told them.
   Sandra and her 19 fellow Presidential Scholars in the Arts were
chosen from among 5,200 applicants whose achievements were judged by
the non-profit National Foundation for Advancement in the Arts at
Miami. Finalists were recommended to the White House commission for
final selections.
   The 20 top young artists displayed their talents Monday night on
the stage of the Kennedy Center Concert Hall, one of five days of
activities ending today. Sandra, who specializes in modern dance,
performed a solo she choreographed with her high school teacher,
Paul Thompson.
   In a backstage interview before the show, Thompson said that as a
freshman in his dance class, ``Sandra was so shy she couldn't even
speak her name'' and would turn away and hide her face.
   ``But when she danced her first solo, I saw that she had some
special spirit, this fire, this spark,'' he said. ``I knew it would
come out, so I didn't push her. Although she was very, very shy, she
had this incredible desire to learn and excell.''
   Sandra said dance lessons were too expensive in Haiti, so at age
13 she moved to Brooklyn to live with an aunt and study in New York.
She didn't know a word of English. ``I was feeling like an
outcast,'' she said, blaming her shyness on fear of being ostracized
because of her Creole accent.
   But a few months after she began studying with Thompson, she
said, her fear abruptly vanished in her physical exuberance on the
dance floor.
   ``I suddenly burst out,'' she said. ``My body just let go, and he
told me it was good. Dancing really helped me to open up, and it
became easier to use that freedom to speak.''
   At 15, she won favorable notice in The New York Times for a dance
recital by her high school troupe at a Manhattan theater. She won
scholarships to study at the Joffrey Ballet and the Martha Graham
School of Contemporary Dance. This summer, she studied on
scholarship with the Dance Theater of Harlem.
   Sandra has pursued her dream without apparent support from her
mother, who moved to Brooklyn from Haiti with Sandra's brother and
sister in 1986.
   ``My family has never seen me dance,'' she said. ``My mother
doesn't like it because she says you can't earn a good living at
dancing.''
   But Thompson is convinced that Sandra will prevail because of her
natural talent. ``Her growth in the last four years has been
phenomenal,'' he said.
</TEXT>
