<FIRST>r w PM-Shoreham-Ritter     06-21 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shoreham-Ritter,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Seeks to Block Shoreham Shutdown Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxpayers nationwide will foot the bill if a
New York utility is granted deductions for its losses on the
Shoreham nuclear power plant, a Pennsylvania congressman contends.
   ``Taxpayers from Alaska to Florida will suffer because the
plant's owner has been granted a $2.8 billion tax break,'' Rep. Don
Ritter, R-Pa., said Tuesday in denouncing plans to close the Long
Island reactor.
   Ritter is pushing legislation to block the estimated $2.8 billion
writeoff for the Long Island Lighting Co.
   The Internal Revenue Service in April approved the tax deduction
for losses sustained as a result of scrapping the plant.
   Ritter's measure would change the tax code to bar deductions for
losses on the abandonment of a fully licensed nuclear plant. The
bill was referred to the House Ways and Means Committee, where
senior New York Democratic Reps. Charles Rangel and Thomas Downey
could be expected to block it.
   Brad Johnson, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo's Washington lobbyist,
said Tuesday he takes the challenge seriously but does not think the
bill has much chance of passing.
   ``It would be analogous to a New Yorker introducing legislation
to reopen a plant in California after ratepayers had voted to close
it,'' Johnson added. ``This would be a gross misuse of congressional
power.''
   Under a plan negotiated by Cuomo and LILCO, Shoreham would be
sold to New York state for a symbolic dollar in exchange for a
series of rate hikes. Shoreham's license would be transferred to the
Long Island Power Authority, which would contract with the New York
Power Authority to decommission the $5.5 billion plant.
</TEXT>
