<FIRST>r w PM-TravelerBush     06-21 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Traveler Bush,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Lots of Motion, but Any Progress?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush rattles off his address as
``Pennsylvania Avenue, 1600,'' but don't count on finding him there
if you visit the nation's capital this summer.
   From Memorial Day to Labor Day, Bush will have spent more days
away from the White House than in it.
   If Bush were required to report to Congress on what he did over
the summer, it would fill a substantial volume.
   Between lengthy trips to Europe, Bush has been bounding about the
country, giving a string of often disjointed speeches and conducting
the nation's business on the road.
   Some critics have questioned whether Bush, in his multitudinous
travels, has been logging useful mileage or merely spinning the
adminstration's wheels.
   In the three weeks since he returned from a four-nation, weeklong
trip to Europe centered on a NATO meeting in Brussels, Bush:
   _Made a 4,000-mile, 30-hour round trip to Yellowstone National
Park, Wyoming's Grand Tetons, and Lincoln, Neb., nominally to tout
his environmental programs. However, Bush's late-day visit to
Yellowstone consisted of a tour of an area damaged by last year's
forest fires, and was unrelated to the chief topic of the day _ the
White House's new clean-air legislation.
   _Visited a federal law enforcement training center at Glynco,
Ga., to talk about his anti-crime package. The speech spotlighted a
plan whose details had been announced several weeks before.
   _Flew by helicopter to the Philadelphia suburbs, where he gave a
high school graduation speech and shook hands with all 331 graduates.
   In addition, Bush planned to travel today to Richmond, Va., where
he was to speak at a motor coach exhibit at the Virginia State
Fairgrounds and attend a Republican fund-raiser.
   On Thursday, he travels to New York, both for a fund-raiser and
to unveil details of a youth service program.
   He caps next week with a visit to his family home in
Kennebunkport for a five-day Fourth of July holiday, then goes to
Europe for the seven-nation economic summit and side visits to
Poland, Hungary and the Netherlands.
   In August, he plans a 2{-week vacation in Kennebunkport. And he's
been spending most weeekends not otherwise accounted for at the
presidential retreat in Camp David, Md.
   Bush has been doing some business as he moves around the country.
   He vetoed the minium wage bill aboard Air Force One as he
traveled from Montana to Nebraska last week; in Georgia, he signed a
routine message formally transmitting his crime package to Congress.
   ``Usually, this would entail nothing more than a quick flourish
of the pen and then sending an aide on a 10-minute car ride up from
Pennsylvania Avenue, 1600, on up to Capitol Hill,'' he told his
law-enforcement audience.
   ``But when it comes to fighting crime, you deserve more than just
business as usual.''
   However, even in talking about crime _ a favored subject _ Bush
seemed to be sending a mixed message.
   After a tough speech in which Bush declared, ``let's put the
handcuffs on the criminals, not on the criminal justice system,'' he
was asked by a Border Patrol rookie for ``some words of wisdom when
we enter the field.''
   Bush: ``You'll find that you and your colleagues will be severely
impacted by the battle against narcotics. Word of wisdom would be:
an individual should be treated with respect and given his rights,
or her rights, even though the evidence looks overwhelming. ... I
think we have to be tolerant.''
   The press contingent following Bush as he hops from city to city
has grown increasingly more sparse.
   For the trip to Philadelphia, the White House canceled travel
arrangements for the regular White House press corps, beyond taking
a small ``pool.'' It cited lack of interest among news organizations.
   ``I'm not going to be a policeman or try to guide your coverage
habits. It's as simple as that,'' fumed presidential press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
