<FIRST>r w PM-StrikeForce     06-21 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Strike Force,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Plan Would Wreck Crime-Fighting Team, Former Leaders Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's plan to
place the nation's elite corps of organized crime-fighting
prosecutors under control of U.S. attorneys is coming under fire
from former leaders of the unit.
   ``It's impractical, it just won't work,'' Philadelphia attorney
Peter F. Vaira said Tuesday at a hearing of the House subcommittee
on criminal justice.
   Under Thornburgh's plan, prosecutors who are members of the
20-year-old Organized Crime Strike Force would no longer report to
the Justice Department's criminal division. Instead, they would be
controlled by the politically appointed U.S. attorneys in the cities
were they are based.
   Thornburgh says the idea would end turf battles between the
strike force and the U.S. attorneys. His critics say the elite
force, which has chalked up impressive victories in the war against
the mob, would soon vanish.
   ``I guarantee you three years from now it will take the FBI to
find the strike forces,'' said Vaira, a former strike force chief in
Chicago and Phildelphia who also was U.S. attorney in Philadelphia
and briefly headed the President's Commission on Organized Crime.
   Edward A. McDonald, former head of the strike force in Brooklyn,
was sharply critical of what Thornburgh and his aides ``call
euphemistically the merger of the strike force. I like to call it
the destruction or the abolition of the strike force.''
   The plan already has sent strike force attorneys in New York
hunting for new jobs, he said, adding that the departure of highly
experienced prosecutors is likely to grow worse.
   Lawmakers are considering a move to bar Thornburgh from
implementing the plan until Oct. 1 as part of a stopgap spending
bill likely to go to President Bush and gain his signature. But the
move could go forward after that.
   Former New England strike force chief Jeremiah T. O'Sullivan
testified that strike force attorneys often are paid $7,000 to
$10,000 less than U.S. attorneys, even though they usually have more
experience.
   Because of salary adjustments, Thornburgh's plan would cost
$100,000 in each city where the strike force is located, O'Sullivan
testified.
   ``You'd be looking at an increase of $1 million right off the
bat'' nationwide, he said.
   ``After all these victories, I think it is fair to ask: What is
broke that needs fixing?'' said subcommittee Chairman Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y. He said, however, that he would keep an open mind on
the issue.
   Edward S.G. Dennis, head of the criminal division of the Justice
Department, told the panel that Thornburgh's ``concern for the fight
against organized crime is second to none.''
   Thornburgh ``feels strongly enough about this proposal that he is
willing to take the heat and the controversy that this proposal
stimulates,'' Dennis said. He said the idea of merging the strike
forces in each city with the U.S. attorney's office was one that
would promote ``even more harmony'' between the two groups of
prosecutors and end ``turf fights.''
   Dennis took issue with claims that the plan would mean the end of
the strike force, saying its members would not be reassigned to work
on cases not involving organized crime.
   He said turf fighting between strike force attorneys and the U.S.
attorneys offices has at times cut into time that should be spent on
fighting mobsters.
   ``The question is, are we going to spend 30 percent of our time
arguing whose case this is, or are we going to make the case?''
Dennis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
