<FIRST>r w PM-TamponLabeling     06-21 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tampon Labeling,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tampon-Labeling Proposal too Confusing, Says Consumer Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government proposal aimed at helping women
minimize the risk of toxic shock syndrome is too confusing, a
consumer group says, because it would allow tampon boxes to show two
types of absorbency ratings.
   The Food and Drug Administration's revised plan would require
manufacturers to display one of six new standardized absorbency
rating terms ranging from low to high. However, they also could
continue using traditional designations like regular and super.
   ``This whole range system isn't as informative and clear as it
could be,'' said Patti Goldman of the Public Citizen Health Research
Group.
   The proposal is an improvement over FDA's earlier plan to use an
absorbency scale of letters from A to F, ``but there's still
potential for confusion to have the old terms appear nearby,'' she
said.
   The FDA said Tuesday it revised its earlier proposal in response
to about 275 comments from consumers, consumer groups and
manufacturers, many of whom complained that it was too confusing.
   The labeling is designed to help women select the lowest
absorbency tampon they need to reduce the risk of toxic shock
syndrome, which has been associated with tampon use. Toxic shock
syndrome is rare, but sometimes fatal.
   Under the new plan, tampon absorbency would be rated as low,
medium, medium-high, high, very high and highest _ according to the
number of grams the tampon was designed to absorb.
   Tampon boxes also would have to carry labels advising women to
select the lowest absorbency needed to minimize risk of toxic shock
syndrome. Regulations have required this warning since 1982 but
allow it to appear on a package insert.
   Package inserts also must list toxic shock syndrome's symptoms:
sudden fever, vomiting, diarrhea, fainting or nearly fainting when
standing up, dizziness and a sunburn-like rash.
   The FDA has been trying since 1981 to convince manufacturers to
voluntarily label their products with a standardized absorbency
rating so women could compare brand-to-brand. The agency gave up
that route in 1984 and began regulatory efforts.
   The FDA invited public comments on the new proposal until Aug. 11.
</TEXT>
