<FIRST>r w PM-US-ChineseArt     06-21 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Chinese Art,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amid Strained Relations, Chinese Art Exhibition On Schedule</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese government-sponsored art show was
launched for year-long showings in the United States on schedule and
without incident _ but also without official Chinese representation.
   Wang Yani, a 14-year-old prodigy who has made 10,000
brush-and-ink paintings since she was 3 years old, was the
undisputed star at the preview of her exhibition of 69 colorful
pictures.
   In a demonstration lasting barely an hour, she created a 70th
painting, dashing barefoot, brush in hand, from end to end of a 3-by
6-foot parchment laid on a floor.
   Her works show monkeys, birds and other beasts displaying human
emotions and expressions while cavorting through exquisitely drawn
foliage and mountains of Yani's rugged native Guangxi province, in
South China, far from the turmoil of Beijing and Shanghai.
   China's Ministry of Culture is listed as sponsor of the
exhibition but no one from the Chinese Embassy appeared at Tuesday's
event, ``maybe because they were too busy,'' said Milo Beach,
director of the Smithsonian Insitution's Sackler Gallery for Asian
art.
   At the very hour of the preview, Congress members critical of
China's violent crackdown against the pro-democracy movement rallied
at the nearby U.S. Capitol grounds, then went to the Chinese Embassy
to protest killings, violence and arrests in what they described as
a confrontational meeting with Ambassador Han Xu.
   The day after demonstrators were shot down in Beijing's Tiananmen
Square, the U.S. National Academy of Sciences suspended official
scientific exchanges with the Chinese Academy in protest. But no
moves have been reported to suspend cultural exchanges.
   Wang Yani's works have been shown in Japan and Europe and the
U.S. exhibition was first proposed four years ago, said Marc Wilson,
director of the Nelson-Atkins Museum in Kansas City, Mo., which took
the lead in organizing it. It is scheduled to move there Dec. 16 and
on to San Francisco's Asian Art Museum next March.
   Pictures for the exhibit were sent here months ago and there was
no thought of changing plans, only hope that Yani would appear,
Sackler officials said. She flew here with her father via Beijing
last weekend and plans to return next week, said Susan Bliss,
spokeswoman for the U.S. government-supported gallery. ``We see this
is a cultural event, and apparently not a problem,'' she said.
   The exhibition's official catalog, however, treats Yani as a
symbol of the liberalization in China that is now under threat. It
says the Cultural Revolution during the last decade of Mao Zedong's
rule ``ruthlessly suppressed many of China's greatest artists and
artistic traditions in the name of revolutionary culture.''
   ``Public recognition and appreciation of Wang Yani's remarkable
talent may only have been possible because of the gradual loosening
of government controls over art that followed Mao's death,'' it
adds. ``The paintings of a child who knew nothing of politics
offered a fresh vision that many artists sought in their own work.''
   This is reflected in the title of the exhibition, ``Yani: the
Brush of Innocence.''
</TEXT>
