<FIRST>r w PM-VirginIslandsProject     06-21 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Virgin Islands Project,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC-Virgin Islands Project Violated City Law, Draft Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A District of Columbia government office
violated city purchasing laws in a joint personnel project with the
Virgin Islands government, according to a draft report on a probe
into the project.
   The Washington Post reported today the preliminary report showed
that the Office of Personnel project cost the city at least
$258,645, or nearly twice as much as the $144,786 in reimbursement
now being sought by the city.
   ``It appears to the committee that this project was a rogue
operation that operated outside the normal lines of authority and
outside the safeguards'' for the expenditure of public funds, said
the draft report on the District Council's investigation.
   A federal grand jury is investigating the project in which the
district helped revamp the island government's personnel system and
draft new laws.
   Virgin Islands Gov. Alexander A. Farrelly and District Mayor
Marion Barry conceived the project which was jointly supervised by
former district Personnel Director Theodore E. Thornton Sr. and
Charles Lewis, a former aide to Farrelly. Lewis later was convicted
on drug charges in the Virgin Islands.
   Inspector James Richard of the U.S. Interior Deparment has said
some D.C. officials used the project as an excuse to party in St.
Thomas at public expense.
   The draft report said Thornton failed to get a written agreement
from the Virgin Islands government covering the project's
activities, and that costs were allowed to escalate despite
indications of ``serious administrative and financial problems.''
   The report cited testimony by Oscar Mays, chief of budget and
financial management for the Office of Personnel, that he was
ordered by a superior to ignore purchasing requirements in hiring
two consultants.
</TEXT>
