<FIRST>r w PM-GreggNomination     06-21 1011</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gregg Nomination,1040</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gregg Nomination Forwarded to Full Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle over President Bush's choice of
Donald P. Gregg as ambassador to South Korea moves to the full
Senate after a favorable committee vote reflecting sharp
disagreement on whether he lied about playing a role in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Gregg has repeatedly denied under oath that he was involved in
Oliver North's secret operation to resupply the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels while serving as national security adviser to then-Vice
President George Bush.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who spearheaded the lengthy probe
by the Foreign Relations Committee's Democratic majority into
Gregg's alleged links to the operation, said he had not decided how
hard to press the matter on the Senate floor.
   But Gregg's nomination appeared to have been given a solid boost
by the decision of three committee Democrats to join nine
Republicans in recommending approval. The committee voted 12-7 on
Tuesday to send the nomination to the Senate floor.
   The Senate is not likely to act before it returns from its
Independence Day recess on July 10.
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who at one point organized a GOP
boycott of a panel meeting in order to force action on Gregg's
nomination, called the panel's decision ``a very big victory,''
particularly because of Cranston's ``very large expenditure of
energy and political capital.''
   ``Picking up three Democrats is very helpful'' in assuring
Gregg's eventual confirmation,'' McConnell said.
   Earlier McConnell told the committee: ``The president of the
United States is loyal, but he is not foolish. If he had determined
that Gregg was not truthful he would not have submitted this
nomination.''
   Democrats voting to recommend confirmation of Gregg were Chairman
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I. and Sens. Charles Robb of Virginia and Terry
Sanford of North Carolina.
   In explaining his vote, Pell said he ``concluded that Mr. Gregg
and the president should be given the benefit of the doubt'' despite
the ``excellent arguments'' made by Cranston.
   Robb said he closely examined the evidence and found Gregg's
explanations to be ``as reasonable and believable as I think we
could expect under the circumstances.''
   Gregg is a retired career veteran of the Central Intelligence
Committee who served as CIA station chief in Seoul. Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., said he voted against the nomination not because he believed
Gregg lacked credibility but because he is concerned that his CIA
background will make him a political target in South Korea.
   Addressing the committee moments before the vote, Cranston said
the nomination should be rejected ``on the grounds of both
credibility and judgment.''
   ``We are being asked to reward a man many of us do not believe
has been straight with us while under oath,'' Cranston said. ``We
are being asked to promote a man to a crucial diplomatic post whose
judgment _ by his own admission _ has been so flawed that he twice
offered to resign from then-Vice President Bush's staff.''
   Cranston denied he was making a purely partisan effort to harm
Bush as McConnell and some other Republicans have charged.
   He said he remains highly skeptical that Gregg was never told by
his close friend and former CIA colleague Felix Rodriguez that
Rodriguez was recruited by North to help resupply the Contras with
military aid at a time when Congress had forbidden such activities.
   During two separate appearances before the committee, both times
under oath, Gregg said he was unaware that Rodriguez was doing
anything more than helping the government of El Salvador put down
the left-wing insurgency against it, the mission for which he was
sent to Central America.
   Cranston made clear he does not believe Gregg's story that
although Rodriguez told him some of the details of the Contra
resupply mission in August 1986, he did not put the pieces together
until the following December.
   ``Our hearings revealed documents making clear that Rodriguez and
North were working together in an illegal Contra resupply scheme
months earlier, from January 1985 _ the same week Gregg introduced
Rodriguez to Bush,'' Cranston said.
   ``I recognize how difficult it is for some senators to state the
conclusion most of us share: Mr. Gregg has not been straight with
us,'' Cranston said. ``The implications for Mr. Gregg _ and for the
president _ are not pleasant.''
   The panel also postponed action on three other nominations after
Democrats complained that the nominees' only visible qualifications
were large GOP contributions.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., initiated the delay when he complained
that U.S. ambassadors should have at least some qualifications.
   The three include:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Joseph Zappala, a Florida land developer and national
co-chairman of Bush's fund raising committee who has been nominated
to be U.S. ambassador to Spain. Sarbanes said he contributed
$126,000 to the Bush campaign.
   _Marvin Sembler, a Florida shopping center tycoon who has been
named to be ambassador to Australia. Sarbanes said Sembler was a
$127,000 Bush contributor.
   _Della Newman, a Seattle, Wash., residential real estate broker
who has been nominated to be ambassador to New Zealand. She is a
long-time personal friend of Bush and was chairman of the Washington
State Bush For President Committee. Sarbanes said she had no
apparent qualifications except her personal and political ties.
   The panel, and the full Senate, did approve the nomination of C.
Howard Wilkins Jr., a $115,000 contributor to the Bush campaign, to
be ambassador to the Netherlands.
   The panel also confirmed a list of other nominees, including:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Thomas Niles, U.S. representative to the European Community.
   _Morton I. Abramowitz, to be ambassador to Turkey.
   _Edward N. Ney, to be ambassador to Canada.
   _Richard H. Solomon, to be assistant secretary of state for East
Asian and Pacific Affairs.
   _Melvyn Levitsky, to be assistant secretary of state for
international narcotics matters.
   _Jewel S. Lafontant, to be ambassador-at-large for refugee
affairs.
   _E. Patrick Coady, to be U.S. executive director for the
International Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
   _Mark L. Edelman, to be deputy administrator of the Agency for
International Development.
   _Fred M. Zeder II, to be president of the Overseas Private
Investment Corp.
</TEXT>
