<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Slaying     06-21 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Slaying,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Triggerman in Mexican Journalist's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police have arrested a former national
security agent and onetime movie actor on suspicion he was the
triggerman in the 1984 murder of leading newspaper columnist Manuel
Buendia, authorities said.
   The Mexico City Attorney General's Office identified the suspect
as Juan Rafael Mora Avila, 36, a member of a prominent family of
politicians from the neighboring state of Puebla.
   Jose Antonio Zorrilla Perez, former director of a now-dissolved
equivalent of the FBI, was arrested June 13 in Mexico City for
allegedly masterminding the murder and is awaiting trial on charges
of homicide.
   Buendia, whose front-page column in the newspaper Excelsior
exposed wrongdoing in high places, was shot to death on May 30,
1984, at the entrance of a parking garage after leaving his office.
   The Attorney General's Office says it has evidence Zorrilla, 47,
ordered the killing of Buendia, whom he had known for 15 years, when
he learned the columnist planned to expose his links to prominent
drug traffickers.
   The office said Mora was arrested Tuesday and booked ``on
suspicion of being one of the material authors'' in the slaying of
Buendia. A police source, who insisted on anonymity, said
authorities had evidence indicating Mora was the ``triggerman.''
   Under Mexican law, Mora must be arraigned within 24 hours or the
case will be thrown out for lack of evidence.
   The attorney general's office said Mora, when questioned by a
city prosecutor, denied he had anything to do with the shooting,
saying: ``When I arrived he (Buendia) was already dead.''
   The government news agency Notimex identified Mora as the
grandson of former Puebla Gov. Maximino Avila Camacho, a onetime
Secretary of Communications and Transportation.
   Notimex said Mora was also a grandnephew of Manuel Avila Camacho,
who was president of Mexico from 1940 to 1946.
   A 1973 graduate from the Judiciary Police Technical School, Mora
worked for various law enforcement agencies before joinging the
Federal Security Administration in 1982 as a member of an ``elite''
group of 20 special agents, the Attorney General's office said in
its statement.
   Mora had been a member of a rock group and played bit parts as an
actor in at least four horror and crime movies. He is still a member
ANDA, the National Actors' Association.
   Zorrilla was director of the Federal Security Administration from
1982 until the government dissolved it in 1985 because of widespread
corruption.
   The Attorney General's office said in a statement Tuesday that it
had evidence that Zorrilla received millions of dollars a month in
bribes from drug baron Rafael Caro Quintero to allow the smuggling
of large quantities of cocaine from Colombia through Mexico to the
United States.
   Caro Quintero is awaiting trial for the 1985 torture-slaying of
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent Enrique Camarena Salazar
and his Mexican pilot Miguel Zavala Avelar in Guadalajara.
   The attorney general's office said Zorrilla also had links to
Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo, reputedly the country's top drug
trafficker, who was arrested earlier this year.
   Zorrilla, who was first on the scene minutes after Buendia was
shot, conducted the preliminary investigation in the case. He has
also been indicted on charges of obstructing justice and abuse of
authority.
</TEXT>
