<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Time-Warner     06-21 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Lawyers Say Time Buyout Violates FCC Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications says Paramount's
multibillion-dollar attempt to buy Time Inc. violates the 1984 Cable
Act and Federal Communications Commission rules.
   But lawyers for Paramount Communications, which launched a $10.7
billion hostile tender offer for Time after Time announced a
proposed $18 billion merger with Warner, told the FCC on Tuesday it
should set aside its previous ruling allowing Time to transfer
control of its cable TV systems to Time-Warner.
   Paramount said Time had misrepresented to its stockholders the
nature of the transfer and that Time had written to state attorneys
general asking them to oppose Paramount's proposal without notifying
Paramount of the letters.
   These actions raise ``questions about Time's character
qualifications,'' Paramount said, asking the FCC to set aside its
approval of the license transfers pending an investigation.
   The filings were the latest round of high-stakes corporate
manuevering in which the three parties are trying to create the
world's largest entertainment and media conglomerate.
   After the Time-Warner merger was announced in March, Paramount
weighed in with its hostile takeover offer. But Time fired back
Friday with a $12.6 billion offer to buy Warner.
   Besides the tussle over transfer of cable licenses, the battle is
expected to be waged in court in Delaware, where all three companies
are incorporated.
   Paramount earlier this month asked the FCC for permission to give
control of Time to former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld pending
FCC approval of the transfer of 99 cable television franchises and
licenses held by Time's 82-percent-owned subsidiary, American
Television and Communications Corp.
   Art Harding, a lawyer for Warner, said Tuesday that Paramount's
request ``would violate the recent Cable Act because Rumsfeld hasn't
gotten consent from any of these cities for the transfers.''
   Harding, echoing assertions Time made against Paramount in a June
13 FCC filing, said Paramount's plan would ``undermine the delicate
balance'' established in the 1984 Cable Act for regulation of cable
systems by local authorities.
   Warner asked the FCC late Monday to deny the application made by
Paramount and its subsidiary, KDS Acquisition Corp., for expedited
consent to transfer control of Time to Rumsfeld and then to
Paramount.
   Warner said Paramount's plan called for an ``unprecedented
extension'' to the cable TV industry of FCC rules that cover hostile
tender offers for broadcast licenses. It said the FCC can allow
transfer of a broadcaster even before it decides the receiving party
is qualified to hold broadcast licenses, but cable franchises must
be transferred by local authorities and the FCC has no say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
