<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-21 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Up As Dollar Continues to Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange made up
earlier losses to close higher today while the U.S. dollar surged
against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 111.81
points, or 0.34 percent, finishing at 33,345.28 after reversing a
downward trend earlier in the day. It was a 220.29-point winner
Tuesday.
   The dollar ended trading at 144.95 yen, up 1.15 yen from
Tuesday's close of 143.80 yen. It opened at 144.85 yen and traded
between 144.73 yen and 144.03 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's strength was based on overnight gains
in overseas markets.
   ``Investors still want to invest in dollar assets, but the
dollar's value fell so suddenly last week that they are not buying
aggressively,'' said a dealer at a major Japanese city bank, who
spoke anonymously.
   The U.S. dollar fluctuated wildly last week, closing at 151.30
yen last Thursday and then plummeting 6.25 yen on Friday to close at
145.05 yen.
   On the stock exchange, brokers said the index began to rise when
trust investment companies conducted arbitrage deals between the
spot and the futures markets. Bargain hunting in the first section
also pushed prices higher, they said.
