<FIRST>r a PM-MississippiExecution     06-21 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mississippi Execution,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Triple Murderer Executed in Mississippi Gas Chamber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARCHMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black man who insisted he was unjustly
convicted by an all-white jury was executed in the gas chamber early
today for a five-day robbery spree in which three people were slain.
   Leo Edwards Jr., 36, of New Orleans, appeared to gasp for breath
and shrug his shoulders several times as the cyanide gas swirled
around him.
   He was declared dead at 12:15 a.m., minutes after being strapped
into a chair in the gas chamber.
   Edwards was the fourth person executed at the state penitentiary
at Parchman and the 113th in the nation since the U.S. Supreme Court
reinstated the death penalty in 1976.
   Edwards was executed for the June 14, 1980, shooting death of
Jackson convenience store clerk Linzy Don Dixon. The robbery netted
$111 and came during a spree in Hinds and Madison counties in which
two other people were killed and two were wounded.
   Also participating in the spree was Mike White, who escaped with
Edwards from the Louisiana State Penitentiary at Angola.
   White is serving two life terms after pleading guilty to murder
in the death of Dixon and a bar owner.
   Defense attorneys protested that prosecutors deliberately
excluded blacks from the jury, denying Edwards a fair trial.
   On Tuesday, the U.S. Supreme Court voted 7-2 against a stay, and
Gov. Ray Mabus rejected Edwards' plea for clemency.
   ``I will not stand in the way of the courts' justice. ... Leo
Edwards is a mass murderer who killed in cold blood,'' Mabus said.
``He tried and failed to get relief in 16 appeals to the courts, and
discrimination had no bearing in his case. ...
   ``Leo Edwards' sentence is a result of his own crime, and his
fate now rests in God's hands,'' the governor said.
   But in a newspaper interview published Tuesday, Edwards
maintained his innocence and insisted he did not receive a fair
trial, even though four different appeals courts rejected arguments
that prosecutors deliberately excluded blacks from the jury.
   ``You know how I felt when I saw (the all-white) jury?'' Edwards
was quoted as saying. ``I said, `I'm dead.'''
</TEXT>
