<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SkinDonor     06-21 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skin Donor,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dieter Sheds 173 Pounds, Donates Excess Skin to Burn Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-month-old boy with severe burns was the first
beneficiary of Dennis Genz's decision to donate 4 square feet of his
excess skin to a hospital burn unit.
   Genz' diet recently allowed him to shed 170 pounds, but left him
with a large flap of skin on his abdomen, which was removed
surgically Monday.
   ``There have been rare cases where parents have donated skin for
their children,'' Betty Perls, education director for the Regional
Organ Bank of Illinois, said Tuesday. ``But none of us have ever
heard of a case like this.''
   The 5-foot-11 Genz weighed 430 pounds last August when he began a
high-protein weight-loss regimen. Last week, he weighed in at 260.
   He said the operation removed 19{ pounds of skin and adjoining
tissue.
   Some of the skin went to Dexter Moore, a 3-month-old victim of a
fire in Indiana.
   When the infant was admitted, he was suffering from smoke
inhalation and burns to his face, head and arms. It was a
life-threatening situation, said John Easton, spokesman at the
University of Chicago Medical Center.
   Now, said Easton, ``he's doing well.''
   More lives are saved by skin transplants than any other donated
organ, said Dr. Lawrence Gottlieb, professor of surgery and director
of the hospital's burn unit.
   Most donated skin comes from cadavers, Ms. Perls said.
   Donated skin ``is used as a kind of living bandage'' while the
patient regenerates his own skin, Ms. Perls said. Then the borrowed
tissue is shed.
   Because its use is temporary, skin used for burn patients need
not be a perfect match like that used for skin grafts or other organ
transplants, Ms. Perls said.
   Genz, a 43-year-old equipment coordinator for the emergency
department at Sherman Hospital in Elgin, said the idea for donating
the skin came while he was eating lunch with some nurses.
   ``We were joking that it was too bad I couldn't donate the
skin,'' he said.
   ``Then one of the nurses said, `Why not?''' he recalled Tuesday
from his hospital bed, where he was recovering from Monday's surgery.
   The decision ``left me with a good feeling,'' Genz said, adding
he was feeling fine despite ``kind of a big scar.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
