<FIRST>r w PM-Solstice     06-21 0099</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solstice,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Year's Longest Day in North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Today was the summer solstice, the longest day
of the year.
   The solstice occurred at 5:53 a.m. EDT, the moment during the
summer when the sun is farthest from the equator in the Northern
Hemisphere.
   The date has popularly been listed by calendar makers as the
official start of summer, although that title carries no official
weight. For example, meteorologists consider that summer began June
1.
   The summer solstice has also traditionally been known in folklore
as midsummer and has been a time for parties and other celebrations.
</TEXT>
