<FIRST>u i PM-Burma-Arrest 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma-Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0493,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Burmese Opposition Leader Arrested, Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with leader's release, details.
Picks up 6th pvs, `In recent ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities detained Burma's main
opposition leader, Aung San Suu Kyi, while she was laying wreaths
today to honor demonstrators killed a year ago by the military,
official sources said.
   She and the 15 followers rounded up with her were released after
an hour-long interrogation, said the sources, who asked for
anonymity.
   Witnesses said Aung San Suu Kyi and the others were taken away in
open military trucks to a government office near where the ceremony
took place.
   No official statement has been made about the incident at
Myeinigon, four miles north of downtown Rangoon.
   Aung San Suu Kyi, the daughter of deceased national hero Gen.
Aung San, held a religious ceremony with her followers at a branch
office of her National League for Democracy and then walked to the
spot where several demonstrators were shot by police last June 21.
   Several hundred people were present at the wreath-laying when
authorities moved in.
   In recent months, Aung San Suu Kyi has been harassed on occasion
but generally been given considerable leeway by the military
government to campaign throughout the country.
   Aung San Suu Kyi, a charismatic, 44-year-old political neophyte,
is widely regarded as the most powerful opposition figure in Burma
and her party appears to have the biggest backing among the 200-odd
parties that have mushroomed.
   She returned to Rangoon from London, her home for many years, to
look after her ailing mother in April 1988, and became embroiled in
the political turmoil sweeping Burma.
   She became one of the main leaders of a pro-democracy uprising
that seemed on the verge of toppling 26 years of authoritarian rule
through massive street demonstrations.
   But last September, Gen. Saw Maung and a group of military
officers brutally crushed the student-led protests and clamped
martial law on the country.
   The new leaders allowed the formation of opposition political
parties and have promised free general elections next year. But
opponents like Aung San Suu Kyi have remained skeptical about the
balloting.
   Aung San Suu Kyi joined with two popular leaders, retired Brig.
Gen. Aung Gyi and onetime Defense Minister Tin Oo to form the league
of which she is general secretary and Tin Oo president. Aung Gyi
later left the group, claiming the league was being infiltrated by
communists.
</TEXT>
