<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-US     06-21 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-US,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Superpowers Beginning to Act Like Partners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the
chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff today that his visit was
evidence the superpowers are viewing each other more as partners
than adversaries.
   Gorbachev met Adm. William J. Crowe in a Kremlin office on the
last day of a 10-day visit in which Crowe viewed military exercises
in Byelorussia, looked at a Soviet nuclear submarine and traveled
widely in the Soviet Union.
   ``The very fact that you have visited the Soviet Union and have
visited military facilities and units demonstrates that we are
moving from the notion of enemies to the notion of partners,''
Gorbachev told Crowe in the presence of a handful of reporters.
   ``I believe that in the plans made by the Joint Chiefs of Staff
we are still considered to be adversaries, but the process is going
along new lines, and this is extremely significant,'' the president
said.
   Crowe, accompanied by U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock, then met with
Gorbachev, his military adviser Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev and
military Chief of Staff Mikhail A. Moiseyev for about an hour.
   ``Obviously there still are differences in our points of view,''
especially on arms control, Crowe said at a news conference later.
But he added, ``The atmosphere for discussing them has improved
markedly.
   ``I believe we now have an environment in which we can talk
candidly, ask the kinds of questions that are important, we can talk
without rancor or emotion,'' he said.
   Crowe's visit followed a trip by Akhromeyev to the United States.
He is to leave Moscow early Thursday.
   The visit came as the United States and Soviet Union resumed
talks in Geneva on reducing their arsenals of strategic nuclear
missiles, negotiations that were stalled by disagreements and the
change of U.S. administrations.
   The two sides also are engaged in negotiations on short-range
nuclear weapons, chemical weapons and conventional forces in Europe.
   Crowe spent much of his visit assessing changes in Soviet
military policy under Gorbachev. The policy is based on the concept
of ``reasonable sufficiency,'' that the country only needs enough
soldiers and military hardware to defend itself.
   Gorbachev has said the nation needs to redirect resources from
the military to satisfy pent-up domestic demand for food and
consumer goods.
   Crowe told a Moscow military academy last week that the Soviet
Union still has ``overwhelming numbers'' and that he assumes it
might attack.
   But he also said the Soviet Union must be given time to make good
on promises to cut the size of its armed forces by 500,000 soldiers,
take 500 nuclear weapons out of Eastern Europe and withdraw tanks
and artillery.
   ``There is change afoot in this country, politically and
militarily,'' Crow said today, adding that he found Gorbachev ``very
impressive.''
   Crowe said Gorbachev's plan to withdraw 500 tactical nuclear
weapons from Eastern Europe and President Bush's proposals on
reducing conventional forces made him optimistic about superpower
arms talks.
   ``We now believe there are some positive offers, some
constructive offers on the table, that both sides are serious and
sincere and that we can now continue the process of negotiations and
some optimism,'' Crowe said.
   But he said that it is dangerous for arms control negotiators to
be rushed by a desire on both sides for disarmament.
</TEXT>
