<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HarassedVeteran     06-21 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harassed Veteran,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Miller Brewing Employee Wins Worker's Comp Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brewery employees drove a jittery Vietnam
veteran over the edge by making sudden loud noises so they could
watch him throw himself to the floor, a panel ruled in awarding him
$86,000 in worker's compensation.
   ``This is a case where the human insensitivity often witnessed in
the children's schoolyard has reappeared in the adult workplace,''
two administrative law judges wrote in a decision in favor of John
E. Beverly, 42, of Waterloo.
   ``Such callous behavior is not merely reprehensible, but a
disgrace.''
   Co-workers at Miller Brewing Co. learned he had been diagnosed as
suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, including an
exaggerated startle reaction, and ``preyed upon this startle
reaction apparently for amusement or perhaps outright cruelty,''
said Judges Randall R. Kaiser and Nancy L. Schneiders.
   From 1981 to 1983, co-workers dropped tables, broke beer bottles,
dropped heavy equipment from forklifts, popped empty milk cartons
and paper cups and set off fireworks.
   Beverly responded with a flash of fear and an increased heart
rate and jumped or threw himself to the floor.
   A rocket set off in the lunchroom in Beverly's direction so
unnerved him that he was hospitalized for seven months for
psychiatric treatment, the judges said last week.
   Beverly, who left his job as a production worker in 1983 and
never returned, suffers chronic anxiety, distrust of other people,
depression, anxiety attacks and nightmares, the judges found.
   Miller and its insurance companies said the harassment or
horseplay was not directed at Beverly, or if it was, it was not
unusual stress. They also said his post-traumatic stress disorder
resulted from combat, not what occurred at work.
   But the judges ruled that ``the campaign of terror and
harassment'' was out-of-the-ordinary stress and noted that six
psychiatrists and six psychologist found that Beverly's current
problems resulted from harassment.
   His lawyer, Arthur Heitzer, said Tuesday that Beverly had not
worked since leaving Miller.
   The brewer and its insurers have three weeks to appeal.
   Miller spokesman Peter Acly said the company was reviewing the
decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
