<DOCNO> AP890621-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Submarines 1stLd-Writethru a0446 06-21 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Submarines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Rejects Move to Kill Trident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs penultimate graf, Earlier the subcommittee, to restore
first reference to Rowland.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee says the Pentagon should
be allowed to keep the Trident submarine in its 1990 budget, but it
wants a study on whether the one-a-year purchases are necessary.
   The House Armed Services seapower subcommittee on Tuesday
rejected 8-3 a plan by Rep. Herbert H. Bateman, R-Va., to replace
the $1.28 billion Trident with a smaller Los Angeles-class attack
submarine.
   The attack subs are made by both the Newport News Shipbuilding
Co. in Virginia and the Electric Boat Division of General Dynamics
Corp. in Connecticut. The Trident is made exclusively by Electric
Boat.
   The Reagan administration budget had called for a Trident and two
attack subs, but Defense Secretary Dick Cheney scratched one attack
submarine from his revised budget in a cost-cutting move.
   Earlier this year, Rep. Thomas Foglietta, D-Pa., and Rep. Les
Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee,
called for scaling back the yearly purchases of Tridents in light of
U.S.-Soviet arms control advances.
   The subcommittee, in a closed session, voted 7-4 to reject a
Foglietta amendment to eliminate $140.6 million requested by Cheney
for a Trident in 1992.
   Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla., chairman of the subcommittee,
voted against elimination of Trident funding, but pushed through an
amendment requiring the Navy to study whether one Trident a year is
necessary, said Perry Pockros, an aide to Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn.
   Earlier, the subcommittee rejected 7-6 an amendment to eliminate
a guided missile destroyer requested by Cheney and use the money for
an attack sub, according to David Boomer, an aide to Rep. John
Rowland, R-Conn.
   The Bush administration budget calls for five destroyers and a
single attack sub. This is the last year of the attack subs, which
will be replaced by a new design in future budgets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
