<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0502,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Raid Palestinian Targets; 8 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with casualties, Israel saying Jibril
target of attack. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAAMEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today bombed the
headquarters of a Palestinian guerrilla faction in the hills south
of Beirut, and officials said at least eight guerrillas were wounded.
   The Israeli army said its air force jets attacked targets that
serve as the base for Ahmed Jibril, head of the pro-Syrian Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   A spokesman for the Lebanese Civil Defense said rescuers
evacuated eight wounded guerrillas from the targeted site _ wooded
hills of Naameh overlooking the Mediterranean. The spokesman refused
to say which faction the guerrillas belonged to.
   ``All planes returned safely, and the targets were damaged,'' the
Israeli army said in an announcement from Jerusalem. It made no
mention of casualties.
   It was Israel's ninth air attack into Lebanon this year and the
second in a week.
   On Friday, Israeli warplanes raided south Lebanon's Rashidiyeh
Palestinian refugee camp. Police said two children were wounded in
the attack.
   By police count, nine people have been killed and 60 wounded in
the previous eight Israeli air strikes, which began Jan. 11.
   Jibril's group is headquartered in the Syrian capital, Damascus,
and maintains bases in a chain of tunnels across the Naameh hills.
   A police spokesman said four warplanes blasted the hilltop
positions in six runs spaced over one hour. Thick palls of dust and
smoke billowed from the stricken targets.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party
militia also has bases in the hills, and his militiaman blocked all
roads leading to Naameh, firing AK-47 assault rifles into the air to
prevent reporters from passing checkpoints to the stricken area.
   ``Civilians are not allowed into the area!'' shouted one
militiaman as the raiding jets roared overhead.
   Several Israeli gunboats were seen cruising the Mediterranean off
Naameh.
   Two Israeli helicopter gunships approached the coast, drawing
anti-aircraft fire from Jumblatt's militia and Palestinian
guerrillas, but no hits were observed.
   The Palestinian guerrilla groups with bases in the area also
include George Habash's Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine; Nayef Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine and the Palestine Popular Struggle Front.
   ``But it seems that the main target of the raid is the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command,'' said a
Druse militiaman.
   Israeli air, naval and ground forces fought a nine-hour battle
with the faction in the Naameh hills on December 9. At least eight
guerrillas and a ranking Israeli officer were killed.
   Three Israeli soldiers and 16 guerrillas also were wounded in the
December confrontation.
   Jibril held a news conference at the tunnel base shortly after
the December battle and said helicopter-borne Israeli paratroopers
had released a number of Doberman pinschers fitted with tear gas
containers and explosives to chase his fighters across the tunnels.
   Reporters saw five Dobermans killed by guerrillas. The dogs had
explosives and gas containers strapped around their bellies.
</TEXT>
