<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CargoDoor-Search     06-21 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cargo Door-Search,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Navy Asked To Look For Jet's Cargo Door Three Miles Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy will search the ocean floor more than
three miles down for the 800-pound cargo door that ripped from a
United Airlines jet on Feb. 24 and sent nine people to their deaths,
according to a news report.
   The Navy operation about 85 miles southwest of Honolulu is
scheduled for October, ABC reported Tuesday.
   A row of seats was sucked through the hole on the New
Zealand-bound flight when the fuselage tore open. The pilots managed
to get the crippled Boeing 747 back to Honolulu for a landing that
saved the 345 people still aboard.
   The National Transporation Safety Board, which requested the
search, the Federal Aviation Administration, United and Boeing Co.
have agreed to share the estimated $300,000 cost of recovering the
door, ABC said.
   ``At this time we intend to pursue getting it,'' NTSB spokesman
Ted Lopatkiewicz told The Honolulu Advertiser.
   United spokesman Rob Doughty told the Advertiser the airline is
willing to pay its $70,000 share and had been in contact with the
safety agency.
   David Jimenez, a Boeing spokesman, said Tuesday, ``I think we're
proceeding to recover the door.'' But he said he did not know any
details of the plan or how the Navy would do it.
   NTSB investigators have said the door would help determine what
caused the plane to pop open at 22,000 feet, ripping a 10-by-20-foot
hole in the fuselage.
   In April, a three-day hearing on the accident failed to produce
conclusive evidence of the cause. United executives said then they
wanted to see the door recovered.
   Negotiations were reported to be under way at that time on
whether to retrieve the door and how the costs would be divided.
   Military radar had tracked an object believed to be the cargo
door falling into the ocean at a point where the water is 16,800
feet deep.
   Soon after the mishap, undersea experts said the Navy is probably
the only agency with equipment capable of handling the recovery of
the door.
   A search would probably involve use of a sonar sled and a
remote-controlled vehicle with a camera, Paul Wolcott, a research
submarine pilot at the Hawaii Undersea Research Lab at the
University of Hawaii, said earlier this year.
   The vehicle could probably hook a line to the door to lift it to
the surface, he said.
   The least likely possibility because of the tremendous cost _ up
to $40,000 a day _ would be the Navy's Sea Cliff, one of the world's
few manned research submarines capable of reaching that depth,
Wolcott said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
