<FIRST>r a PM-RunawayTrain     06-21 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Runaway Train,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Takes Off Without Conductor, Engineer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The early departure of a commuter train
caught some passengers off guard but was even more surprising for
the conductor and engineer, who were still in the station.
   None of the dozen or so passengers on the runaway Metro North
train were hurt in the incident Tuesday, which ended when a
passenger pulled an emergency brake, halting the 96-seat train about
200 feet from the station.
   ``The car wasn't going too fast, maybe 15 miles an hour or so,
but we were going to Bridgeport all right,'' said Jack Comerford, a
passenger.
   Metro North spokesman Dan Brucker said the railroad was
investigating what caused the 7:07 a.m. train to begin rolling at
6:57 a.m. without its engine engaged.
   Investigators were focusing on the electric switch that governs
the brakes, he said.
   ``When the engineer and conductor came out to find their train
missing, they were, we understand, somewhat surprised,'' he said.
