<HEAD>Navy Reschedules Mock Invasion After Council Invitation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marines will storm Duluth this summer
after all.
   The Navy on Tuesday accepted the city's invitation to reschedule
a mock beach assault that was canceled after peace activists and
others opposed it.
   The City Council, after hearing from peace activists and veterans
Monday night, voted 6-3 to extend the invitation.
   ``If the City Council is willing to brave the demonstrators, so
will we,'' said Lt. Commander Luanne Smith, executive officer of the
Navy Recruiting District in Minneapolis.
   Earlier this month, religious and peace groups and City Council
President Joyce Benson got the Navy to cancel the public relations
show set for July 21. Many complained that it would glorify war and
damage the Lake Superior beach.
   The exercise involving 200 Marines was to be part of a recruiting
and goodwill visit.
   Kathy Anderson of Duluth Clergy &amp; Laity Concerned said peace
activists will demonstrate against the landing next month.
   Pat Olson, adjutant of Veterans of Foreign Wars Post 137,
countered, ``For every one of those carrying a sign, there'll be two
of us.''
