<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-US-Espionage 3rdLd-Writethru   06-21 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-US-Espionage, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0523,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Soldier Pleads Guilty to Espionage Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details on charges dropped,
panel chosen to decide sentence; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FULDA, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. soldier today pleaded guilty to
charges he gave secret NATO defense plans to communist East Germany,
a military spokesman said.
   Spec. 4 Michael A. Peri of Laguna Niguel, Calif., who had been
described as a model soldier, could receive a life sentence.
   Peri, 21, initially pleaded innocent to the espionage charges. He
changed his plea today when his court martial began, said Maj.
Samuel Taylor, a spokesman for the U.S. Army's 5th Corps.
   Taylor said Peri also pleaded guilty to violating regulations
banning travel by U.S. military close to the East German border
area; being absent without leave; and failing to obey regulations
requiring him to obtain permission to travel to East Germany.
   Taylor said prosecutors dropped a charge of removing classified
information because Peri pleaded guilty to espionage.
   On Feb. 21, Peri disappeared from his unit in Fulda, near the
East German border, taking a portable computer from the office where
he worked as an electronics warfare signal specialist.
   He turned himself in 11 days later.
   On March 16, the Army's 5th Corps in Frankfurt said Peri had been
indicted for espionage for allegedly giving East Germany secret NATO
plans for protecting West Germany in the event of an attack.
   It said the East Germans notified U.S. officials that Peri made
contact with them.
   Peri is assigned to the U.S. Army's 11th Cavalry Regiment in
Fulda, about 60 miles northeast of Frankfurt. The unit is
responsible for front-line patrols along West Germany's border with
East Germany.
   Peri had been kept in investigative custody at the U.S. Army's
confinement facility in Mannheim before the court-martial started.
   Peri, neatly dressed in a U.S. Army uniform, walked with his head
bowed into the U.S. Army Community Center building. The young
soldier was not handcuffed but was escorted by military police.
   The judge, Col. Craig C. Jacobson, ordered the public out of the
courtroom while specifics of the secret information Peri allegedly
gave to the East Germans were discussed by the court.
   Taylor said a board of military officers would be selected
Thursday to hear testimony that will help determine the length of
Peri's sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
