<DOCNO> AP890621-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FHALosses     06-21 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FHA Losses,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Times Says Home Mortgage Insurer's Reserves May Disappear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An audit of the Federal Housing Administration is
expected to show that its main mortgage insurance fund has been
suffering losses at a rate that could run it dry in five months, The
New York Times said today.
   The newspaper, citing government investigators and private
auditors, said the findings will be contained in the first full
audit of the 55-year-old agency, which insures $275 billion worth of
U.S. home mortgages.
   It cited agency officials as saying the FHA was down to a
five-month reserve, $2.8 billion, to cover holders of defaulted
mortgages.
   When the reserve runs out, the Treasury must pick up the payments.
   The main fund is the Mutual Mortgage Insurance Fund, which covers
5.5 million mortgages of up to $101,000 each on single-family homes.
The insurance is financed largely by premiums paid by home buyers.
   Claims on the fund amounted to $2.9 billion in 1986, $4.4 billion
in 1988 and will hit an estimated $6.6 billion this year, according
to budget documents cited by the Times.
   It said that a General Accounting Office report last month put
FHA's losses for the year ending September 1988 at $452 million and
that preliminary figures for the following six months indicated an
additional $150 million in losses.
   Economic downturns, particularly in the oil industry in the
Southwest, plus fraud, mismanagement and a sluggish housing market
contributed to the agency's problems, the Times said.
   Senior officials of the FHA's parent organization, the Department
of Housing and Urban Development, speaking anonymously, said the two
consecutive years of losses did not pose a serious threat, the Times
said.
   But a private auditor said he was less optimistic, particularly
if there were a recession.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     06-21 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Warns Against `War' Among Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who has been
denounced as a traitor by ultra-nationalist Jewish settlers, urged
Israelis not to battle among themselves over how to end the
Palestinian uprising.
   Shamir also endorsed a proposal to include Jewish settlers in
army defense units in the occupied lands despite a recent rise in
settler attacks on Palestinians.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, meanwhile, assailants shot and
killed taxi driver Hassan Sharoub, a 47-year-old Palestinian who was
suspected of cooperating with Israel, radio reports and Arab
journalists said.
   An army official confirmed a fatal shooting in Nablus and said
the circumstances were under investigation.
   Sharoub's death brought to 527 the number of Palestinians killed
in the 18{-month uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and
occupied Gaza Strip. The figure includes 64 suspected collaborators.
Twenty-three Israelis also have died.
   Israeli newspapers reported today that Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin has asked Israeli experts to examine the legality of using
harsher measures against Palestinians.
   Rabin reportedly wants to deport Palestinians within a week after
such an order has been issued. Deportees now can appeal the order
and the legal procedure can take months.
   Rabin also wants to scrap the possibility of appealing
army-ordered house demolitions, the Davar newspaper reported.
   The army sometimes destroys or seals the homes of Palestinians
suspected of attacks on Israelis. The United States has condemned
the practice, saying it denies suspects due process of law because
the army usually acts before a suspect has been tried.
   Shamir has come under growing pressure from the extreme right to
use harsher measures to quell the uprising. His critics also argue
that his peace plan, based on elections in the occupied lands, will
pave the way for a Palestinian state.
   On Tuesday, settlers shouted down Shamir as he spoke at the
funeral of a U.S.-born West Bank settler allegedly slain by
Palestinians.
   Shamir said on Israel radio today that disagreements over
government policies must not degenerate into domestic strife. ``We
must do everything to make sure such a war never happens. This is
the most dangerous thing,'' Shamir said.
   ``I would suggest to everyone to lower the profile of our
internal debates, because if the profile rises you can slide into
irresponsible actions,'' he added.
   Shamir's rival in the Likud bloc, ultra-nationalist Industry
Minister Ariel Sharon, was met by thunderous applause during
Tuesday's funeral. Sharon has engineered a showdown with Shamir over
the peace plan at a Likud convention next month.
   A poll published by the Yediot Ahronot daily Wednesday indicated
Shamir had the support of 55 percent of the 2,600 members of the
party's Central Committee. Twenty-one percent opposed it and 24
percent were undecided, the poll said.
   In an apparent bid to appease the settlers, Shamir said he backed
a proposal to include them in regional defense units. ``We can
definitely take this path,'' he said.
   In the past, settlers doing army reserve duty were barred from
serving near their hometowns. Most Israeli men serve in the reserves
for up to two months a year until age 54.
   Shamir also criticized an attack Tuesday in which a 23-year-old
Jewish settler fired at a group of Palestinians standing at an
intersection near Tel Aviv. Two Arabs were wounded, one of them
seriously.
   Israel radio said the assailant, who staged the shooting after
attending the funeral of the slain settler, has a police record.
   ``We must prevent such actions. They only strengthen the other
side, the extremists among the Arabs,'' Shamir said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
