<HEAD>Parliament Opposes Move to Allow Supreme Leader to Dissolve It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with parliament member criticizing
return of West German and French ambassadors; picks up 5th graf pvs: The
lawmakers...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian parliament member today
criticized the foreign ministry's decision to allow the return of
the West German and French ambassadors to Tehran, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said Qorban Ali Salemabadi
claimed the two countries led a European attack on Islam and the
late revolutionary leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The deputy was referring to a decision by 14 Western nations in
February to recall their envoys from Iran in retaliation for a death
sentence issued by Khomeini against British author Salman Rushdie
for allegedly blaspheming Islam in his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   France and West Germany decided last week to send back their
ambassadors to Iran after the death June 3 of Khomeini, 86. Several
European countries have already sent back their envoys.
   Salemabadi, a deputy from the northeastrn city of Mashhad, called
on the foreign ministry to revise Iran's relations with Paris and
Bonn.
   Also today, IRNA said nearly 180 members of the 270-member
Majlis, or parliament, wrote to committee chairman Ayatollah Ali
Meshkini to express concern over proposed changes in the
constitution that would allow the nation's supreme leader to
dissolve the legislature.
   A committee set up by Khomeini in April to write a new
constitution has proposed widening the leader's powers, the Islamic
Republic News Agency said.
   Iranians are to vote on the new constitution and elect a
president on July 28.
   The lawmakers said Khomeini had not asked the 20-member committee
to review this issue and that the current constitution says the
Majlis should be active under all circumstances.
   IRNA reported the government-run Tehran Times said in an
editorial that ``the late imam believed that the supreme leader was
above the three branches of government.''
   President Ali Khamenei became Iran's highest leader on June 4, a
day after Khomeini, the architect of Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution,
died at age 86.
   Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani is the only announced
candidate for president in the July election.
   IRNA also reported today that another government-run newspaper
said in an editorial that Khomeini's will has relevance for ``the
entire oppressed peoples of the world, regardless of their religion
or nationality.''
   Kayhan International said the will should be translated into all
major languages.
   It said the will stresses the importance of self-reliance and
warns of the dangers of adopting foreign cultures, especially
American, according to IRNA.
</TEXT>
