<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Spill-Taxes     06-21 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Taxes,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Opposes Bill to Deny Exxon a Cleanup Tax Deduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration today opposed a bill
aimed at denying Exxon Corp. a tax deduction for costs of cleaning
up the Alaska oil spill.
   ``The bill would violate the fundamental principle of business
taxation that a taxpayer's ordinary and necessary business expenses
may be deducted in computing net income,'' Kenneth W. Gideon,
assistant treasury secretary for tax policy, told the Senate Finance
Committee.
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., sponsor of the bill, said: ``I do not
want to tell my constituents that the American people owe Exxon, the
biggest polluter in history, millions of dollars in a tax rebate in
return for destroying the environment and raising prices at the gas
pumps.''
   Waving a handful of Exxon credit cards that irate customers had
mailed him in protest, Reid added:
   ``Given the company's dismal cleanup performance and the
resultant permanent scar that now defaces Alaska's beauty, it is
incomprehensible that Exxon should be able to claim its cleanup
costs _ estimated at $500 million _ as an `ordinary and necessary'
cost of doing business.''
   Some 10 million gallons of crude oil were spilled into Alaska's
Prince William Sound on March 24 when the tanker Exxon Valdez ran
aground.
   A large share of Exxon's cleanup costs apparently are covered by
insurance. Under present law, any uninsured share could be deducted
from taxable income as a cost of doing business. Because the top
corporate tax rate is 34 percent, the effect would be for the
federal treasury to pay 34 percent of the uninsured expenses.
   Reid's bill, which also would apply to any future chemical spill,
would prohibit such a deduction unless the federal government
certified that the cleanup had been conducted in accordance with the
law.
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who said he supports the concept of
Reid's bill, pointed out that existing environmental laws contain no
objective standards for determining whether a cleanup was proper.
   Paul R. Huard, vice president of the National Association of
Manufacturers, which opposes the bill, said the legislation likely
would discourage corporate efforts to clean up spills.
   ``Because the sanctions ... are so draconian, a likely response
is that taxpayers involved in oil spills or hazardous substance
dischages will undertake very little cleanup activity on their own
initiative, and instead will choose to protect the deductibility of
their expenditures by awaiting specific directions from the
applicable government agency,'' Huard said.
   The bill was supported by Clifton E. Curtis, executive director
of the Oceanic Society, an environmental group. He said the
legislation should be made tougher by denying ``tax deductions to
spillers for oil or hazardous spill-related expenses without regard
to adequacy of cleanup.''
   ``Such an approach would send a message that would foster
stronger preventive measures by industry,'' Curtis said.
   Rep. William O. Lipinski, D-Ill., who has introduced a companion
bill to Reid's in the House, said Exxon's cleanup expenses should
not be tax-deductible because ``oil and toxic spill cleanup is not
`ordinary' and is not a `necessary' business expense.''
</TEXT>
