<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   06-21 0931</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0966</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: it easier.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 16
   The Arizona Daily Star, Tucson, Ariz., on Chinese dissidents:
   While Ambassador James Lilley has said the United States doesn't
want to inflame the situation by posturing, the State Department was
nevertheless straightforwardly vocal ... in flatly stating its
intention to protect Chinese dissidents Fang Lizhi and Li Shuxian.
   The United States must not waver in its commitment to this
couple, even if it means letting them stay indefinitely at the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing.
   The importance of that commitment exists on two levels _ one
personal, the other symbolic.
   With several executions already ordered by Chinese officials,
Fang is in grave personal danger, since the ``crime'' he is accused
of is comparable to treason. On a broader scale, since Fang and his
wife are aligned with the aspirations of the student democracy
movement, U.S. treatment of them will also inevitably symbolize its
regard for the movement, as well as its commitment to the ideals of
free expression and democracy.
   Author Orville Schell wrote for The New York Times ..., ``Deng
Xiaoping and Li Peng have begun searching for ways to divert
attention from the carnage they wrought in Tiananmen Square on June
3.'' He was referring to their singling out of Fang as an
``archenemy of the nation.''
   Since that piece was written, the government has moved on, adding
two Western journalists as still more diversions, still more objects
of contempt.
   It is a familiar maneuver for Chinese officials. Now Associated
Press reporter John Pomfret and Voice of America's Beijing bureau
chief, Alan Pessin, have been expelled. Pomfret, who speaks Chinese
and who had done much reporting among student demonstrators, was an
obvious target, as was Pessin, whose organization's broadcasts have
tried to counter the Chinese government's shameful rewriting of
recent history.
   It is vital that the United States make known, through both words
and deeds, that it deplores the mass arrests, the planned
executions, the attempt to rewrite history, the intention to arrest
dissident Fang Lizhi and the expulsion of journalists.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 14
   The Register-Herald, Beckley, W.Va., on Chinese dissidents:
   Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi is not the first to seek refuge in
an American embassy. Nor is it likely he will be the last.
   Fang is holed up in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing. China has issued
official proclamations to stop Fang at all borders and all points of
transportation out of the country. But the dissident need not take
another step.
   The Bush administration has three options, but only one choice.
   Under no circumstance should Fang be handed over to the
authorities, who want Fang's hide for his role in the demonstrations
that led to the violent showdown two weeks ago.
   To spirit Fang out of the country would serve only to provoke the
Chinese government _ provoked enough already because we are giving
Fang sanctuary.
   The only choice is to house Fang indefinitely inside the embassy.
   That would be a form of passive resistance to China's latest
outrage.
   But in making that choice, America would be wise to be prepared
for further outrages.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 17
   The Milwaukee Journal on a healthy start program for infants:
   Children deserve the best possible start in life. That means
their mothers must have adequate prenatal care, a relative luxury
for the thousands of Wisconsin women not fortunate enough to be
covered by insurance yet not needy enough to qualify for Medicaid.
   It is for these women, and their infants less than a year old,
that Wisconsin's Healthy Start program was designed.
   Now legislators seem inclined to expand Healthy Start, to include
women whose family incomes are higher than current ceilings set by
the state. That's not just a compassionate gesture; in the long run,
it would prove cost-effective, too.
   Healthy Start pays all prenatal doctor bills, whatever
prescription costs the woman incurs during pregnancy and all
expenses associated with labor and delivery. In addition, the
program covers the costs of the mother's medical care for 60 days
after delivery and the infant's for a full year.
   Obviously, a baby who is immunized and whose growth and
development are tracked by a doctor will have an edge over one
lacking such attention.
   The benefits of prenatal care may seem murkier but are no less
compelling. The longer a woman delays prenatal visits to a doctor,
the more likely she is to bear a child needing medical attention
because of prematurity, low birth weight or some other complication.
Experts calculate that every $1 spent on prenatal care saves $3.38
that would otherwise have to be spent later on a youngster born with
problems.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 19
   The Indianapolis Star on the lottery and political contributions:
   You'd think that after devoting that much time and attention to
the lottery, state lawmakers would have gotten it right. If they
had, there wouldn't be any wrangling about what they meant and what
they didn't mean.
   Under dispute is a provision in the lottery statute governing
political contributions. It prohibits the lottery commission from
entering into a contract with a person who contributed within the
past three years to a candidate for a statewide office.
   In addition, individual vendors and service contractors may not
contribute to a candidate for three years. ...
   If the legislature had stated its intentions precisely, clearly
and unambiguously there would be no confusion, no need for the
governor to ask the attorney general for a ruling, no need for the
attorney general to make one and no bickering about the nature and
content of the ruling.
</TEXT>
