<FIRST>u w PM-Lukens 1stLd-Writethru a0546 06-21 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0546,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Republicans Urge Ethics Probe of Lukens</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Puts attribution on the record; inserts four new grafs after
3rd graf pvs, Such a ..., with Michel comment and with reason for GOP action;
new graf after 4th graf pvs, Lukens spokesman ..., with additional comment;
two grafs Walker comment after 9th graf pvs, In presenting ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unprecedented move, House Republicans
today asked the ethics committee to investigate GOP Rep. Donald E.
Lukens of Ohio, convicted last month of charges stemming from his
sexual relationship with a 16-year-old girl.
   The House Republican Conference, the organization of all GOP
House members, took the action in a closed-door meeting at the
behest of its top leadership, according to a statement issued by
Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill.
   Such a request virtually ensures that the ethics panel will open
a formal investigation of Lukens, who was convicted May 30 in
Franklin County, Ohio, of contributing to the unruliness or
delinquency of a minor. He is appealing.
   Michel said the move ``reflects our total commitment to standards
of behavior for members of Congress which reflect honorably on the
institution and the nation. House Republicans will not accept
anything less.''
   He said the GOP will live up to its constitutional obligation to
police its own members ``no matter how distasteful or painful.''
   Despite Michel's comments, the move was seen as a pre-emptive
strike by Republicans and an effort to keep Democrats on the
defensive on the ethics issue, which the GOP has said will be its
main emphasis this year. The ethics committee likely would have
investigated Lukens anyway.
   Lukens spokesman William Jarrell said: ``Congressman Lukens
welcomes a full and open investigation that may once and for all
bring forth the truth about this entire episode. In fact, this will
probably assist in our appeals.''
   Jarrell said Lukens was hampered in court because he was not
permitted to cast doubt on the motives and credibility of the girl
and her mother, who were Lukens' accusers. ``Now we'll be able to
bring forth the background and the motives'' of the two, he said.
   The jury found Lukens guilty of the misdemeanor charge based on
its conclusion that he had sex with the girl at his Columbus
apartment last November. Such a conviction does not automatically
deny Lukens the right to serve in Congress or seek re-election.
   The resolution asking for an investigation of Lukens requests
that the ethics panel, formally called the Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct, ``determine whether Rep. Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens
failed to conduct himself at all times in a manner which reflects
creditably on the House of Representatives.''
   The source, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said the
resolution was passed by a show of hands on a ``substantial''
majority.
   In presenting the resolution, Michel said it was unprecedented
for the conference to call for an ethics probe of one of its own
members.
   And another member of the GOP leadership, Rep. Robert Walker of
Pennsylvania, suggested Democrats might do well to turn the ethics
spotlight on their own bad apples.
   ``We have taken that step of asking for an investigation,''
Walker said. ``I think it's an appropriate kind of step to suggest
that the other caucus ought to also be willing to do the kind of
tough thing that is involved in what our conference did today.''
   The document notes that House members, ``in order to perform
their constitutional duties, must conduct themselves with
integrity'' and that House rules require conduct which will not
bring disrepute on the institution.
   Lukens, 58 and divorced, has said he planned to fight the
conviction and remain in Congress in the meantime. ``I refuse to
allow the lies and deceit of one delinquent individual to ruin me. I
am now fighting for my life,'' he said in a statement following his
conviction.
   Lukens said in that statement that his accuser had ``fantasies of
`getting even with the establishment.'''
   But the court refused to allow him to bring up evidence he wanted
to present to raise doubts about her reliability, the conservative
lawmaker said.
   Since the conviction, Ohio state GOP chairman Robert Bennett has
said Lukens will not be on the party's ticket in 1990 based on
opposition from local party officials.
   Lukens' Republican House colleagues also have distanced
themselves from him. His conviction has harmed their cause at a time
when they have been seeking to use the ethics issue against
Democrats.
   Lukens is currently in the second term of his second stint in
Congress. He also was in Congress for two terms from 1967 to 1971.
</TEXT>
