<HEAD>Hoyer to Head House Democratic Caucus</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2 grafs for 2nd graf pvs, Hoyer, 50, ..., to fix Hoyer's
tenure and include comment, explanation of job.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland won election today
as chairman of the House Democratic Caucus, the fourth-ranking
position in the party leadership.
   Hoyer, 50, the deputy chairman of the caucus for the past 6
months, defeated Rep. Barbara Kennelly, D-Conn., 165-82, in a closed
meeting of House Democrats. Two votes were cast for others in the
secret balloting.
   The Maryland lawmaker, who first came to Congress in a special
election in 1981, said he wanted to ``revitalize'' the caucus, which
holds meetings of all House Democrats on party policy positions.
   The election was part of an ongoing effort by the Democrats to
restore their leadership ranks in the wake of the ethics inquiries
that led to the resignation of Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and
Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the party's chief vote counter.
   Rep. Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., succeeded Wright and Rep. Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., took Foley's post of majority leader. Hoyer
succeeds Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., who was elected last week
as majority whip.
</TEXT>
