<FIRST>r w PM-Genscher 200   06-21 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Genscher, 200</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Reports on Gorbachev Visit, Outlook for East-West Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher came here today with a report to the Bush administration on
the recent visit of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to Bonn.
   Genscher also had on his agenda arms control issues and next
month's economic summit meeting in Paris.
   He saw Secretary of State James A. Baker III at the start of the
day, and was scheduled to call on President Bush, Secretary of
Defense Dick Cheney and leading members of Congress.
   In contrast to recent visits, there was no major dispute in U.S.
relations with West Germany to discuss.
   Bush and Chancellor Helmut Kohl struck a deal at the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization summit meeting in Brussels last month
over short-range nuclear missiles.
   A U.S.-British plan to make the weapons deadlier was postponed
until 1992, which pleased Bonn. Also, Bush agreed to negotiations
with the Soviets on a cutback.
   But the West Germans lost out in a drive to hold those talks
promptly. Negotiations would begin only after NATO and the Warsaw
Pact concluded an agreement to reduce conventional armaments and
troops in Europe.
   Genscher's visit fulfills an invitation extended by Baker at the
summit meeting.
</TEXT>
