<DOCNO> AP890621-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-ABA     06-21 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-ABA,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Federal Law Does Not Apply to ABA Role in Picking Judges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that a federal
law allowing public scrutiny of governmental advisory groups does
not apply to the American Bar Association's role in picking federal
judges.
   Voting 8-0, the justices allowed the ABA's deliberations to
remain largely secret.
   Justice William J. Brennan, in his opinion for the court, said
Congress did not intend the ABA's confidential relationship with the
Justice Department in selecting judges to be made public when it
passed a law covering adivisory committees.
   Tipping the balance in favor of confidentiality, Brennan said, is
the risk that public disclosure of ABA deliberations would infringe
improperly on the president's power to nominate federal judges.
   But Brennan stopped short of declaring that the constitutional
doctrine of separation of powers between Congress and the president
guarantees the confidentiality of the deliberations.
   Today's ruling upheld a federal judge's decision last year
barring application of the Federal Advisory Committee Act to the
ABA's Standing Committee on the Federal Judiciary.
   The ABA, the nation's largest lawyers' organization, has for some
40 years played a key role in advising presidents on nominees to the
federal bench.
   The Justice Department asks the ABA's judiciary committee for
confidential evaluations of possible judicial nominees. The panel is
the only non-government group that routinely is told of potential
nominees before the names are made public.
   ABA evaluations are made public after a nomination is submitted
to the Senate _ although the substance of the deliberations
generally remains secret.
   The ABA, after interviewing lawyers, judges, professors and the
nominee, rates potential nominees as exceptionally well qualified,
well qualified, qualified or not qualified. The ABA is not required
to reveal who was interviewed or any specifics of the process.
   A controversy over the ABA's role was ignited when the ABA panel
was divided over former President Ronald Reagan's nomination of
Robert H. Bork to the Supreme Court in 1987.
   Republicans on the Senate Judiciary Committee accused ABA
committee members of being politicallly motivated in questioning
Bork's fitness to be a justice.
   The Senate defeated Bork's nomination after a long, bittr fight
in which opponents said he was too rigidly conservative.
   The conservative Washington Legal Foundation and Public Citizen,
a liberal public-interest organization, joined forces in seeking to
compel the ABA committee to reveal its deliberations.
   The former Reagan administration opposed the move. The Justice
Department last year said the Federal Advisory Committee Act is
aimed at special groups and the ABA panel does not fit into that
category.
   Justice Antonin Scalia did not take part in today's ruling.
   The cases are Public Citizen vs. Justice Department, 88-429, and
Washington Legal Foundation vs. Justice Department, 88-494.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
