<FIRST>u w PM-DrillingBan     06-21 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drilling Ban,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Approves Ban on Some Offshore Oil Drilling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee approved a one-year ban on
oil exploration in Alaska's Bristol Bay and voted to continue bans
on drilling in areas offshore California, Florida and the
mid-Atlantic.
   The action Tuesday by the House Appropriations subcommittee on
the interior marked a significant expansion of limits on the oil
industry's offshore drilling efforts and reflects political backlash
from the Exxon spill in Alaska last March.
   The ban is attached to a spending bill that will take effect on
Oct. 1. The Appropriations Committee is scheduled to consider the
legislation next Tuesday.
   The measure also asks Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan to study
options for buying back approximately $95 million in Bristol Bay
development leases sold to oil companies last October.
   The oil industry considers Bristol Bay a prime prospect.
   The panel also recommended continuing for another year existing
bans on drilling in offshore areas in northern and southern
California. Environmental considerations linked to drilling in those
areas is under review by a task force appointed last March by
President Bush. It is due to report to him next January.
   The subcommittee also voted to continue for another year existing
bans on oil drilling in areas off southern Floria, and to withhold
for one year plans for selling exploration leases in a mid-Atlantic
area stretching from Maryland to Rhode Island.
   Lisa Speer, senior staff scientist for the Natural Resources
Defense Council, an environmental group, called the panel's decision
``a real step toward coastal protection.''
</TEXT>
