<FIRST>u i PM-China-DengSpeech 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Deng Speech, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0580,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Defends Crackdown And Says Open Door Policy Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to fix typos, clarify differing accounts on death
toll. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping of China said the
United States used troops to quell student demonstrations during the
1960s and should not criticize China for its crackdown on
dissidents, a Hong Kong newspaper reported.
   The English-language South China Morning Post on Tuesday
published the full speech Deng delivered to senior military
officials on June 9, five days after the army entered Beijing to put
down the pro-democracy movement.
   Portions of the speech, which were broadcast on national Chinese
television, had been reported previously. The newspaper did not say
how it obtained the full text of the speech.
   Deng noted that Washington has criticized China for suppressing
students but said the United States also mobilized troops against
student rioters in the 1960s and 1970s.
   ``They were suppressing students and the people, but we are
quelling counterrevolutionary riots. What qualifications do they
have to criticize us!'' he said.
   In his speech, Deng said the pro-democracy protesters hoped to
``topple the Chinese Communist party and to overthrow the socialist
order ... Of course these slogans are just a front ...Their goal is
to establish a totally Westernized bourgeois republic.''
   Deng said that in the course of quelling the rebellion, many
people died.
   China has maintained that less than 300 people died, about half
of them soldiers. Western intelligence sources and Chinese students
have estimated that up to 3,000 may have been killed in the June 3-4
incident.
   ``No matter how heavy our losses, and in spite of the change of
generations, this army of ours is forever an army under the
leadership of the party, forever the defender of the country,
forever the defender of socialism, forever the defender of public
interest,'' Deng said.
   He indicated in the speech that the student-led protest movement,
which lasted seven weeks, was inevitable.
   ``This storm was bound to come sooner or later ... We are
fortunate that it has come about now, mainly because we have a large
group of senior comrades who are still alive. They have experienced
many storms and they know the cause of effects of things,'' the
84-year-old leader said.
   Deng stressed that the basic concept of reform and openness for
the past 10 years is correct and indicated that China wants to
maintain economic ties to the rest of the world. ``Without reform
and openness, how could we have what we have today?''
   He said the results of the economic reforms that began in 1979
should be carefully assessed. ``We must persist in the coordination
between a planned economy and a market economy. There cannot be any
change in this policy ... What is important is that we should never
change China into a closed country.''
   He urged more investment in China ``even if it involves heavy
debts.''
   However, less than two weeks after Deng's speech, Japanese
Foreign Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka said it will put a halt to all
economic aid negotiations with China. Japan supplies 80 percent of
the international credit China receives.
   On Tuesday, Washington announced it was tightening diplomatic and
financial pressure on China, including postponing new loans.
</TEXT>
