<HEAD>42 Casualties in Second Afghan Air Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transport plane crashed this week in
southern Afghanistan, killing or injuring 42 passengers and crew, a
Moslem rebel news service reported Wednesday.
   The Afghan News Agency said the Soviet-built An-32 went down
Sunday at Lashkhar Gah, capital of Helmand province bordering
Pakistan.
   There was no independent confirmation.
   ANA did not say whether the plane, normally a civilian aircraft
capable of carrying 39 passengers, belonged to Afghanistan's Ariana
national airline or whether it was in military service.
   The agency said it was not clear whether it crashed due to a
technical problem or was shot down by guerrillas fighting the
country's Soviet-backed Marxist government.
