<DOCNO> AP890621-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-ChildCare 1stLd-Writethru a0432 06-21 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>White Houses Raises Child Care Veto Prospect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with administration raising prospect of veto;
picks up at pvs 3rd graf, ``I have''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will veto major child-care
legislation being advanced by Senate Democrats and a Republican if
it reaches the White House in its present form, the administration
said today.
   A letter from the Office of Management and Budget distributed on
Capitol Hill said the multibillion-dollar package before the Senate
``violates all of the president's principles.''
   The letter said the revised measure before the Senate was an
improvement over the original bill but remained ``fundamentally
flawed.'' It said the measure would restrict parental choice in
child care, provide assistance only to families who pay for child
care and discriminate against low-income parents who have other
family members care for their children.
   The White House is backing an alternative Republican package. The
OMB letter said that if the plan favored by the Senate's Democratic
leadership ``were presented to the president, his senior advisers
would recommend that he veto it.''
   The statement was distributed as Senate GOP leaders sought
support for the alternative. Debate on the issue continued in the
Senate today, but no votes were scheduled until Thursday.
   The criticisms in the OMB letter were similar to those raised by
many Republicans during the Senate's five days of debate on the
issue. The points prompted Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican who
co-sponsored the Democratic bill, to lash out at his GOP colleagues.
   ``I'm ashamed when I hear some of the arguments that I've heard
on this floor,'' Hatch said Tuesday, accusing critics of spreading
``misinformation and disinformation and distortions.''
   ``I have no respect for people who distort the facts,'' Hatch
said. ``We have an obligation to tell the truth and let the chips
fall as they may.''
   Hatch, who has been critical of the Bush administration's
competing child care proposal, said he believed provisions of the
president's tax-credit package could be merged with the revised Act
for Better Child Care sponsored by Hatch and Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn.
   ``This should not be a partisan political issue,'' Hatch said.
``We're willing to do what it takes to get a child care bill and we
don't care who gets the credit for it.''
   Republican leader Bob Dole had planned to offer a White
House-backed alternative to the ABC plan on Tuesday but held off as
the GOP leadership sought support from Southern Democrats.
   It relies almost exclusively on tax credits, including an
expansion of the existing earned income tax credit for low-income
families with children under the age of 5. Like the Dodd-Hatch
proposal, the Dole alternative would provide up-front money to
families that otherwise could not take advantage of the existing
dependent care tax credit because of low income.
   Dole also called for a $400 million block grant program states
could use to fund programs designed to improve the quality and
quantity of child care. And, borrowing a proposal from Sen. William
Armstrong, R-Colo., Dole proposed exempting child care earnings from
the outside income limitations faced by Social Security recipients.
   Dole and other Republicans have touched on their plan during the
four days of Senate debate. Democrats, joined by the GOP's Hatch,
have called it inadequate while offering to merge its tax credit
provisions with the direct subsidies provided to parents and child
care providers under the ABC plan.
   Benefits under Bush's plan would be available mainly to those
making under $10,000 a year. The Democratic subsidies would be
available according to formulas determined at the state level.
   An aide to Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell predicted
Dole's effort to substitute his proposal for the Dodd-Hatch measure
would fail. ``Senator Mitchell has proven in the past that he knows
how to count,'' the aide said.
   Mitchell, unable to reach agreement with Republicans on a
timetable to bring the issue to a final vote, warned he would delay
a two-week Senate recess due to begin next week if debate and
amendments prevented a final vote by Friday.
   ``This is a very important matter,'' Mitchell said. ``We're going
to stay as long as it takes.''
   With Dole holding his plan, the highlight of Tuesday's debate was
Hatch's angry criticism of fellow Republicans and conservatives.
   Waving a copy of a circular distributed at a Republican caucus
that attacked the Dodd-Hatch bill, Hatch said he did not mind
arguments over honest disagreements but added: ``I mind people who
try to win their case with falsehoods.'' He said the letter was on
paper without a letterhead. ``I do not know who prepared this piece
of junk.''
   As revised, the ABC bill would authorize $1.75 billion for child
care programs in fiscal 1990, with 70 percent of the money going to
low-income parents to help them pay for child care. The remaining
funds would go to states for programs to improve the quality and
quantity of available child care.
</TEXT>
