<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Festival     06-21 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Festival,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Bans South Koreans from Attending North Korean Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Wednesday refused to
allow 40 Christian youths and newspaper reporters to attend a
festival in North Korea, saying their participation would harm
national interests.
   The refusal confirmed an earlier ban on South Koreans taking part
in the 13th World Festival of Youth and Students scheduled July 1-8.
   ``The Pyongyang gathering is not in conformity with the
government's basic unification policy and is detrimental to our
national interest,'' National Unification Minister Lee Hong-koo told
reporters.
   He added, however, that Seoul will continue to encourage contacts
with North Korea that do not harm South Korean interests.
   Lee said senior government officials turned down the requests
from 40 Christian youths and journalists.
   The decision came after authorities denied entry visas to three
festival delegates who wanted to travel to Seoul.
   Delegates from Belgium, Jamaica and Uruguay were refused entry
visas by the South Korean consulate in Hong Kong and were not
allowed to board a Korean Air plane, delegation leader Theo Celens
said by telephone from Hong Kong.
   Celens, a Belgian representing the Vienna-based International
Union of Socialist Youth, said his delegation wanted to urge Seoul
to let South Koreans join the festival.
   ``Our intention was to have a neutral contact,'' he said, adding
the festival committee did not want only radical South Koreans, but
``a balanced delegation.''
   North Korea has invited about 500 South Korean students and
dissidents to join in the sports, cultural and political event
attended mainly by students from Third World and communist nations.
   Seoul accuses Pyongyang of using the festival to dramatize its
demand for the withdrawal of U.S. troops based in South Korea under
a mutual defense treaty.
   The festival's organizing committee said Wednesday the South
Koreans could attend as observers if their government was concerned
about the festival's political nature, according to the official
North Korean Central News Agency, monitored in Tokyo.
   ``We have given assurances that we would not do anything that may
impose a political burden on the South Korean youth and students
participating in the festival and that we had no intention to use
them politically,'' it quoted the committee as saying.
</TEXT>
