<FIRST>u a PM-UnlicensedDropout     06-21 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unlicensed Dropout,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Restores Dropout's License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge temporarily restored driving
privileges today to a teen-age father-to-be whose license was
revoked because he dropped out of school.
   Circuit Judge Paul Zakaib Jr. set aside Michael Means' license
revocation for 30 days while lawyers file briefs and the judge makes
a decision.
   Means, 17, who dropped out in ninth grade last year, is appealing
the loss of his license May 30 under a first-of-its-kind law aimed
at curbing truancy in a state where the dropout rate is around 17
percent.
   Under the law passed last summer, students under 18 who miss more
than 10 consecutive days of school or have 15 unexcused absences
lose their driving privileges.
   Means, whose 16-year-old wife, Tonya, is expecting their first
child this fall, sued on June 8, the first time the law has been
challenged in court. His father said the teen-ager cannot support
his growing family without a license.
   The law allows school boards to grant hardship exceptions, but
state officials maintain that the teen-ager could hold a job and
still complete his education.
   Educators have praised the legislation, saying its brings
teen-agers back to school, but Means' lawyer, Chris Butch, has
argued that it conflicts with another law allowing students to drop
out at 16. He called the law ridiculous.
   ``It says you're poor, you dropped out of high school, and now
we're going to punish you some more,'' Butch said.
   Several states, including Wisconsin and Texas, where Gov. Bill
Clements signed a dropout bill into law Friday, have similar laws.
   The judge today Zakaib said Means keep his driving privileges if
he enrolls in a high school equivalency course and makes
satisfactory progress.
   ``I think they're trying to force me to go into a GED program and
I don't like being forced to do anything,'' Means said after the
hearing.
</TEXT>
