<FIRST>u a PM-Mayors 3rdLd-Writethru a0561 06-21 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayors, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0561,0967</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Deplore Supreme Court Rulings on Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE Flynn winning election and RESTORE
first reference to Atwater. PICKS UP 13th graf pv, ``Even some ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's mayors today adopted a
statement deploring recent Supreme Court decisions that they say
weaken affirmative action.
   The U.S. Conference of Mayors also called for higher federal
taxes and a ban on possession of semi-automatic weapons.
   Before wrapping up their annual conference, the mayors also
settled an unprecedented contested race for the conference's future
leadership, choosing Democrat Ray Flynn of Boston over Republican
William Althaus of York, Pa.
   The mayors overwhelmingly voted down an effort by some Florida
mayors to soften the language of their resolution on
anti-discrimination in employment.
   Mayor Cecil Bradbury of Pinellas Park, Fla., argued that whites
have been victims of discrimination through efforts aimed at
encouraging minority employment.
   But the mayors sided with Republican William Hudnut of
Indianapolis, who argued that without affirmative action, ``the good
ol' boy network'' will favor whites.
   The mayors said recent Supreme Court decisions are ``making it
more difficult to ensure equal opportunities in employment for all
Americans.''
   Among the other statements, the mayors called for higher federal
taxes to cut the deficit and allow more urban aid, and urged a ban
on possession of military-type semi-automatic assault weapons.
   The five-day meeting of mayors from around the nation neared an
end one day after the session erupted into partisan name-calling,
with New York's Ed Koch launching a bitter tirade against the
Republican national chairman.
   Flynn was elected chairman of the organization's advisory
committee, an unglamorous title but a job that puts him in line to
be president of the conference in 1991.
   The vote was cast largely along party lines, 67-35, although
Houston's Kathy Whitmire, a Democrat and incoming president of the
group, sided with the Republican.
   Flynn said the issue was whether the mayors wanted an outspoken
critic of President Bush who would challenge Republican policies.
Whitmire, from Bush's Texas, has said she is optimistic about the
new administration.
   ``I don't think this is time for mayors to sit back and just go
along, to say everything's all right in our cities. Everything is
not all right in our cities,'' Flynn said.
   The contest for advisory committee chairman was thrown to the
full conference when two Democrats sided with the Republicans and
deadlocked a nominating committee that for 57 years has settled such
matters in private.
   The meeting, where partisanship is often submerged in discussions
of common urban needs, saw party bickering flare when Lee Atwater,
the GOP national chairman, spoke Monday.
   Even some Republicans complained about his blunt partisan speech,
including Atwater's statement that he was targeting Koch's
re-election race.
   Arriving Tuesday, Koch denounced Atwater as ``amoral'' and a
``pathological'' liar. He said Atwater bore responsibility for the
Republican memo that attacked House Speaker Tom Foley with
homosexual innuendo and had lied in denying it.
   ``He may be the best hired gun in the world, but he carries with
him all of the things that America hates, which is low-level,
disgusting tactics ... vile things,'' Koch said of Atwater.
   Democratic National Chairman Ron Brown, who previously called for
Atwater's resignation, also addressed the group Tuesday and laced
his speech with blasts at Atwater. Brown accused his Republican
counterpart of having ``taken politics to the lowest level of my
lifetime.''
   ``Thanks to the Lee Atwaters of the world, national politics is
looking more and more like the coastline of Valdez, Alaska,'' Brown
said. ``Make no mistake, they want the political oil spill of
negative campaigning to spread across America.''
   In Washington, RNC spokeswoman Leslie Goodman said, ``We assume
Ed Koch has said all these things because he's in a heated race for
mayor.'' She had no comment on Brown's remarks.
   The partisanship, combined with the unusual leadership race,
dominated discussions among the mayors.
   Indianapolis Republican Mayor William Hudnut, who on Tuesday had
said he was ``embarrassed and disappointed'' by Atwater's remarks,
criticized Brown on Wednesday.
   ``I just think politicizing the meeting is wrong, and Ron was as
guilty as Lee was,'' Hudnut said.
   He noted that many mayors are elected in races where no party
affiliation is listed, and said the conference shouldn't invite
national party chairmen again.
   ``We work very hard not to be partisan in this organization,''
added Althaus, who was working to avoid a party-line vote in his own
race since Democratic mayors outnumber Republicans.
   The race was for the job of chairman of the conference's advisory
committee. It carries an unglamorous title, but the job is third on
the group's leadership ladder and means the winner will be scheduled
to assume the post of president of the conference _ and leading
spokesman for the nation's mayors _ in 1991.
   The race had partisan dimensions because a victory by Althaus
would mean the conference would have two consecutive Republican
leaders for the first time ever.
   Republican Mayor Bob Isaac of Colorado Springs, Colo., has the
job and is scheduled to be president in 1990, following Democrat
Kathryn Whitmire of Houston, who was to assume the presidency today
after a year as vice president.
   The mayors were ending their meeting having barely mentioned the
scandals involving the Department of Housing and Urban Development,
which is beset by allegations of influence peddling and disclosures
of embezzlement.
   ``We can't let the Republicans turn housing programs for the poor
into subsidy programs for wealthy Republican consultants,'' Brown
said in one of the few public airings of the issue this week.
</TEXT>
