<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov     06-21 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Human Rights Activist Receives Oxford Honorary Degree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei Sakharov received a prolonged
ovation Wednesday as Oxford University honored ``a noble champion of
harmony'' with an honorary doctorate in science.
   Dressed in a scarlet and gray gown, the Soviet human rights
activist stood in silence as the Professor of Poetry Peter Levi
described his work and words as a ``harbinger of glasnost.''
   Sustained applause rang through the Sheldonian Theatre for
several minutes as Sakharov received his degree from Chancellor Roy
Jenkins.
   Oxford also bestowed a doctorate of civil law on Queen Sofia of
Spain ``in appreciation of her hard and varied work for the Arts and
for Music''.
   Sakharov, accompanied by his wife, is on his first trip to
Britain. The 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner received an honorary
degree at Sussex University on Monday, and will meet Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher on Friday.
   The 68-year-old physicist was elected to the newly formed
Congress of the People's Deputies by the Soviet Academy of Sciences
in April, three years after he was freed from internal exile in the
city of Gorky. He had been sent there as punishment for his
dissident activities, including criticism of the Soviet military
intervention in Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
