<DOCNO> AP890621-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Tibet     06-21 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Tibet,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Tourists in Tibet Since Martial Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten tourists from West Germany and Switzerland
arrived in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa on Tuesday, the first tour
group to visit the city since martial law was imposed there March 7.
   The tourists, organized by a Swiss travel group, entered Tibet by
land from Nepal, according to the People's Daily.
   An employee at the Lhasa Hotel, who identified himself only as
Wang, said the group arrived Tuesday and would leave Saturday. He
said a second group was to arrive Sunday.
   Wang said a notice had been issued reopening Lhasa to tourist
groups, although individual tourists were still barred from entering
the city.
   In Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan province, a travel agency
employee said he had heard nothing on lifting the ban on tourist
travel to Lhasa. Chengdu is the jumping-off point for all flights to
the mountaintop city.
   China imposed martial law in Lhasa after several days of violent
anti-Chinese demonstrations, the third bloody outbreaks of rioting
in a 18-month period. All foreign travelers and journalists were
ordered out of the city.
   The government has not said how long the military will remain in
Lhasa.
   Tourism had become a major source of revenue for the impoverished
Tibetan area. In 1987, 40,000 foreign tourists spent $8 million in
Tibet.
</TEXT>
