<FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-US     06-21 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thailand-US,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai-U.S. Troops in Climax to War Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHAO NONG KHLO, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai jet fighters dropped bombs
and helicopter-borne U.S. infantrymen swooped down on imaginary
enemies Wednesday in the climax to this year's joint war games.
   About 400 U.S. troops and a like number of Thai soldiers took
part in a day of live fire exercises in hilly, forested countryside
about 200 miles northwest of Bangkok.
   The scenario in the ``Cobra Gold '89'' war games called for the
two sides to resist an enemy push and launch a counterattack with
the support of tanks, artillery and air strikes.
   A company from the 3rd Brigade of the U.S. 25th Infantry Division
was flown into attack position while jets and helicopter gunships
provided support.
   Both sides flew supersonic F-16 fighters, which Thailand has
acquired from the United States. Two Thai Air Force F-5 warplanes
dropped 500-pound bombs on a hillside.
   The exercise was watched by military attaches from the region and
Brig. Gen. Mya Thien of Burma.
   Burmese troops have recently intruded and fired weapons into
Thailand while fighting Karen rebels. The fighting continues along
the frontier just west of where the games were staged.
   ``Cobra Gold '89,'' the eighth in this annual series, began June
3 and has involved 6,000 Thai troops and 3,200 U.S. personnel,
including 2,000 from the Hawaii-based U.S. 25th Infantry Division.
   The United States, which based thousands of troops in Thailand
during the Vietnam War, is the country's key Western ally.
</TEXT>
