<FIRST>r w AM-HouseDemocrats     06-21 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Democrats,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoyer Elected to Democratic Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats on Wednesday elected Steny
Hoyer of Maryland to their fourth-ranking leadership post, filling
the last major vacancy left from the shake-up that began with the
ethics probe of Speaker Jim Wright.
   Hoyer, 50, defeated Rep. Barbara Kennelly, D-Ct., 165-82, for
chairman of the House Democratic Caucus. Two votes were cast for
others during the closed meeting of all House Democrats.
   Hoyer has served as deputy chairman of the caucus for six months.
   The caucus chairman has few official duties other than to preside
over party meetings, but the post has been a launching pad to higher
positions.
   Hoyer succeeds Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., who moved up to
majority whip last week. Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., resigned as
majority whip rather than face an inquiry into his personal finances.
   ``It's considered to be a major step in the leadership ladder of
the House of Representatives,'' said Speaker Thomas S. Foley,
D-Wash., himself a former caucus chairman.
   Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., the newly elected majority leader, is
also a former chairman.
   The election was part of the Democrats' ongoing effort to restore
their leadership ranks in the wake of ethics inquiries that led to
the resignation of Wright, D-Texas.
   Foley succeeded Wright, Gephardt took over for Foley and Gray
replaced Coelho..
   Wednesday's vote means the party still includes no women in its
top ranks.
   ``I thought it was time the Democratic Party had a woman's face
in the leadership,'' Kennelly said after her defeat.
   Hoyer, a liberal member in his fifth term, agreed.
   ``I'd like to see a woman in the leadership ... although I was
not prepared to drop out of the race,'' he said.
</TEXT>
