<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Railroads     06-21 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Railroads,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Eases Way for Railroad to Sell Off Lines Without Labor Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, by a 5-4 vote, today gave
railroads greater leeway to sell off rail lines without first
entering into collective bargaining about a sale's effects.
   The court, resolving one of the most critical issues facing the
nation's railroad industry, said the Pittsburgh &amp; Lake Erie
Railroad, or P&amp;LE, may sell its 182 miles of rail line in eastern
Ohio and western Pennsylvania without first negotiating with its
employees' unions.
   Interpreting the Railway Labor Act, a federal law governing the
railroad and airline industries, the court said the P&amp;LE was not
obligated to bargain over the effects of the sale, including lost
jobs.
   The P&amp;LE, having lost $60 million in the five previous years,
announced in 1987 that it had agreed to sell its trackage and other
assets for about $70 million to a newly formed subsidiary of the
Chicago West Pullman Transportation Corp.
   The subsidary intended to operate the railroad as the P&amp;LE had,
except that it would not assume the P&amp;LE's union contracts and would
lay off about 500 of the railroad's 750 employees.
   When the unions were notified of the sale, they challenged it as
a violation of the Railway Labor Act. The Interstate Commerce
Commission, however, approved the sale.
   A federal trial judge and the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled that the P&amp;LE was legally obligated to negotiate with its
unions about the sale's effects on the workforce.
   Today, the Supreme Court said the lower courts were wrong.
   After the sale was postponed, the P&amp;LE sought a new purchaser.
Today's decision also makes that pursuit easier.
   Writing for the high court, Justice Byron R. White said the P&amp;LE
was not obligated to postpone its sale of the trackage ``beyond the
time the sale was approved by the commission and was scheduled to be
consummated.''
   He added: ``To the extent that the unions' demands could be
satisfied only by the assent of the buyers, they sought to change or
dictate the terms of the sale, and in effect challenged the decision
to sell itself.
   ``At that time, P&amp;LE was under no obligation to bargain about the
terms it had already negotiated,'' White wrote.
   White was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   Justices John Paul Stevens, William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall
and Harry A. Blackmun dissented.
   But by a unanimous vote the court left unresolved _ and sent back
to the 3rd Circuit court for further study _ the related issue of
what authority federal courts have to block strikes in such cases.
   The cases are Pittsburgh &amp; Lake Erie Railroad vs. Railway Labor
Executives Association, 87-1859, and P&amp;LE vs. RLEA, 87-1888.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0120 </DOCNO>
