<FIRST>r p PM-MississippiElections 1stLd-Writethru a0533 06-21 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mississippi Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0533,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Blacks Win Judicial Races in Court-Ordered Mississippi Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD poll tax repealed; PICKS UP 6th graf
pvs, `The state's ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of six black candidates won judgeships
in elections ordered by a judge who said Mississippi's judicial
districts discriminated against blacks.
   Mississippi now has five blacks among its 78 judges, a gain of
one after Tuesday's elections. One incumbent lost.
   ``In spite of some black leaders' allegations that there is no
more discrimination in Mississippi, these election results are clear
indication that discrimination is alive and well in Mississippi and
will probably be around for some time to come,'' said attorney
Carrol Rhodes.
   Rhodes was one of the lawyers who represented blacks in a 1986
federal lawsuit that resulted in the redrawing of judicial districts
in Mississippi.
   ``Voting patterns along racial lines, if it has been changing,
it's becoming more pronounced,'' he said. ``It just shows that we
have a lot more work to do.''
   Mississippians on Tuesday also finally removed from the state
constitution an unenforcable poll tax that was enacted years ago to
keep blacks from voting but was struck down by the U.S. Supreme
Court in 1966.
   With 98 percent of the vote in, unofficial returns had 99,648
voting for repeal of the tax and 72,844 against repeal.
   The state's four black judges are Supreme Court Justice Reuben
Anderson, Circuit Judges Fred L. Banks Jr. and Lillie
Blackmon-Sanders and Chancery Judge Isaac Byrd.
   Each was appointed to fill a vacancy, but Anderson went on to win
a full eight-year term in 1986; he was not up for election Tuesday.
Byrd did not seek election, Banks was unopposed and Blackmon-Sanders
was challenged.
   Blackmon-Sanders lost to Republican challenger Richard Watson,
12,878 votes to 9,600. One other black Democrat, Isadore W. Patrick
of Vicksburg, was unopposed in the general election.
   The two black winners in contested races were Pat Wise, a
Democrat, who defeated Republican Billy W. Keyes for an open Hinds
County chancery judge's post, 5,942 votes to 1,638; and Denise Sweet
Owens, also a Democrat, who defeated Republican George M. Arthur in
another open family court post, 4,628 votes to 1,259.
   Black candidates Solomon Curtis Osborne, Clell G. Ward and Harold
Brittain all lost to incumbents.
   ``I am disappointed with the situation as it now exists outside
of Jackson,'' said former state Sen. Henry Kirksey of Jackson, one
of the plaintiffs in the lawsuit that resulted in the redistricting.
Jackson is the county seat of Hinds County and the state capital.
   Kirksey said the voting vindicated his complaints about the
redrawing of some of the districts. He also said there wasn't enough
time to persuade black voters to cast ballots only for black
candidates.
   U.S. District Judge William H. Barbour Jr. ruled in 1987 that
Mississippi's judicial districts discriminated against blacks. The
ruling, the first to apply the 1965 Voting Rights Act to judicial
elections, was upheld on appeal.
   Barbour ordered some districts redrawn to create minority
subdistricts so that black voters would have a better opportunity to
elect black judges.
   Sixteen elections were contested Tuesday. Those elected will take
office on July 3.
</TEXT>
