<FIRST>r a PM-PennwaltCase     06-21 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt Case,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Demands Polluter's `Top Man'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today refused to accept a
guilty plea from a company indicted for water pollution, demanding
Pennwalt Corp. send its ``top man'' rather than the three executives
it flew in from Philadelphia.
   The case involved a 1985 spill into Tacoma's Hylebos Waterway in
which at least 75,000 gallons of a cancer-causing chemical escaped
from a ruptured 180,000-gallon storage tank that had been poorly
maintained.
   An undetermined amount of the chemical reached the waterway in an
overflow last year.
   In a plea bargain, Pennwalt agreed to pay $1.1 million for the
spills.
   ``Before I accept this plan the top officer of your company will
be here. Not a division; the top man,'' U.S. District Judge Jack
Tanner told Pennwalt senior vice president Marty Schwartzberg.
   In addition to Schwartzberg, Pennwalt sent a senior vice
president for legal matters and president of the company's inorganic
chemical division.
   Tanner had told attorneys in May that he would not accept the
plea unless a Pennwalt executive was present, but he didn't specify
which executive.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Marshall told the judge that he was
satisfied that Schwartzberg and another of the executives ``are very
high in this company and should be able to answer any questions the
court has.''
   Pennwalt lawyer Tom Kelly argued it was very unusual to compel
executives to appear in such cases. Usually, a company pleads
through its attorneys.
   ``People in this company have had deterrence imprinted on their
memory through this investigation,'' Kelly said. ``There will be
deterrence here, your honor.''
   Tanner, however, cited statistics indicating Washington ranks
second in the country in the number of such reported pollution
violations.
   ``Apparently deterrence is not being very effective,'' he said.
   The judge rescheduled the plea hearing for July 19.
</TEXT>
