<FIRST>r a AM-GuardPilot     06-21 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guard Pilot,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Guard Pilot Medically Unfit to Fly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indiana Air National Guard pilot
killed during an emergency landing after he blacked out would have
been grounded if officials had known he had high blood pressure, a
National Guard Bureau report says.
   First Lt. David E. Kruse had lied to flight surgeons, concealing
his medical problems for years, so he could fly F-4E Phantom
fighters assigned to the 122nd Tactical Fighter Wing at Baer Field,
said the report released Tuesday in Washington.
   ``Had the military medical staff been aware of the extent of
Kruse's civilian medical problems, he could never have been
medically qualified for flying duty,'' investigators said.
   Medical report forms indicate Kruse hid his blood pressure
problems from military doctors even though he had been a patient at
the Hypertension Research Center at Indiana University Medical
Center.
   Kruse fainted after shoveling snow Dec. 27, 1988, and his doctor
advised him to tell a flight surgeon about the blackouts, the report
said.
   Adj. Gen. Jack K. Elrod of the Indiana National Guard has ordered
flight surgeons to review the medical records of all flying
personnel.
   Kruse, 26, of Fort Wayne, blacked out about 10 minutes after
declaring an emergency and smoke in the cockpit during a Feb. 10
night training flight. He was about eight miles from the runway when
he lost consciousness.
   Maj. Wilburt J. Elliott, 39, the weapons systems officer, took
control from the jet's rear seat and landed. However, the plane
swerved off the runway, damaging the nose gear and activating an
automatic ejection system.
   An autopsy by Allen County Coroner Philip E. O'Shaughnessy found
Kruse suffered a broken neck, back and legs and internal bleeding,
all of which were enough to kill him.
   The autopsy showed no signs of smoke inhalation.
   ``We don't know why he passed out,'' said Chief Deputy Coroner
Robert Cummins. ``He was ejected, and then that's when he suffered
the injuries, naturally.''
   Cummins, who stressed he is not a doctor, said Kruse could have
passed out for any number of reasons. ``There's so many things that
could have caused that. Something wrong with the plane, the oxygen
in the plane ... but certainly the high blood pressure may have been
a factor,'' he said.
   Elliott, who also was ejected, suffered minor injuries.
   The report concluded the emergency Kruse reported involved a
hydraulic problem that corrected itself before he blacked out. The
cause of the cockpit smoke was not given.
</TEXT>
