<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Mafia     06-21 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Mafia,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Found Near Anti-Mafia Judge's Villa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday foiled an apparent
attempt to kill Italy's most celebrated Mafia fighter when they
discovered a bomb near his villa, news reports said.
   Security forces assigned to protect Judge Giovanni Falcone
reportedly found 44 pounds of plastic explosives stuffed inside a
waterproof bag.
   The guards, part of a 24-hour security detail, noticed the bag on
a sunbathing platform at the edge of the sea, about 20 yards from
the villa. The bag was the type used by divers to store their gear.
   Experts blew up the bomb.
   The Italian news agencies ANSA and AGI quoted explosives experts
who examined the bomb as saying it was clearly meant to kill the
judge or his family, who frequently went for swims in the morning.
   News agencies said investigators theorized that the potential
assassins had set up a surveillance base either in one of the nearby
villas or in a boat offshore. They theorized the bomb would have
been set off when Falcone went down the walk leading to the sea.
   When the bomb was discovered, Falcone was about to leave the
villa for a morning workout at a health club. His guards rushed him
instead to his heavily guarded office in Palermo's Palace of
Justice. It was not reported whether other members of his family
were home at the time.
   Falcone's investigations of the Mafia have led to hundreds of
convictions. He reportedly receives frequent threats, and his
security precautions are among the tightest in Italy.
   For his summer stay at the villa, guards have been stationed
along the road that runs above the villa, and police motor launches
periodically patrol offshore.
   Mafia members who turned informants have reportedly said that
Falcone is the top target of the organization.
</TEXT>
