<FIRST>r a PM-BrushFires 3rdLd-Writethru a0574 06-21 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brush Fires, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0574,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Conquer Calif. Blazes; Rain Helps in Fla.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Joshua Tree fire contained,
CORRECTS acreage to 935 sted 1,200; PICKS UP graf pvs, `One outbuilding
...'; SUBS last graf to UPDATE with another fire contained.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters laboring in 100-degree-plus heat today contained a
desert wildfire near the grotesquely shaped trees of California's
Joshua Tree Monument. In Florida, rain helped crews battling a blaze
in the dry Everglades.
   The 935-acre blaze in the desert raged within 1,000 feet of homes
and was the largest of four fires that burned 1,500 acres in
Southern California before being contained.
   A predicted high of 118 degrees, brittle vegetation and
capricious winds were expected to keep 375 firefighters on the fire
lines all day.
   One firefighter suffered burns on the face, said state Forestry
Department spokeswoman Deborah McClellan.
   The fire burned away from the Joshua Tree monument, a rugged area
named for the trees with dagger-shaped leaves and branches like
upraised arms. The Joshua Tree is common to the Southwest.
   The fire started Tuesday, prompting authorities to order the
evacuation of 85 homes as flames bore down on a neighborhood in the
city of Joshua Tree. But the fire was stopped short of the houses,
and most people had returned by late in the day.
   ``The residents had cleared the brush around their homes and if
it hadn't been for that clearance the homes would definitely have
burned,'' said McClellan.
   One outbuilding was destroyed in the sparsely populated area 110
miles east of Los Angeles.
   In Florida, rain brought firefighters closer to putting out a
wildfire that has scorched 43,700 acres of the Everglades. Nearly
400 firefighters from at least seven states battled the blaze, which
has been fed by wind and dry grass.
   ``If things work like they're working now, I'd say two to three
days,'' information officer Sam Logan said Tuesday. ``If all of a
sudden it dries up and we get some crazy winds, it could do
something else.''
   The area is so dry that alligators have abandoned secluded
marshes in the Arthur R. Marshall Loxahatchee National Wildlife
Refuge, Florida's largest, for a canal on its rim. As a result, the
refuge has been closed to boaters and fishermen.
   In California, a 175-acre brush fire in the hills above San
Clemente was contained at 8 a.m., and firefighters earlier doused a
300-acre blaze in the Newbury Park area of Ventura County and a
115-acre fire in San Bernardino County's Devore area.
</TEXT>
