<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-China 5thLd-Writethru a0616 06-21 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0616,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Regrets Executions, But Won't Add Sanctions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 6 grafs of Fitzwater comment after 8th graf, Hours after;
deletes last 6 grafs to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States deeply regrets China's
execution of three men in the crackdown on pro-democracy forces, but
the administration is not considering additional sanctions against
Beijing, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said today.
   ``There is an important relationship which we should seek to
preserve if we possibly can,'' Baker told reporters. ``That is a
consideration that must be taken on board when we consider what
specific actions'' should be taken.
   Baker spoke with reporters outside the White House as he
accompanied visiting West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher to a luncheon.
   ``We deeply regret the fact that these executions have gone
forward, notwithstanding appeals from the United States, appeals
from the Federal Republic of Germany and perhaps other countries,
for clemency,'' Baker said.
   Asked whether the United States would impose additional sanctions
in retaliation for the executions in Shanghai, he said: ``The United
States is not contemplating any additional action at this time.''
   Baker said President Bush believes that sanctions already in
place are the proper response to the bloody crackdown in China and
the arrests of more than 1,600 pro-democracy demonstrators. Eight
protesters in Beijing also have been condemned to die.
   Tightening diplomatic and financial pressure on China, Bush took
steps Tuesday to block at least $1.4 billion in development loans
while he said China is gripped by an ``atmosphere of suspicion and
reprisal.''
   Hours after the U.S. actions were announced, Chinese authorities
in Shanghai ignored the international pleas for clemency and shot to
death the three men, who had been convicted of setting a train on
fire. They were the first reported executions since the crackdown
began.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged today that
China has not been influenced by the United States or other nations.
   ``The weight of world opinion has been heavy on the shoulders of
China and it does not appear to have made much difference,'' he
said, adding that ``history has shown that they generally are not
that responsive to outside kinds of pleas.''
   Fitzwater said the United States could not afford to turn its
back on China even though it deplores what is happening there.
   ``Everyone has to recognize, first of all, that this is a country
of a billion people ... a sizeable portion of the world's population
that cannot be closeted off and ignored,'' he said.
   Moreover, he said China plays an important role in regional
conflicts, such as Afghanistan, Cambodia and the Iran-Iraq war, and
also is a nuclear power that possesses ballistic missiles.
   ``It's important that we have some perspective in viewing the
overall, longterm relationship with China and that we believe we
have tried to strike the right balance,'' Fitzwater said.
   Genscher, at a picture-taking session with the president, was
asked his reaction to the executions.
   ``We are condemning the brutal ...,'' Genscher began. His comment
was interrupted by a White House aide who shouted an order that
ended the photo session. Bush made no comment.
   On Bush's orders, the United States will try to postpone
consideration of new loans to China by international financial
institutions.
   One administration source said the action could freeze $1.4
billion over the next six months from the World Bank and
International Development Bank. Other estimates indicated the figure
could be even higher.
   Bush also curtailed contacts by U.S. officials with their Chinese
counterparts, ordering a suspension of all high-level exchanges of
government officials with Beijing.
   While not affecting embassy-to-embassy contacts, it will force
Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher to scrap a trip to China next
month, Baker said.
   ``This action is being taken in response to the wave of violence
and reprisals by the Chinese authorities against those who have
called for democracy,'' White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said.
   ``The U.S. hopes that the current tragedy in China can be brought
to a peaceful end and that dialogue will replace the atmosphere of
suspicion and reprisal,'' Fitzwater said. ``China is an important
state with which we hope to continue productive relations.''
   The latest action follows earlier orders for a freeze on military
sales to China and a suspension of contacts by military leaders.
   With the repression in China, Bush has been prodded by
conservative and liberal members of Congress alike to take tougher
action, such as withdrawing most-favored-nation trading privileges
from Beijing.
   The administration has argued that China is impervious to
pressure from the United States, and Bush has said he wants to
refrain from commercial sanctions that would hurt the Chinese people.
   Congressional Del. Walter Fauntroy, D-D.C., said at a House
Banking subcommittee hearing prior to Bush's action that China has
$4.7 billion in loans ``pending or in the pipeline'' at the World
Bank and $1.1 billion being processed by the Asian Development Bank.
The White House statement said Bush's action was aimed at new loans
to China, so it was unclear how much money was involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
