<NOTE>Eds: A version moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After losing millions of dollars he made in the
ring, former boxing champion Leon Spinks is making a new start on
Chicago Bears Coach Mike Ditka's team _ Ditka's Restaurant team.
   The ex-fighter is a greeter and goodwill ambassador at the
restaurant, partly owned by the coach.
   ``I'm enjoying the people and the people are enjoying me,'' said
Spinks, an Olympic gold medal winner who shocked the boxing world
when he took the heavyweight crown in his eighth professional fight
from Muhammad Ali in 1978. Ali regained the championship seven
months later. Spinks, 35, retired last year.
   ``I've had my lumps and bumps, but now I've got my life on a roll
again,'' he said Tuesday.
   Spinks wouldn't say how much Ditka is paying him to mingle with
customers and represent the restaurant at charity events and other
occasions, but one report put it at $50,000 to $70,000 a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Ernest Borgnine, making an appearance
to promote teacher-training to help students avoid drugs, said such
a program is only one part of a battle he believes society must
fight on all fronts.
   ``The whole mess is getting the dealers. I'd say let's start
hanging them,'' said Borgnine, often portrayed as a heavy in movies.
   He appeared on behalf of the National Masonic Foundation for the
Prevention of Drug and Alcohol Abuse Among Children. The Masons are
contributing about $24,000 toward a state program to train 150
teachers each summer to identify students who may be abusing drugs
and find services to help them.
   The 72-year-old actor said, in response to questions, he may have
worked with people who used drugs in Hollywood, but added, ``It's no
more prevalent than it is in Peoria or Kansas or anywhere else.''
</TEXT>
