<FIRST>r i AM-China-Philippines     06-21 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Philippines,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>18 Chinese Want Asylum in Taiwan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen Chinese refugees who arrived
in the Philippines by boat have asked for asylum in Taiwan because
they are afraid to return to their homeland, officials said
Wednesday.
   Immigration Chief Miriam Defensor Santiago said the 16 men and
two women would be turned over to the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees to determine whether they can be classified as political
refugees.
   Ms. Santiago said the group, mostly fishermen, left the southern
Chinese province of Guangdong on April 29 and reached the northern
Philippines on May 3, a month before Chinese troops dispersed
pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing. They were brought to Manila
June 13, Ms. Santiago said.
   They apparently left China ``because they anticipated that
trouble was brewing ... that there was going to be political
commotion in the next few months,'' Ms. Santiago said.
   ``And at the same time, they left because of a desire to enhance
their economic status,'' she added. ``According to the affidavits
taken, they do not wish to return to mainland China. They are afraid
that they will be punished or killed by authorities in the mainland.
They wish to go to Taiwan because they think that there are better
job prospects there.''
   Seven of the 18 refugees went before reporters at Ms. Santiago's
office. The others were being held at the headquarters of the
Philippine army.
   When reporters asked why the refugees were afraid to return home,
one of them, Lim Niet Nee, replied: ``Because we will be killed.''
   ``We want to go to Taiwan or any other place other than China,''
Lim said through an interpreter.
   Karola Paul, deputy representative of the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees, said U.N. officials would interview the group and
consult with U.N. officials before deciding whether to certify them
as political refugees.
   In Taiwan, Liao Cheng-hao, deputy director of the Government
Information Office, said the Nationalist government would not accept
the 18 Chinese until they are confirmed to be political refugees and
not just people looking for a better life.
   Ms. Paul said the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees advised its
regional offices on June 12 to expect a possible exodus of Chinese
refugees from the mainland following the June 3-4 crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing.
</TEXT>
