<FIRST>r w AM-HongKongVisas     06-21 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong Visas,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Apply for Temporary Visas at Accelerating Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nervous about falling under Chinese control,
residents of Hong Kong are applying for temporary visas to the
United States at an accelerating rate.
   But most of those wanting to move permanently from the world's
third-largest financial trading center are looking to other
countries.
   Last year, applications for non-immigrant _ or temporary _ visas
to visit the United States averaged 650 a day. Since Chinese troops
fired on pro-democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen Square June 3-4,
the daily total has risen above 1,000, the State Department said
Wednesday.
   There were no figures available on permanent immigration, but a
department official said other countries were preferred because U.S.
law restricts entry to aliens with close family ties to Americans,
occupations in demand here, or other specific qualifications. Other
countries are more lenient.
   Telephone calls for information to the U.S. consulate in Hong
Kong have increased, but most Hong Kong residents are well aware of
the U.S. rules, the official said.
   Britain's 99-year lease on Hong Kong expires in 1997 under terms
worked out with the Chinese in 1984. The agreement specifies that
Hong Kong would retain its status as an intenrational financial
center.
   The U.S. consulate reported to the State Department that
residents were ``nervous about coming under PRC (People's Republic
of China) sovereignty and they have responded with an unprecedented
demand for foreign visas,'' said an official, declining to be quoted
by name. ``We're not getting the bulk of them.''
   Last year, Congress reserved 4,800 visas for wealthy immigrants
from Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
