<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GayScholarship     06-21 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Scholarship,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Man's Death Spurs Unique Scholarship for Homosexual Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALNUT CREEK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man's suicide in despair over
his homosexuality has led to a college scholarship in his memory,
and changed his mother's fundamentalist views.
   The $500 scholarship in memory of Bobby Griffith will be offered
beginning next year in Contra Costa County, site of an acrimonious
struggle between fundamentalists and homosexuals. It is intended to
encourage and give a sense of caring to gay students facing
prejudice and hostility, according to the organization that created
the gift.
   ``What we are saying to gay students is there is a (gay)
community out there and we care about you,'' said Rob Birle, an
Antioch High School teacher and chairman of the Contra Costa County
chapter of the Bay Area Network of Gay and Lesbian Educators.
   The scholarship, funded by donations, will be open to
heterosexual students, though preference will be given to
homosexuals.
   ``I don't know why nobody ever thought of this before,'' Birle
said. ``There are scholarships for Italians, Catholics, Hispanics
and every other kind of minority _ so why not for homosexuals?''
   Birle said he could find no similar scholarships around the
country, and the California Teachers Association said it never heard
of one, either.
   So far, 21 of the county's 23 high schools have agreed to include
the scholarship in the list they offer students.
   Opposition is expected from the Anaheim-based Stop Homosexual
Advocacy in Education group, which for more than a year has actively
opposed school programs in Contra Costa that portray homosexuality
positively.
   But the Anaheim group's activities, and Bobby's death, prompted
his mother, Mary Griffith, to give her blessing when Birle asked if
she would support the scholarship.
   ``I really believed God would come to Bobby's rescue. And when he
didn't, I had to rethink everything,'' she said Monday.
   Mrs. Griffith was initially horrified by her son's homosexuality,
which she learned of when he was 16. Within a year of his death,
Mrs. Griffith quit her church. She now is president of the Diablo
Valley Chapter of Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays.
   Depressed over his family and friends' disapproval, Bobby
Griffith dropped out of high school two months before he was to
graduate in 1981. He killed himself Aug. 27, 1983, in Portland, Ore.

</TEXT>
