<FIRST>r i AM-HeathrowSecurity     06-21 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heathrow Security,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists to be Restricted at Heathrow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heathrow Airport authorities are withdrawing 180
press passes to improve security in the wake of the bombing of Pan
Am Flight 103 in December.
   As of July 31, reporters, photographers and camera crews will be
barred from large areas of the airport where they had traditionally
been permitted access.
   Heathrow Airport Ltd., the airport authority, said access
generally will be restricted to essential personnel.
   ``The reason for the withdrawals is that fewer numbers means
fewer people that have to be ... searched, questioned or monitored
and greater attention can be focused on those who are airside,''
said airport spokesman Garry May. ``It is not a review of media
passes but a review of all passes.''
   May said the restrictions had nothing to do with stories
questioning airport security written by reporters who had gotten
jobs as aircraft cleaners after only minimal security checks.
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth. The question is only
one of security. It has nothing whatsoever to do with press
activities at this airport before Lockerbie or after Lockerbie,'' he
said.
   A bomb hidden inside a radio-cassette player exploded over
Scotland, killing all 259 aboard and 11 residents of Lockerbie.
</TEXT>
