<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-China-Loans     06-21 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China-Loans,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank Paying Out Old Loans to China; New Loans Blocked June
8</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank suspended new loans to China two
weeks ago after the bloody crackdown on demonstrators by Chinese
troops, though the bank is still paying out money on previous loans,
a spokesman said Wednesday.
   President Bush promised on Tuesday that the U.S. government would
use its voting power in the World Bank and other international
lending institutions to try to prevent new loans to China.
   Frank Vogl, chief spokesman for the bank, said that new loans
were suspended on June 8 and all but one of the bank's eight staff
members were pulled out of Beijing although some have returned.
   Sheldon Rappaport, the bank's financial spokesman, estimated that
on March 31 about $4.4 billion worth of approved loans to China had
not yet been disbursed.
   Bank President Barber Conable, a former New York congressman,
decided on June 8, shortly after the Chinese crackdown, not to
submit new loans for final approval to the 22-member Board of
Executive Directors, which meets every week in closed-door session,
representing 151 member governments.
   As the biggest shareholder, the U.S. government has just over 18
percent of the voting power and strong influence over many other
members.
   Shahid Burki, a Pakistani who heads the bank's China desk, is due
back at the bank's Washington headquarters from Beijing on Monday
with a report for Conable and the board.
   ``If economic chaos or some other reason was preventing a loan
for irrigation from being properly spent, for example, we would not
want to keep putting out the money,'' Vogl said in an interview.
   The bank lends $2 billion to $2.5 billion a year to China, the
third-largest borrower after India and Mexico.
   Pastor Sison, spokesman on Asia, calculated that $780 million
worth of new lending for China was due for approval by the board
before the bank's fiscal year ends June 30.
   The bank is planning to lend $20 billion to $21 billion this year
to over 100 Third World countries. The usual rush is on to complete
this program by the end of the fiscal year and the board has
scheduled three meetings next week.
   Sison said it would be hard to transfer to other borrowers the
amounts designated for China.
   A spokesman at the International Monetary Fund, the bank's sister
organization, said it has no loans pending or being disbursed to
China. China does get loans from the Asian Development Bank, an
international body with headquarters in Manila.
</TEXT>
