<DOCNO> AP890621-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NoStateMoney Bjt   06-21 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-No State Money, Bjt,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embarrassed Arkansas Lawmakers Scramble to Avert Fiscal Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red-faced legislators met in an
emergency special session Wednesday to re-pass hundreds of spending
bills that were ruled invalid because the Legislature violated a
requirement in the state's constitution.
   Virtually all state spending will halt July 1, when Arkansas'
fiscal biennium begins, unless the legislators approve nearly 300
appropriations bills all over again.
   ``I am embarrassed,'' veteran state Rep. Jodie Mahony said of the
procedural snafu during the regular session, which ended in April.
``But it is an honest mistake.''
   The special session convened late Tuesday, one day after a
specially appointed Arkansas Supreme Court ruled that the General
Appropriation Act did not pass with a three-fourths majority as
required by the state's 115-year-old constitution.
   Since the General Appropriation Act must be passed before any
other spending bills may be enacted, the ruling meant the state had
not authorized a spending blueprint.
   ``The fact that our state constitution is an amalgamation of
anachronisms is no justification to ignore it,'' Arkansas Gazette
columnist John Brummett wrote Wednesday.
   During the regular legislative session, the general appropriation
bill got a 65-22 vote in the 100-member House, and a 25-9 vote in
the 35-member Senate, where 27 votes equals three-fourths.
   The House, and later a Senate Rules Committee, decided that the
general appropriation bill fell under the category of ``just
debts,'' which the constitution says is exempt from the
three-quarters rule.
   A Little Rock attorney, Sam Perroni, then filed a friendly
lawsuit challenging the General Appropriation Act's validity.
   When a Pulaski County chancellor rejected the ``just debts''
argument in ruling the appropriation act invalid, the issue went to
the state Supreme Court. However, the seven justices recused
themselves, citing a possible conflict of interest because the
legislature appropriates funds for the high court.
   A special seven-member Supreme Court was appointed that also
rejected the ``just debts'' argument, so on Monday night, Gov. Bill
Clinton's staff began rounding up lawmakers to return to Little Rock.
   The only legislators missing from the special session were a
House member who was sick and another who was out of the country.
The constitution requires that all special sessions meet for at
least three days, and Clinton said he hoped lawmakers could wrap up
things Thursday or Friday.
   To show his desire for no-nonsense action, Clinton decided
against an opening speech for the session, which is costing
taxpayers an estimated $20,000 a day.
   ``I want to do it as quickly as possible, keep it to this agenda
and finish,'' the governor said.
   Once in session, lawmakers hastily assigned bill numbers and gave
the familiar items two readings, dispatching them to the Joint
Budget Committee, where the panel's co-chairman, Rep. John E.
Miller, pressured colleagues to grind out all spending bills in a
two-hour sitting.
   ``Understand, this is a re-hash, the same thing, and all of us
know what we have done,'' Miller said. ``We're showing we're not
derelict in our duties.''
   ``It's just unfortunate we are not as good constitutional lawyers
as the Supreme Court,'' said Rep. Mike Wilson, a lawyer. ``But I
know there was a general good faith belief that it was properly
passed.''
   The court ruling also invalidated an unpopular $119 million,
10-year settlement of state liability in desegregation lawsuits
surrounding schools in Little Rock's Pulaski County. The settlement
passed by a narrow margin the first time around, and opponents say
they won't let it pass again.
   Sen. Stanley Russ, a member of the Joint Budget Committee, which
recommended the settlement bill for passage Wednesday, predicted the
bill would pass the Senate but die in the House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
