<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Steel     06-21 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Steel,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Meets with Lawmakers on Steel Import Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of steel import restraints told
President Bush on Wednesday that he should not feel bound by a
campaign pledge to renew the trade barriers.
   ``(Winston) Churchill used to say, `I'd rather be right than be
consistent,' and I reminded the president of that,'' Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, told reporters after the meeting at the White House
regarding the import curbs that expire Sept. 30.
   Bush met privately with lawmakers who favor extending the trade
program and with Gramm and others who are urging it be dropped.
   Bush ``tipped his hand in no direction whatsoever,'' said Sen.
Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., chairman of the Senate Steel Caucus.
   The Reagan administration negotiated five-year,
product-by-product ``voluntary restraint agreements'' in 1984 with
Japan, South Korea, the European Community, Brazil and other nations
to limit the flow of foreign steel into the United States.
   Three days before last November's election, Bush wrote a letter
to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., pledging to renew the program in some
form. But with the steel industry newly profitable, opponents of the
curbs say they can make a case for Bush to end the barriers or at
least narrow their scope.
   ``We'd like to think his normal inclination would be on the side
of fewer barriers,'' Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., told reporters after
the meeting. ``What he's going to do with that statement that he
made in Pennsylvania toward the end of the campaign, I don't know.
But I suppose I could live with a compromise.''
   ``Everything is different than it was in 1984,'' Gramm said.
``The industry is operating at 96 percent of capacity, steel prices
are rising very rapidly now, especially for the smaller fabricators
who do not have long-term agreements with the domestic steel
industry. The steel industry is profitable.''
   Advocates of continuing the program argue that steel price hikes
have been caused not by import barriers but by strong worldwide
demand and shifting exchange rates.
   The trade conditions that spawned the restraint program still
exist, Rockefeller said.
   ``America is playing by the right rules and everybody else is
playing by protectionism, and we get hurt,'' Rockefeller said.
   He said the program must be extended ``so the steel industry can
complete about another $10 billion of modernization that they have
to complete in order to be competitive with the rest of world, which
is already subsidizing and dumping in United States.''
   The administration has not said when a decision will be made, but
Heinz said he expected something in the next several weeks. Heinz
and Rockefeller said they attended the meeting on behalf of steel
companies and steelworkers pressing for a five-year renewal of the
program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
