<FIRST>r p PM-Pepper'sSeat     06-21 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepper's Seat,0133</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixteen Qualify for Aug. 1 Primary to Fill Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political battle royal has begun in
South Florida's 18th congressional district as 16 candidates vie for
the seat once held by Claude Pepper.
   Nine Democrats were among those who met Tuesday's filing deadline
for the Aug. 1 primary, including Pepper's niece, JoAnne Pepper, a
probation officer; City Commissioner Rosario Kennedy of Miami;
Gerald Richman, a lawyer and former president of the Florida Bar,
and banker Raul Masvidal.
   The four Republican candidates include state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen and businessman Carlos Perez.
   Three others entered as write-in candidates.
   Pepper, a liberal Democrat who died May 30, held the seat since
its inception in 1962, despite the district's increasingly
conservative, Hispanic makeup. Republicans hold a 10-8 edge in
Florida's House delegation.
</TEXT>
