<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     06-21 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Hit Palestinian Base; Kill 1, Wound 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Ppress Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAAMEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes destroyed the
headquarters of a dissident Palestinian guerrilla faction Wednesday,
and the guerrillas reported one fighter killed and six wounded.
   Palls of dust and smoke billowed from the oak woods around
Naameh, 10 miles south of Beirut, as guerrillas opened up with
anti-aircraft guns on fighter-bombers that dived from clear skies.
   The jets released scarlet balloons to deflect heat-seeking
missiles.
   Guerrillas launched one SA-7, but the Soviet-made projectile
missed its target.
   Police said four warplanes struck two positions of the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command in the bluffs
of Naameh.
   A police spokesman said eight guerrillas were wounded.
   A statement from the guerrillas' headquarters in Damascus
reported one guerrilla killed and six wounded.
   It said the raid lasted 105 minutes, during which nine formations
of U.S.-built F-4 Phantom and Skyhawk bombers dropped more than 100
rockets.
   The statement said guerrillas prevented several attempts to land
airborne and seaborne commandos in the area, where they maintain
bases in a chain of tunnels across the Naameh hills.
   Israeli gunboats were cruising the Mediterranean and two
helicopter gunships hovered over the beaches, but reporters saw no
attempt to land troops.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army said its planes returned safely
from an attack on targets that ``served as the headquarters for
Ahmed Jibril.''
   It was the third air raid on Lebanon this week and the ninth this
year.
   On Friday, Israeli warplanes bombed south Lebanon's Rashidiyeh
refugee camp, wounding two children.
   By police count, nine people have been killed and 60 wounded in
the eight other air strikes.
   Jibril, a former Syrian army captain, is leader of the
Libyan-financed faction that has been at odds with Yasser Arafat's
mainstream Palestine Liberation Organization for six years.
   Another guerrilla group, George Habash's Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, said its Naameh base was hit, but gave no
details of damage or casualties.
   Habash's organization, the second-largest of the nine PLO
factions after Arafat's Fatah, pledged in a statement to ``continue
the painful raids against the Zionist enemy.''
   The Lebanese spokesman could confirm only the hits on Jibril's
bases.
   He said four of the rockets struck the entrance to a tunnel and
10 others devastated a base near a deserted monastery.
   A Palestinian guerrilla source said on condition of anonymity
that the attack ``inflicted severe damage on the base near the
monastery, but the tunnel was not affected.''
   The base is only 500 yards east of the highway linking Beirut
with south Lebanon.
   Panicking motorists deserted their vehicles and ran for cover in
banana groves. Swimmers hurried to a nearby motel.
   But Naameh residents, accustomed to Israeli attacks, climbed to
rooftops to watch the planes.
   Lebanese militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt blocked roads
and fired automatic rifles in the air to keep reporters and
photographers from stricken targets.
   The Naameh bluffs were the scene of a nine-hour confrontation
between Jibril's fighters and Israeli air, naval and ground forces
Dec. 9. Eight guerrillas and an Israeli officer were killed.
   Jibril said after that battle the helicopter-borne paratroopers
released dogs fitted with tear gas containers and explosives to
chase his fighters across the tunnels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
