<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-21 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLARKSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To be frank, pun-haters should skip this
news item: The Oscar Mayer Weiner Mobile, a 23-foot-long hot dog on
wheels, broke down Tuesday on promotional visit to Clarksburg.
   Driver Mike Culver blamed an overheated radiator.
   ``We certainly had a `hot dog,' if you don't mind the
expression,'' said Culver. ``But we got it all taken care of ... so
now I guess you could say we have a `chili dog.'''
   The mobile has been touring America in one form or another since
1936, and was even stolen once. It was recovered the next day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick McLynn's new car is a cream puff,
but when fully armed, it has retractable armor, concealed machine
guns, explosive charges in the wheel hubs and remote voice-activated
controls. All he needs is a Bat Cave to park it in.
   McLynn, an engineering student whose goal is to become a toy
designer, won an MTV giveaway of the Batmobile used in the movie
``Batman.'' He is to collect his prize at a theater Friday from
actor Robert Wuhl, who plays a reporter in the movie.
   McLynn is working his way through Virginia Commonwealth
University by tending bar part time and doesn't own a car, but he's
not sure what he'll do with the Batmobile.
   It's 20 feet long and more than 11 feet wide, and the engine has
been removed for safety reasons.
   ``The car was the real prop used in the picture. But its motor
was too heavy, the ratio wasn't according to regulations. It has
only been driven by stunt men,'' said Greg Drebin, an MTV publicist.
   Luckily for McLynn, the prize also includes $25,000 for bat-gas.
He said he will invest the money in certificates of deposit and use
the interest to buy a motorcycle.
</TEXT>
