<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SubAccident     06-21 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sub Accident,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sub's Sonar Sub Didn't Spot Tugboat, Investigator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear submarine that snagged a
towing cable and dragged a tugboat under, killing a deckhand, had
failed to detect the 97-ton vessel by sonar, a federal investigator
says.
   The analysis by National Transportation Safety Board investigator
Donald Tyrell is based on interviews with the crew of the USS
Houston after the accident June 14.
   Tyrell, in an interview in Wednesday's Long Beach Press-Telegram,
said the tug's engine noises may have been masked by the sounds of
larger ships in the area, or the sub may have been in a spot where
it couldn't pick up the tug's sounds.
   Requests for Navy comment were referred to Lt. Sonja Hedley at
the sub's home port in San Diego, and she wasn't immediately
available.
   According to Tyrell, the 360-foot sub was relying on ``passive''
sonar, which allows tracking of vessels by engine and other noises.
This is normal for military subs, Tyrell said, noting that active
sonar, which emits ``pings'' that bounce back and locate vessels
more accurately, give away a sub's position.
   The Houston snagged the submerged cable linking the 73-foot tug
to two barges. Two crewmen swam to safety in the early-morning fog,
but a deckhand was lost.
   Shortly before the accident, the sub had helped in filming of the
movie ``The Hunt for Red October.''
 
</TEXT>
