<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChildMurders     06-21 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Murders,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prepare New Drive for Wayne Williams in Atlanta Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a decade after the first of the ``child
murder'' victims was found, lawyers for Wayne Williams are headed
back to court to try to show that the Ku Klux Klan, not Williams,
was responsible for the deaths.
   From July 1979 to May 1981, 29 poor, generally street-wise young
blacks were found killed in and around Atlanta. One other is missing.
   Williams, now 30, was convicted in 1982 of two of the deaths and
is serving two life sentences. Authorities attributed 22 other
killings to him. The other cases remain classified as unsolved.
   New York civil rights lawyer William Kuntsler said he and others
working on Williams' case will meet Tuesday in Atlanta to organize
what he called ``the final thrust'' of their appeal and to request a
new evidentiary hearing.
   ``We've been collecting more and more information, all of which
points to Wayne's innocence,'' he said Wednesday from his New York
office.
   The prosecution has contended since Williams was convicted that
the evidence points to him and to nobody else. But doubt has
remained in the minds of many, including the parents of some
victims, over whether Williams was behind all of the killings or
acted alone.
   The Georgia Supreme Court unanimously rejected an initial appeal
of Williams' conviction in 1983 and later voted 6-1 not to
reconsider.
   In November 1985, Kuntsler and others on the defense team
appealed in Butts County Superior Court in Jackson, where Williams
is imprisoned, claiming authorities withheld vital information from
the defense that might have exonerated the former freelance
photographer and music promoter.
   Since then, the case has remained dormant while defense attorneys
sought information to support their contention.
   ``What we have put together is the fact that there was a meeting
in the governor's office in which it was decided that they could not
charge a white Klan member without causing a race riot,'' Kuntsler
contended. ``Wayne became the fall guy. Everything we have sustains
that.''
   George Busbee was governor at the time. His secretary said he
could not immediately comment Wednesday because he was in meetings.
   Kuntsler said investigators have amassed more than 300 pages of
new evidence that points away from Williams.
   ``We have as much as we're going to get,'' he said. ``We're going
to reopen this case and get Wayne out of there and go after the
Klan.''
   Among evidence withheld, he contends, are wiretap recordings in
which Klan members admit ``that they did it and they boasted about
it.''
   Lewis Slaton, district attorney for Fulton County where most of
the killings took place, said he was aware of ``nothing new'' in the
case and added that the move appears to be a continuation of the
appeal previously filed.
   Williams was convicted largely on the basis of fibers found on
the victims that could be traced to the Williams household carpet,
Williams' bedspread, his dog and other sources.
   Prosecution witnesses testified that the odds of random
duplication of that combination of fibers were 150 million to one.
   Joseph Drolet of the Fulton County district attorney's office,
who prosecuted the case, said fiber evidence linked Williams to
about 20 of the cases and the same fiber combination has not been
found on a murder victim since Williams was arrested. Some victims
were found in rivers or on river banks and were washed clean of
evidence, he said.
</TEXT>
