<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Service     06-21 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Service,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Americans Urged to Help Rescue Those ``Free Falling Through
Society''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a clarion call to community
service, urged young Americans on Wednesday to help rescue millions
of homeless, poor and other needy people who are ``free falling
through society.''
   ``I need your help. ... America needs your help,'' Bush told more
than 3,000 teen-agers and children on the White House lawn.
   ``It is a time of need for millions of Americans,'' said Bush.
``Too many people are free falling through society with no prospect
of landing on their feet.
   ``No one _ young, old, white, brown or black _ should be
permitted to go through life unclaimed,'' said Bush. ``You must show
us how to reclaim these lives.''
   He made his appeal as part of his Youth Engaged in Service (YES)
to America drive to muster support for community service.
   In New York on Thursday, he will unveil details of a wider
national service initiative ``to encourage volunteers of all ages,
all backgrounds, all abilities,'' Bush said.
   Aides said Bush would urge virtually every institution in society
to give a new push to volunteerism.
   But on this steamy morning, he aimed his message at the young,
from 5 to 25, saying all had something to give.
   Bush invoked the image of the bell in the church steeple that in
``a simpler time'' summoned neighbors to help.
   ``When people heard that bell, they didn't stop to ask why it was
ringing, they just came, (on) horseback or foot, by buggy or
bicycle, honking the horn of a Model T, they just came,'' said the
president. ``Whatever the problem, whoever was in need of help, they
were ready.''
   ``The bells have been silent too long,'' he said. ``Let them ring
in your hearts and across the land.''
   ``Commit yourselves. Listen to the bells. Make it your mission to
make a difference in somebody else's life,'' he said.
   ``All of you have something to offer _ kids from tough
neighborhoods, kids from broken homes, kids who have grown up on
food stamps and hand-me-downs. ... You each have a gift that America
needs,'' he said.
   His remarks hit a receptive chord in the audience, invited from
Boy Scout troops, church groups, schools and other organizations
already engaged in service.
   ``He's preaching to the converted in my case,'' said Alexandra
Warren, 19, of New Hope, Pa., who is spending this summer as a
volunteer for Common Cause before her junior year at Haverford
College. Service ``is part of the Quaker ethos at Haverford,'' she
said.
   Shaka Brown, 12, a Boy Scout from Washington, D.C., said, ``I
just helped somebody a little while ago. A young lady lost her
nametag.'' He helped her find it on the soggy and packed White House
lawn.
   As presidents in time of war called for young people to defend
America, Bush said he was urging them to fight poverty, homelessness
and other ills.
   He told Congress in February he will seek $100 million over four
years to endow a YES foundation to provide matching grants for
community service projects.
   Bush said young people could find meaning and adventure in
community service.
   He listed sad statistics about America's youth _ 1,700 drop out
of school, 4,000 run away from home and 2,700 become pregnant daily
_ but he insisted: ``You're not the problem. You are the solution.''
   ``You don't need to be bribed with incentives and threatened with
penalties to get engaged in community service,'' he said. ``Service
is its own reward, satisfaction guaranteed.''
   ``He wants to save money,'' said June Shih, 17, of St. Agnes
School in Alexandria, Va., where the girls are required to perform
40 hours of community service before senior year.
   ``It's good, the 1,000 points of light and everything,'' said
Shih, a Red Cross volunteer. ``America's in the red. He has to find
some way to help the less-fortunate without straining the budget.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
