<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     06-21 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Refuse to Fire Policeman Accused of Intimidation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibia's administrator Wednesday
refused to dismiss paramilitary policemen who have been accused of
intimidating civilians and jeopardizing independence elections in
the territory.
   South African Administrator Louis Pienaar told a news conference
he will allow members of the recently disbanded Koevoet
counterinsurgency unit to remain in the regular police force.
   Members of Koevoet, which means ``crowbar'' in Afrikaans, wore
military uniforms and traveled the bush in armored personnel
carriers. They are known for often brutal tactics against supporters
and guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's Organization, which
has fought 23 years to end South African rule of Namibia.
   Koevoet was made up mostly of black Namibians led by white South
Africans.
   Pretoria, which has ruled Namibia for 74 years, has agreed to a
yearlong transition to independence supervised by more than 4,000
U.N. monitors.
   Both the United Nations and South-West Africa People's
Organization accuse ex-Koevoet members of continuing to harass
civilians since their January integration into the regular police
force.
   ``Their activities appear to have createad an atmosphere of fear
and intimidation among much of the population in the northern
region,'' Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N. special representative to
Namibia, said in a June 9 letter to Pienaar.
   ``In my opinion, (they are) unfit for continued service in the
police during the transition period in view of the need to ensure
the necessary conditions for free and fair elecations,'' the letter
said.
   Pienaar said he has reports guerrillas are storing arms caches in
northern Namibia and he cannot afford to reduce the police strength.
   ``We feel obliged to maintain a state of alertness, commensurate
with a potential threat to the security of the region,'' he said.
   ``I reject the possibility that men should be removed from the
police just because they have been members of the counterinsurgency
unit.''
   He emphasized he would dismiss individuals found guilty of
misconduct.
   Ahtisaari and Pienaar met Wednesday to discuss the intimidation
charges and plan more talks, officials said.
   In other developments, U.N. officials said 5,621 Namibian exiles
have been flown home since they began a repatriation campaign 10
days ago. The U.N. has registered more than 41,000 Namibian refugees
at camps in neighboring Angola, Zambia and Botswana and wants to
bring back 1,000 a day for six weeks.
   South Africa agreed to grant Namibia independence in exchange for
the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops helping Angola's government
fight U.S.-backed rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     06-21 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader: Summit Will Fail Without Rebel-Gov't Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOA ESPERANCA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel leader Jonas Savimbi said
Wednesday an African summit aimed at resolving the Angolan civil war
will fail unless direct talks begin between the rebels and the
government.
   But he told a news conference at his bush camp that ``never in 14
years of war have we come so close'' to peace.
   Angola's official news agency announced Wednesday the government
released 700 rebel prisoners. The dispatch said the prisoners were
released June 2 and reported the prisoners had renounced the rebel
movement and accepted the government's offer of clemency.
   The announcement came on the eve of a meeting of African leaders
in Gbadolite, Zaire. The meeting could clear the way for direct
peace talks between Angola's Marxist government and the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   Savimbi said his delegation in Zaire was willing to be flexible
about procedures leading to elections and formation of a national
unity government.
   But, he said, the rebels would reject any amnesty or clemency for
the guerrillas.
   ``Our army, 75,000 men in the field, will not accept amnesty,
clemency or integration'' into the ruling Popular Movement for the
Liberation of Angola, Savimbi said. ``That wording has a political
context that means (the rebel army) is considered criminal. Our army
was not defeated and is not going to be defeated.''
   Savimbi said he has agreed to stay out of the negotiations and
will not demand a role in any transitional government. But he said
he would remain the head of his party. He also wants to participate
in free elections he anticipates within two years of a formal
cease-fire.
   He dismissed reports he might go into exile, saying he would
remain in Angola after a cease-fire, but not necessarily in his
southeastern stronghold of Jamba.
   Angola's government has rejected elections, insisting on
maintaining one-party rule and offering some rebels positions in the
administration.
   The Angolan news service ANGOP said Wednesday that President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos' has a peace plan calling for Savimbi to go
abroad, recognize the legitimacy of the government and for the rebel
movement to be integrated into the one-party state. Savimbi
vehemently vetoed all these proposals at his news conference.
   Savimbi said the Angolan government was under pressure, because
within six months, half of the 50,000 Cuban soldiers who have
supported it will have left Angola under a U.S.-mediated southern
African peace agreement reached in December.
   The Cubans have agreed to a gradual withdrawal, to be completed
by July 1991. But Savimbi said the Soviet Union and the United
States have promised to ``help the Cubans leave quickly'' if the
peace talks lead to formation of a transitional unity government
before then.
   The U.S.-backed rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war to
force the Cuban- and Soviet-assisted government to share power since
shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   Savimbi praised Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko for organizing
the summit, expected to be attended by leaders from Zaire, Angola,
Mozambique, Cape Verde, Guinea-Bissau, Sao Tome e Principe,
Botswana, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Gabon, Ivory Coast, Tanzania, Congo and
Mali.
   According to news reports in Portugal, Savimbi might also travel
to Zaire to participate in the indirect talks. Savimbi was preparing
to fly out of Angola after the news conference Wednesday but did not
say where he was going.
   At the request of Ivory Coast President Felix Houphouet-Boigny,
the rebels have declared a ``de facto'' cease-fire and are
conducting only defensive operations. He said the government army is
still attacking, ``trying to capture prisoners for their amnesty,''
but with much less intensity than in the past.

</TEXT>
