<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     06-21 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Burmese Opposition Leader Arrested, Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's main opposition leader and 15
supporters were detained Wednesday during a ceremony to honor people
slain last year during a military crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators, official sources said.
   The sources said Aung San Suu Kyi and her followers were
interrogated for about an hour and then released. They spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   No official statement was made about the incident at Myeinigon,
four miles north of downtown Rangoon.
   In Washington, State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher
said the incident would be a ``grave blow to hopes that next year's
election will be free and fair.''
   Boucher said the administration has noted with concern the
Burmese government's restrictions on political activity, including a
ban on gatherings of five or more people, prohibition of opposition
publications and harassment and arrest of opposition party leaders.
   Aung San Suu Kyi is the daughter of deceased national hero Gen.
Aung San. A 44-year-old political neophyte, she is widely regarded
as the most powerful opposition figure in Burma. Her party appears
to have the biggest backing among the more than 200 that have
mushroomed since last year's pro-democracy movement.
   She held a religious ceremony with her followers at a branch
office of her National League for Democracy and then walked to the
spot where several demonstrators were shot by police last June 21.
   Several hundred people were present at the wreath-laying when
authorities moved in.
   Witnesses said Aung San Suu Kyi and the others were taken away in
open military trucks to a government office near where the ceremony
took place.
   In recent months, Aung San Suu Kyi has been harassed on occasion
but generally been given considerable leeway by the military
government to campaign throughout the country.
   She returned to Rangoon from London, her home for many years, to
look after her ailing mother in April 1988, and became embroiled in
political turmoil sweeping Burma at the time.
   She became one of the main leaders of a pro-democracy uprising
that seemed on the verge of toppling 26 years of authoritarian rule
through massive street demonstrations.
   But in September, Gen. Saw Maung and a group of military officers
brutally crushed the student-led protests and clamped martial law on
the country.
   The new leaders allowed the formation of opposition political
parties and have promised free general elections next year.
   Aung San Suu Kyi joined with two popular leaders, retired Brig.
Gen. Aung Gyi and former Defense Minister Tin Oo, to form the
National League for Democracy. Aung Gyi later left the group,
claiming the league was being infiltrated by communists.
</TEXT>
