<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Bevilacqua     06-21 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bevilacqua,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Chief Justice, Speaker Brought Down By Mob Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph A. Bevilacqua, whose lifelong
friendships with reputed mobsters tarnished and eventually ended his
career as Rhode Island's top legislator and top judge, died
Wednesday. He was 70.
   Bevilacqua died at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston. No
further information was immediately available, said hospital
spokeswoman Brenda Buratti.
   He had been hospitalized several times during the last few months
in Providence, most recently in early May for a heart attack. He was
taken to Brigham and Women's on May 30 when he complained of
problems with his medication, relatives said.
   Bevilacqua was elected to the Rhode Island House in 1954 and
maintained a successful criminal law practice while he rose through
the ranks to become majority leader in 1966 and speaker in 1969.
   Questions about his ties to criminals came into the open when the
General Assembly elected him chief justice of the state Supreme
Court in 1976.
   Among them were allegations that Bevilacqua had harbored a
fugitive from a 1963 department store robbery and accepted $2,000 of
the loot from him. The fugitive, Robert Northrop, later recanted his
story.
   Then-Attorney General Julius Michaelson investigated the matter
in 1977 but concluded there was ``no prosecutable case.''
   At about the same time, a letter surfaced in which Bevilacqua
told the state Parole Board in 1973 that Raymond L.S. Patriarca, the
late New England organized-crime boss, was ``a person of integrity
and, in my opinion, good moral character.''
   The Commission on Judicial Tenure and Discipline took no action
after it investigated the letter and Bevilacqua's officiating at the
the wedding of Patriarca's chauffeur six months after becoming chief
justice. The chauffeur, Joseph A. Badway, was under indictment for
fraud at the time.
   The series of events that finally brought Bevilacqua down began
at the end of 1984, with a Providence Journal-Bulletin story
alleging that state police and the newspaper's reporters had
observed Bevilacqua repeatedly visiting the homes of underworld
figures.
   The state police subsequently alleged that Bevilacqua had also
visited a Smithfield motel, owned by men linked to gambling and
drugs, for trysts with his secretary and another woman to whom he
was not married.
   The judicial commission launched a new investigation, hiring
former U.S. Supreme Court Justice Arthur J. Goldberg as special
counsel, and censured Bevilacqua for associating with criminals.
Bevilacqua agreed to take an unpaid four-month leave of absence in
1985.
   When the General Assembly convened the next year, it launched
impeachment proceedings. Two weeks after the House Judiciary
Committee began public hearings on the matter, Bevilacqua resigned.
   In February 1987, U.S. Attorney Lincoln C. Almond confirmed that
Bevilacqua's personal finances were under investigation.
   At the time Bevilacqua stepped down, the impeachment hearings had
begun to focus on his personal finances, which he handled in cash
and through third parties.
   He is survived by his wife, two sons and daughter.
   Funeral plans were incomplete.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MississippiExecution     06-21 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Execution,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killer Dies in Gas Chamber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARCHMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A robber who shot a convenience store
clerk to death was executed Wednesday in Mississippi's gas chamber,
insisting to the last that he was convicted unfairly because of
racial discrimination.
   A doctor at the Mississippi State Penitentiary at Parchman said
Leo Edwards Jr., 36, of New Orleans was heavily sedated at his own
request. But the lethal fumes awakened him and he cried out and
gasped before he died at 12:15 a.m.
   Edwards was the fourth person executed at the Mississippi
penitentiary and the 113th in the nation since the U.S. Supreme
Court reinstated the death penalty in 1976.
   He was executed for the shooting death of Jackson convenience
store clerk Linzy Don Dixon in a June 14, 1980, robbery that netted
$111. Dixon was shot while he talked on the telephone.
   Edwards, who was black, was convicted by an all-white Hinds
County Circuit Court jury and was sentenced to death April 1, 1981.
Defense attorneys protested that prosecutors deliberately excluded
blacks from the jury, but four appeals courts disagreed.
   Edwards maintained again in a Memphis, Tenn., newspaper interview
published Tuesday that he did not receive a fair trial, recalling
that when he saw the all-white jury he said, ``I'm dead.''
   Late Tuesday, Gov. Ray Mabus rejected a plea for clemency.
   ``I will not stand in the way of the courts' justice. ... Leo
Edwards is a mass murderer who killed in cold blood,'' Mabus said.
``He tried and failed to get relief in 16 appeals to the courts, and
discrimination had no bearing in his case.''
   The U.S. Supreme Court refused, in a 7-2 vote, to delay the
execution on procedural grounds.
   Dixon, who also was black, was killed during a five-day robbery
spree by Edwards and co-defendant Mike White that left three people
dead and one wounded. White, who got three life terms, testified
that Edwards told him he had shot the store clerk to avoid being
identified later.
   Before his execution, family members including his mother and
daughter spent most of the day with Edwards. He also talked with a
priest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
