<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Doctors     06-21 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe-Doctors,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criminal Charges Dropped Against Interns Who Went on Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Wednesday they have
dropped criminal charges against medical interns arrested during a
four-day strike last week.
   The decision was made ``in the public interest'' and to smooth
the way for a settlement of grievances, according to a government
statement.
   Several hundred striking interns at state hospitals and clinics
stayed off the job to demand a review of salaries and working
conditions.
   More than 70 were detained by police June 14 on charges they
violated laws barring those working in essential services from going
on strike.
   The strikers spent a night in jail but were then released and
ordered to appear in court June 29 and July 19. The crimes with
which they were charged carry a maximum sentence of 10 years in jail.
   There were no reports of deaths of patients during the strike.
   The stoppage ended after the government promised to settle
grievances in the state health service.
   Health minister Felix Muchemwa said salaries will be raised and
their compulsory attachment to state health facilities will be
reduced from five years to three years.
   Interns earn a monthly income of about $300.
   Muchemwa did not release details of the pay offer.
   Andrew Cakana, leader of the Hospital Doctors' Association, said
Wednesday his organization was reserving its comments until interns
have studied the offer.
</TEXT>
