<FIRST>r a AM-JobDiscrimination     06-21 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Job Discrimination,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Job Service Employees Suspended Following Discrimination Check</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten employees of a state job service
agency have been suspended for a month without pay for agreeing to
requests to provide only white male applicants for certain job
openings, officials said.
   Such actions are ``totally in violation of anything this
department is about,'' said state Jobs and Training Commissioner Joe
Samargia, whose department oversees the job service offices.
   The suspensions announced Tuesday came after an investigation by
the state Human Rights Department, which made tape-recorded phone
calls to state employment offices in April and May. In the calls,
job applicants were requested for a fictitious employer.
   ``They were told, `We don't want any females and we don't want
any minorities _ we just want white males,''' said state Human
Rights Commissioner Stephen Cooper. ``We made 12 different calls and
10 came up bad and two came up good.''
   After the findings, the state Department of Jobs and Training and
the Human Rights Department reached agreement on training and rules
to ensure that discriminatory job orders aren't accepted in the
future.
   ``We were going to file some charges, but they were willing to
work with us so we didn't need to,'' Cooper said.
   Samargia said the 10 job service interviewers were suspended last
week.
   Reconstructing one conversation, Samargia said a job service
worker told the undercover caller that the discriminatory order
could not be accepted as offered but that the order would be handled
as the caller desired.
   ``If St. Paul found out, I'd be in trouble,'' the employee said,
according to Samargia.
   An official of the Minnesota Association of Professional
Employees, a union representing nine of the suspended employees,
said it is contesting the suspensions.
   ``They were totally inappropriate,'' said union president Peter
LeWon, contending that the department provided little, if any
training for employees on how to handle such matters.
   Samargia insisted, ``We've had training on this.''
</TEXT>
