<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AMAConvention     06-21 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMA Convention,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Endorses Federal Mandated, Employer-Provided Health Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association, for the first
time in its history, endorsed Wednesday the concept of federally
mandated, employer-provided health insurance.
   Under a proposal passed by delegates at the AMA's annual
policymaking convention, the nation's largest organization of
doctors agreed to press for legislation calling for ``a phased-in
requirement that employers (limited initially to larger employers)
provide health-insurance coverage within the private sector for all
full-time employees, with coverage expanding over several years.''
   In addition, the delegates recommended ``a program of diminishing
tax credits or other incentives to avoid adverse effects on
employers.''
   The policy adopted by the 433 members of the House of Delegates
calls for the AMA to work with business groups to develop the
approaches that are best suited to the needs of small employers.
   Such legislation would help the nation's 37 million uninsured and
also would allow doctors to recover fees lost under the Medicaid
program, an AMA spokesman said.
   Small businesses have lobbied heavily against proposals calling
for any type of federally mandated employer-provided insurance, and
an industry spokeswoman said they would do the same with measures
like that endorsed by the AMA.
   Marcia Bradford, spokeswoman for National Small Business United,
a Washington, D.C. lobbying organization representing about 50,000
small businesses, said that while the AMA's desire to include small
businesses in developing national legislation is a step in the right
direction, ``there's still a fundamental question of government
mandates that we're opposed to.''
   The AMA's action is part of the organization's effort to combat
moves to nationalize the U.S. health care system. A group of
physicians started such an effort this year, seeking adoption of a
system similar to Canada's in which individuals and employers are
taxed to pay for health coverage for all.
   The AMA's Board of Trustees strongly opposes the Canadian system,
in which ``all responsibility for health care payment is placed on
the government.''
   The AMA also opposes a move led by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
to force employers to provide a specific package of health-insurance
benefits for employees, said Dr. Wayne Bradley, the AMA's assistant
executive vice president.
   That plan, with no gradual phase-in, ``might cause an employer
not to hire an extra person, or it might cause a business to go
broke,'' Bradley said.
   The AMA favors less drastic reforms and advocates ``the principle
that employees be covered by health insurance in the workplace,'' he
said. ``It's a major national problem.''
   Bradley said it was the first time the AMA had endorsed the
concept of federally mandated, employer-provided health insurance.
   In other action Wednesday, the delegates elected the first female
phsyician to the AMA's Board of Trustees, its governing body.
   Nancy Dickey of Richmond, Texas, thanked the delegates for the
``history you have just made.'' Women have been appointed in the
past by other board members to student and resident trustee
positions, but Dickey is the first to be elected a regular trustee
by the full delegation.
   Dr. Alan Nelson, a Salt Lake City internist and president-elect
for the past year, was named president of the AMA. Nelson takes over
the one-year post from Dr. James Davis, a Durham, N.C., surgeon. Dr.
C. John Tupper, an internist from Davis, Calif., was elected
president-elect.
   Dr. Mary Ann Contogiannis, a resident physician from
Winston-Salem, N.C., was elected to the resident position on the
Board of Trustees.
   Dr. William E. Jacott, a family physician from Minneapolis, was
elected to the Board of Trustees. Re-elected to the board were Dr.
Frank B. Walker, a pathologist from Detroit, and Dr. John Ring, a
family physician from Mundelein.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
