<FIRST>u w AM-BlackCatholics     06-21 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Catholics,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Priest to Start Own African-American Catholic Congregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black priest who plans to start a separate
African-American Catholic congregation said Wednesday he is not
defying Roman Catholic tenets, despite warnings from church leaders.
   ``While the establishment of this congregation does not enjoy the
endorsement or authority of His Eminence, James Cardinal Hickey, we
see ourselves as being obedient to the law of God and following the
dictates of our consciences,'' said the Rev. George A. Stallings Jr.
   Stallings, 41, said he plans to create the Imani Temple
African-American Catholic Congregation in Washington because the
Roman Catholic Church has failed to meet the spiritual and cultural
demands of its black parishioners.
   However, the priest said his move is not intended to be a
departure from Catholicism.
   He said his church would adopt a Zairian liturgy and would
combine readings from the works of noted black writers and
philosophers, such as Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm X, with
traditional Scripture passages.
   Imani means ``faith'' in Swahili.
   Cardinal Hickey of Washington and a prominent black church leader
both condemned Stallings' actions.
   ``In spite of his claims to the contrary, Father Stallings'
action is a serious step towards separating himself from the Roman
Catholic Church,'' Hickey said in a statement. ``This situation has
more to do with the needs and expectations of Father Stallings than
with broader questions about the adequacy of Catholic ministry
within the black community.''
   Bishop John Ricard, chairman of the Committee for Black Catholics
of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, also expressed
criticism, in a statement issued by Hickey's office.
   ``Although I acknowledge that we as African-American Catholics
still find it necessary to struggle for full inclusion in the
Catholic Church, the founding of the Imani Temple is a regressive
step,'' Ricard said.
   Hickey also said that Stallings' former Catholic parishioners
should not support his efforts and that doing so would leave them in
an ``ambiguous position'' with the Roman Catholic Church.
   Stallings said of his own situation, ``I cannot be excommunicated
from my faith. ... When I lay down I have to answer not to an
institution but to the man that woke me up.''
   Of the nation's 300 bishops, 13 are black. While there are about
1,100 predominantly black parishes nationwide, there are just 200
black priests.
   Hickey noted that Stallings made his announcement even though the
bishops, in their national conference, committed themselves only
last Sunday to stronger efforts to support the black Catholic
community.
   But Stallings said those efforts fall short of black
parishioners' needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
