<FIRST>u i AM-China-Executions 1stLd-Writethru a0671 06-21 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Executions, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0671,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Ignores World Opinion in Executions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``In addition, ...'' to fix wording and to conform
to AM-China.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's execution of three people Wednesday for
burning a train during a pro-democracy protest flouted worldwide
calls for mercy in the government's crackdown on political dissent.
   The death sentences, announced on radio and television, were
carried out in Shanghai, where the arson incident occurred June 6.
   The executions came a day after President Bush appealed for
clemency, and White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged
that China had turned its back on the pleas.
   ``The weight of world opinion has been heavy on the shoulders of
China and it does not appear to have made much difference,'' he
said. ``History has shown that they generally are not that
responsive to outside kinds of pleas.''
   So far, 28 people have been condemned to death: the three who
were executed, the 17 who were sentenced on Wednesday after a public
trial in Shandong province, and eight others in Beijing who were
previously sentenced to death.
   Their crimes ranged from ``rumor-mongering'' to beating soldiers
and burning vehicles.
   The three executed were convicted of setting fire to a train
after it smashed through a barricade set up by demonstrators,
killing six people. The three then beat firefighters who tried to
douse the blaze, according to the Shanghai People's Intermediate
Court.
   Bush on Tuesday suspended high-level U.S.-Chinese contacts and
moved to block $1.4 billion in development loans to protest the
crackdown. France and the Netherlands already had frozen relations
and Japan has suspended new development loans.
   The government depends heavily on foreign investment for capital
and technology, and has stressed during the past two weeks that
things are back to normal in China.
   China did not immediately respond to the U.S. moves, but the
state-run Xinhua News Agency said Wednesday the United States was
interfering in China's affairs and that there would be no mercy.
   ``The 11 thugs have been sentenced to death according to China's
criminal law, because they committed heinous crimes of beating,
smashing, looting and burning,'' Xinhua before the additional
sentences were announced.
   Other nations had joined the United States in urging clemency,
and some denounced China following the executions.
   ``What is happening in China is atrocious,'' Foreign Minister
Roland Dumas of France told the National Assembly in Paris. ``The
totalitarian machine, in all its horror, is rolling.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain said in London that
she and Prime Minister Bob Hawke of Australia were discussing steps
against the Chinese government. ``The punishment is totally out of
proportion to the crime,'' she said.
   In the Hague, the Dutch government said it was seized by
``disgust.'' ``This new sad fact can only lead to a further cooling
of relations,'' said a statement issued by the Foreign Ministry.
   China began its crackdown on the pro-democracy movement on June 3
and has said the matter is a domestic affair.
   Premier Li Peng said Monday the government would spare no effort
in tracking down protest organizers.
   The approach is not new. In a 1987 speech, senior leader Deng
Xiaoping said that after widespread arrests of pro-democracy
protesters 10 years ago, China suffered ``no discredit,'' and that
``on the contrary, the prestige of the country is steadily growing.''
   Fitzwater said the United States could not afford to turn its
back on China even though it deplored the crackdown.
   ``Everyone has to recognize, first of all, that this is a country
of a billion people ... a sizeable portion of the world's population
that cannot be closeted off and ignored,'' he said.
   China imposes the death penalty for certain violent and economic
crimes but also for some political offenses, and often for crimes
involving foreigners.
   In April a court in Shanghai sentenced a man to death after he
was convicted of robbing the U.S. Consulate in that city over a
period of 14 months of about $8,900.
   The human rights group Amnesty International said in 1985 that
10,000 people had been executed in China since a nationwide
crackdown on crime two years earlier. Chinese officials do not
release figures on executions.
</TEXT>
