<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old Oklahoma girl gave birth
Wednesday in the bathroom of a Senate office building while the
group she was with toured the Capitol.
   ``Last I heard she was doing fine,'' said Capitol Police
spokesman Dan Nichols. ``She walked out of the bathroom carrying the
baby.''
   Nichols said the Blanchard, Okla., girl, whose name was not
released because she is a minor, went into a bathroom on the ground
floor of the Senate Dirksen office building about 8 a.m. EDT and
gave birth.
   The group's chaperon, Don Grabbe, helped deliver the boy, Nichols
said.
   ``When I got there it was the mother and two of the people on the
tour trying to get the baby to breathe,'' said Debora Brooke, a
Capitol Police sergeant who said she rushed from another building to
help.
   ``He was kind of red,'' she said. ``I was able to put my finger
down the little boy's throat and he coughed up some of the mucus and
starting breathing on his own.''
   The girl and infant were taken to the Washington Hospital Center
where officials said the mother was in fair condition.
   The 4-pound-5{-ounce baby, who officials believe was born
prematurely, was listed in critical condition, said hospital
spokesman Alexander Sinclair.
   No other details were immediately available.
