<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Iran     06-21 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Iran,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Invites Gorbachev to Iran, Agrees on Economic Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and the Soviet Union ended nearly a decade of
icy relations Wednesday when Iran's Parliament speaker invited
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to visit Iran and the two leaders agreed on
wide economic cooperation.
   Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani told the Soviet president that
Iranians hold him in high esteem and look forward to meeting him,
the official Tass news agency reported.
   It said Gorbachev thanked Rafsanjani for the invitation and said
frequent high-level contacts are appropraite as relations warm. No
date was set.
   Only a handful of Third World leaders have visited Tehran since
the 1979 Islamic Revolution transformed the Iranian capital into a
city known for mobs of religious fanatics shouting, ``Death to
America! Death to Russia!''
   Rafsanjani and Gorbachev have been meeting in the Kremlin over
two days with a number of their colleagues. Tass said they will sign
several agreements before Rafsanjani leaves Moscow.
   Among them are a promise to be good neighbors on their 1,550-mile
border and an agreement on joint projects in 15 areas of the
economy, including nuclear energy, gas processing, and space.
   The level of relations, which may extend to putting an Iranian on
board a Soviet spaceship, marks a dramatic turnaround. Earlier this
decade, the Soviet Union was supplying weapons for Iraq to fight
Iran, and Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's fundamentalist regime was
banning Iran's Communist Party.
   In contrast, Tass quoted Rafsanjani as saying Wednesday, ``I have
been in Moscow less than 24 hours, yet already I feel almost at
home.''
   Tehran television said Rafsanjani is extending his visit beyond
the planned Thursday departure.
   It was Rafsanjani who suggested a joint Soviet-Iranian space
voyage, and Gorbachev ordered his deputies to begin planning details.
   Rafsanjani emphasized that it was Khomeini himself who in
February, several months before his death on June 3, called for
better relations with the Soviet Union. Tass noted that Gorbachev
and Khomeini exchanged messages in February, and since then their
foreign ministers have met four times.
   ``We should admit that in the past we had periods where our
border turned into a blank wall,'' Gorbachev said at a Kremlin
banquet for Rafsanjani. ``It is good that those times apparently
have passed.''
   Moscow had hoped the revolution that ousted the late Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, a longtime U.S. ally, would give it a toehold
in the nation on its southern border. Instead, Iranian
fundamentalists chose an independent path and held Moscow in disdain.
   Now, Tass said, rail links will be restored and another rail line
constructed.
   With ties to the West strained, Tehran is looking to the Soviet
bloc for help in rebuilding Iran after its eight-year war with Iraq,
which halted with a cease-fire in August.
   Iranian officials said last month they hoped to sign an arms deal
with Moscow, but Tass said nothing on the subject.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Jets     06-21 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Jets,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Allows Boeing 737-400 Jets To Fly With Power Curb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Civil Aviation Authority Wednesday lifted its
grounding order on 12 Boeing 737-400 planes operated by British
airlines provided modifications are made to the engines.
   The planes were grounded nine days ago after two incidents in
which 737-400s were forced to make emergency landings because fan
blades broke in their CFM 56-3C engines.
   The engines are manufactured by CFM International, a joint
venture between SNECMA of France and General Electric of the United
States.
   Britain's aviation authority imposed power cuts of 1,500 pounds
of thrust on the CFM 56-3C engines, effectively converting them to a
previous generation of that make.
   The planes will be allowed a maximum thrust of 22,000 pounds, the
same as the previous CFM 56-3B, which had 6 million hours of
reliable service.
   Airlines were also ordered to replace the engines' fan blades and
discs. Regular visual inspections of fan blades and the front face
of the engine discs will also be required, a spokesman for the
British authority said.
   Airlines were already making the modifications and some 737-400s
might be back in operation on Thursday, he said.
   Demonstrations Wednesday by the engine manufacturer showed that
fan fatigue occurred near the peak in the engine's thrust, the
spokesman said.
   ``It has now been found that running it at that higher speed,
particularly at the rate of climb, has induced something that will
need further investigation,'' he said.
   The grounding order was made after fan blades broke on a DanAir
plane at Gatwick Airport on June 9 and on a British Midland Airways
aircraft at Heathrow Airport on June 11.
   Fan blade problems were also thought to have contributed to the
engine failure that led to the January crash of a British Midland
737-400 near East Midlands Airport in Leicestershire, killing 47.
   The U.S. Federal Aviation Adminstration rejected the British
authority's grounding request and cleared 737-400s to fly with the
lower engine thrust and new blades and discs.
   In addition to British Midland and DanAir, 737-400s are operated
by Novair, Air Europe and Air UK-Leisure.
</TEXT>
