<HEAD>Soviet Stowaway Crushed In Undercarriage of Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet man who apparently stowed away in the
undercarriage of a Japanese jet was found crushed to death Wednesday
when the plane arrived from Moscow, police and airline officials
said.
   All Nippon Airways said the dead man is believed to be a
21-year-old Russian who had been trying to emigrate.
   The airline's Boeing 747 left Tokyo on Monday and had been in
Moscow nearly two days before it flew to England on a trial run for
its new Tokyo to London service beginning next month. It carried no
passengers.
   Airline spokesman Shinobu Hasegawa said a British Airways
engineer found the body inside the wheel well in the right hand main
undercarriage after the plane landed at London's Gatwick Airport.
   ``We are fairly sure he was attempting to defect because his
paperwork was not in order. The police, ourselves and the airport
are in touch with the Russian Embassy,'' Hasegawa said.
   Sussex police said they believe the man was crushed when the
undercarriage was raised after take off.
   ``There are no suspicious circumstances, and from documentation
found in the bay it would appear that the body is that of a Russian
national,'' a police spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   A coroner is negotiating with the Soviet Embassy to establish the
man's identity, the spokesman said.

