<FIRST>r a AM-UnlicensedDropout     06-21 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unlicensed Dropout,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Restores Dropout's License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge temporarily restored driving
privileges Wednesday to a married teen-ager whose license was
suspended under a law aimed at curbing a high rate of school
dropouts.
   Kanawha County Circuit Judge Paul Zakaib Jr. set aside Michael
Mean's license suspension for 30 days to allow attorneys to file
briefs in the case.
   Means, 17, of Charleston, who dropped out of the ninth grade last
year, appealed a Department of Motor Vehicles decision to suspend
his license under a first-of-its-kind law aimed at reducing the
state's dropout rate, now about 17 percent.
   Under education reform law passed by the Legislature last summer,
students under 18 who miss more than 10 consecutive days of school
or have 15 unexcused absences must give up their driving privileges.
   Means' attorney, Christopher Butch, argued that the law was in
conflict with another state law permitting students to drop out of
school at age 16. The law, he said, was condemning Means and his
family to poverty because he was unable to earn the money he needed
to support his family without a driver's license.
   ``The law is not only draconian, it's unreasonable in this
case,'' Butch told the court Wednesday.
   Means' 16-year-old wife, Tonya, who is expecting a child in
August, said the state was preventing her husband from caring for
her and their unborn child. Her license also was suspended because
she is a dropout.
   ``We have the same responsibilities as anyone over 18,'' she
said. ``He has a house to pay for and has to earn money to care for
me and the baby.''
   Means said despite the judge's decision, he still felt the state
was trying to force him to return to school.
   ``I think they're trying to pressure me, to force me to enroll in
a (high school equivalency) program. I don't like being forced to do
anything,'' he said.
   Zakaib said Means could retain his driving privileges permanently
if he enrolls in an equivalency course and makes satisfactory
progress.
   Deputy Attorney General Bruce Wilson, who represents the
Department of Motor Vehicles, said he was satisfied with the
progress of the case.
   ``I was just worried that this would drag on through the courts
until he turned 18,'' Wilson said. `` I think this allows for a
quick resolution.''
   Butch left the court room immediately after the judge stayed the
suspension and was unavailable for comment.
   Wilson argued that revoking the decision to suspend Mean's
license would send the wrong message to teen-agers in similar
situations.
   ``It will encourage those people who want to avoid their
responsibility to the state and to themselves,'' Wilson said.
   He argued that statistics show dropouts are less likely to be
able to obtain jobs paying above the minimum wage.
   ``Maybe an education, some training, would help these people
break this cycle, a cycle of poverty and lowered ambitions.''
   Therese Wilson, director of the Office of Support Services for
the state Department of Education, testified that after the law went
into effect, 1,800 dropouts returned to school in the fall and 50
percent were still attending school in March.
   The state's recent dropout rate of around 17 percent is
equivalent to 5,000 students, Wilson said. The state expected to
reduce the rate this year by 1,000 students as a direct result of
the new law, she said.
   Several states, including Wisconsin and Texas where Gov. Bill
Clements signed a dropout bill into law Friday, have passed similar
legislation and others are considering such laws.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0180 </DOCNO>
