<DOCNO> AP890621-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-China     06-21 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-China,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urged to Curb Trade with China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders Wednesday urged President
Bush to consider curbing trade with China in an effort to end the
executions of pro-democracy demonstrators.
   ``The president must and should consider taking further steps,
particularly with respect to trade,'' Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, told the Senate, calling the executions
``barbaric'' acts.
   ``I say that in full awareness that we benefit from trade with
China,'' Mitchell said. ``But there are times when what America
stands for and believes in is more important than an economic
benefit to be derived from a trade relationship.''
   Three men were executed in Shanghai on Wednesday and as many as
17 other people have been sentenced to death for their roles in the
student-led protests earlier this month.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Sentate Appropriations
foreign operations subcommittee, said he told Chinese Ambassador Han
Xu in an hour-long conversation Wednesday that economic sanctions
were certain if repression and executions continue.
   ``Much that has been built up in the last 10 years could be
destroyed,'' Leahy said. ``If the repression and executions continue
much longer, the break will be irreparable.''
   Han, Leahy said, replied with ``the official line,'' stating that
actions taken by his government are ``internal matters.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, introduced legislation to
make it easier for Chinese students and scholars in the United
States to apply for asylum.
   He said the purpose of the legislation was to provide a safe
haven for students who fear persecution if they return and to signal
the Chinese government ``that its repressive campaign will mean the
loss of thousands of its best and brightest students.''
   Cohen said his bill would go beyond the step taken by President
Bush of authorizing a special immigration status permitting Chinese
students to remain through June 5, 1990.
   An alternative bill was introduced by Sens. Herb Kohl, D-Wis.,
and Alan Cranston, D-Calif., to permit Chinese students to renew
their visas and apply for permanent residence in the United States.
   There are more than 40,000 Chinese students attending American
colleges and universities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
