<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CableTV     06-21 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable TV,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Industry Has Become Monopoly, Senator, Others Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few major cable television operators are now
the ``godfathers'' of the industry, exacting tribute from start-up
companies and withholding programming from rural viewers, a Senate
panel was told Wednesday.
   An increasingly prosperous cable industry has raised prices and
stiff-armed microwave and home satellite dish companies that need
programming, while growing into a ``cable Cosa Nostra'' that can do
as it pleases without fear of regulation or competition, Sen. Albert
Gore, D-Tenn., said.
   Since 1986, when a 1984 law deregulating cable was fully in
place, only about six new cable program networks have been
successful, and they all are at least partially owned by major cable
system operators, Gore said at a Senate communications subcommittee
hearing on ownership of the cable TV industry.
   In the wake of deregulation, ``We have witnessed an extraordinary
concentration of control and integration by cable operators and
program services, manifesting itself in blatantly anticompetitive
behavior towards those who would compete with existing cable
operators for the right to distribute services,'' Gore said.
   ``In the case of satellite dish owners, for example, program
services have consistently refused to deal with distributors unless
they are cable operators, shutting out almost all competition for a
market that, ironically, cable itself has largely refused to
serve,'' added Gore, who has introduced legislation that would
re-regulate cable, allow telephone companies to compete in cable and
require cable operators to provide access for all program services
and delivery technologies.
   Wednesday's was the second in a series of three hearings on media
ownership that have featured a virtual who's who of television
industry executives.
   The hearings were spurred by increasing complaints to Congress of
price hikes and poor service and of ``quick-buck'' buying and
selling of cable systems. The ``horizontal concentration'' of a few
companies has turned cable into a major TV force that enters more
than half the nation's living rooms.
   At least a dozen bills are pending in Congress to re-regulate
cable prices, try to induce competition or to slow the shift of TV
sports to pay television.
   James Mooney, president of the National Cable Television
Association, testified that there was ``great sensitivity'' in his
industry to complaints but that cable has changed television for the
better as it loosened the stranglehold of ABC, CBS and NBC and
offered far more and better programming.
   Cable industry investment in new programming _ so-called vertical
integration _ has spurred the cable boom and has not impeded the
development of competing technologies or program services, Mooney
said.
   But Preston Padden, president of the Association of Independent
Television Stations, said that when NBC launched its new Consumer
News and Business Channel earlier this year, NBC reportedly paid the
nation's largest cable system operator, Tele-Communications Inc.,
``an estimated $20 million to buy or lease Tempo Television _ a
cable service whose apparent assets would appear to have been
negligible.''
   ``That transaction has all the appearances of the payment of
tribute for access through TCI's concentrated monopoly subscriber
base,'' Padden said.
   Gore called it a ``shakedown'' by a ``godfather''-like ``cable
Cosa Nostra'' in which any new programming source first must get
approval from a half-dozen major cable operators before it can even
think of proceeding.
   Gore, subcommittee Chairman Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, and
Sens. Larry Pressler, R.-S.D., and Conrad Burns, R-Mont., expressed
concern that their largely rural constituencies were being
shortchanged by the cable industry's apparent reluctance to sell
programs to microwave cable and home satellite dish users.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
