<HEAD>Immunity Sought in Hastings Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel has asked a judge to grant a
lawyer immunity to compel him to testify in the impeachment trial of
federal judge Alcee Hastings.
   U.S. District Court Judge Louis Oberdorfer has scheduled a Monday
hearing on the Senate Impeachment Trial Committee request for an
order granting immunity for William Borders.
   Borders was convicted in 1982 of accepting a bribe in exchange
for agreeing to try to influence Hastings.
   Hastings, of Miami, was acquitted in 1983 of charges that he
conspired with Borders to solicit a $150,000 payoff from two
defendants in exchange for a reduction in their sentences.
   Borders was sentenced to five years in prison.
   The House voted 17 articles of impeachment against Hastings in
August, including allegations that he lied at his trial six years
ago.
