<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-21 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Locally Heavy Rain Persists Across The East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain triggered floods that forced several hundred people
from their homes in Pennsylvania on Wednesday as showers and
thunderstorms fell over much of the eastern third of the nation.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell from the central Gulf
Coast to the Tennessee Valley, eastern sections of the Ohio Valley,
the lower Great Lakes and the mid- and south Atlantic Coast.
   Rainfall during the 24 hours up to 8 a.m. EDT included 5.76
inches at Wadley, Ala.; 5.50 inches at St. Marys, Pa.; 2.53 inches
at Clermont, Pa.; 2.34 inches at Wilcox, Pa.; and 2.18 inches at
Murphy, N.C.
   Flood or flash flood watches were posted in sections of Alabama,
Georgia, Tennessee, the Carolinas, Maryland, Virginia, West
Virginia, Pennsylvania and New York.
   The rain swelled creeks in Pennsylvania's western and central
mountains and threatened serious flooding downstream on the
Allegheny and Ohio rivers.
   In Ridgway, Pa., a town of about 5,600 in Elk County, about 200
people were evacuated Tuesday and Wednesday before the Clarion River
crested at about 6 feet over flood stage, according to county
Emergency Management Coordinator Ed Zettle.
   In Jefferson County, Pa., about 300 people were evacuated at
Brockway and nearby Snyder, and about 15 families sought higher
ground at Reynoldsville. State police said flooding and mud slides
closed several roads in the area.
   Two bridges were washed out along Cross Creek in Brooke County in
West Virginia's northern panhandle, the weather service said.
   In the morning, thunderstorms poured heavy rain across parts of
Alabama, North Carolina and Michigan. More than an inch and a half
of rain fell in two hours in Henderson, N.C., up to an inch and a
half in three hours in Lincoln and Abel, Ala., and inch and third in
two hours in Plymouth, Mich.
   Strong afternoon thunderstorms over southeastern Alabama blew
down trees and power lines at Clio and dropped hail as big as dimes
near Ozark.
   Huntsville, Ala., has already received 11.65 inches of rain this
month; the former record for the whole month of June was 7.30 inches
in 1976. This is in sharp contrast to last year, when Huntsville had
its driest June on record with only 0.17 inch of rain.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms also fell on the northern
Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley, with scattered showers over
southern New England.
   High wind gusts were common behind a cold front over the northern
and west-central plains, with gusts near 60 mph reported at
Cheyenne, Wyo., and Pierre, S.D., and near 50 mph at Goodland, Kan.,
and Fort Collins, Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Casper, Wyo., to 104 at Thermal and Palm Springs, Calif.,
and Phoenix. Wednesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 21 degrees
at South Lake Tahoe, Calif.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
upper Ohio Valley to the mid-Atlantic Coast; scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the southern Atlantic Coast to the Tennessee
Valley and the central Gulf Coast, from the upper Great Lakes to the
upper and middle Mississippi Valley and the southern half of the
Plains, and over the lower Great Lakes, eastern sections of the
lower Ohio Valley and the Rockies; and widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms over the northern half of the Plains.
   Highs in the 60s and lower 70s were predicted in the northern and
central Rockies; above 90 degrees from Florida to parts of the
middle and lower Mississippi Valley and much of Texas; above 100
degrees over inland central and southern California, the desert
Southwest and parts of southwestern Texas; and in the 70s and 80s in
much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
