<FIRST>r w AM-SodiumSulfate     06-21 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sodium Sulfate,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Removed from Hazard List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on
Wednesday declared that sodium sulfate, which accounts for about
half of the hazardous chemical releases by industry nationwide,
isn't a toxic substance at all.
   Sodium sulfate is a widely used agent and byproduct in a variety
of processes including the production of paper, glass and detergents.
   The chemical industry had petitioned the EPA to reclassify sodium
sulfate arguing that there is no evidence the chemical poses a
significant health threat.
   The action by the EPA had been expected. The agency staff had
earlier recommended that sodium sulfate be reclassified as being
nontoxic ``due to an apparent absence of significant toxicity
concerns'' about the chemical.
   Robert J. Israel, EPA petitions coordinator, said the
reclassification was taken after the agency concluded that sodium
sulfate ``did not meet the health and environmental toxicity
criteria'' required by the law.
   The chemical is widely used in industry and accounted for nearly
54 percent of all the toxic chemicals releases into the air, water
and soil during 1987, according to an EPA report eaerlier this week
on releases by industry of 328 toxic chemicals.
   The agency said that more than 12 billion pounds of sodium
sulfate were releases by industrial plants, most of it into surface
water, during 1987.
   The absence of sodium sulfate from the EPA toxic chemical list
will result in significant changes in the national profile on toxic
releases, agency officials said.
   For example, the largest volume of sodium sulfate releases
occurred in California, including 5.3 billion pounds from one plant,
causing that state to lead every other state in toxic industrial
chemical releases for 1987. Without sodium sulfate, California would
have ranked ninth, the EPA said.
   Overall, 22.5 billion pounds of toxic releases were reported for
1987, according to the EPA report. But that volume is more than cut
in half without sodium sulfate.
   Water discharges were the most common form of toxic chemical
releases in 1987 largedly because three-fourths of all relases of
sodium sulfate were into surface water. Without sodium sulfate,
water releases would have ranked last.
</TEXT>
