<FIRST>u a AM-People-Hurt     06-21 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hurt,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Physician's Wife Says Hurt Referred to Jennings As His Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Hurt referred to his lover as his wife
when she was pregnant with their child, according to a doctor's wife
who testified Wednesday that she recognized the actor's voice from
the movie ``Body Heat.''
   Shirley Credle of Beaufort, S.C., wife of Dr. Bernard Credle, an
obstetrician, said Hurt called their house sometime after he arrived
in the state in late October 1982 to film ``The Big Chill.''
   Hurt was referring to dancer Sandra Jennings, 32, who was then
about eight months pregnant with Hurt's son, Alexander Devon Hurt,
now 6.
   Jennings claims a common-law marriage exists between her and Hurt
under South Carolina statutes. She says she now wants a ``divorce''
and up to half of everything he has earned in the past 6{ years.
   Jennings' lawyer, A. Richard Golub, estimates Hurt's worth at $10
million.
   Mrs. Credle said she did not recognize Hurt's voice until he
identified himself but then she remembered his voice from the movie
``Body Heat.''
   ``Is this Mrs. Doctor?'' Mrs. Credle quoted Hurt as asking. She
said she told him she was and Hurt said, ``Can I speak to the doctor
about my wife?''
   She said she never met Hurt or Jennings.
   Jennings' claim is based on four weeks she spent with Hurt in
Beaufort, from Dec. 9, 1982, to Jan. 10, 1983, while he was filming
``The Big Chill.''
   Hurt reportedly learned he was divorced from actress Mary Beth
Hurt on Dec. 9, 1982, after seven years of marriage. Jennings argues
that from that day on, a common-law marriage has existed between her
and Hurt although there was never a formal ceremony.
   New York, where the two lived most of the time, does not
recognize common-law marriages.
   Golub said Mrs. Credle's testimony proved Hurt and Jennings were
living as husband and wife in South Carolina, but since Mrs. Credle
could not say for certain that the call came after Dec. 9, 1982, the
value of her testimony is questionable.
   State Supreme Court Justice Jacqueline Silbermann, who is hearing
the trial without a jury, must decide whether a common-law marriage
exists. The judge has indicated that Jennings will have a hard time
proving her case.
   Jennings was on the stand part of Wednesday's court session for
cross-examination, and Hurt's lawyer, Martin Shelton, showed that
her testimony was sometimes inconsistent with earlier sworn
statements.
   For example, she once said Hurt had her sign a prenuptial
agreement on Dec. 3, 1982, in which she forfeited any claims to his
money. She later testified she had learned they signed the agreement
around Christmas that year.
   Hurt testified no agreement was ever signed.
   In a sworn affidavit, Jennings said Hurt told her it would be
unseemly for them to have a civil marriage ceremony with her being
nine months pregnant and everybody thinking they were already
married.
   In court Wednesday, she testified that Hurt had never said
anything about a civil ceremony being unseemly. The trial is
scheduled to resume Thursday.
</TEXT>
