<FIRST>r w AM-Fiske     06-21 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fiske,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Aide Says Bush Expected to Nominate Fiske</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department spokesman said Wednesday
that President Bush is expected to nominate Robert B. Fiske Jr., who
has come under fire from some conservatives, to be deputy attorney
general.
   Consultation with senators opposed to Fiske has delayed the
formal nomination, said David Runkel, chief spokesman for Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh. Runkel added that ``it is our expectation
that Mr. Fiske will be nominated and confirmed'' by the Senate.
   Runkel said Thornburgh spoke with a number of Republican senators
who signed a letter last week urging Bush not to nominate Fiske. He
declined to identify those speaking with Thornburgh.
   The letter was signed by 14 senators, including Sen. Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., the ranking GOP member of the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
   It charged that Fiske acted improperly when he chaired the
American Bar Association's judicial screening panel by giving names
of prospective nominees to liberal organizations which then used the
information to mobilize opposition to the candidates.
   The ABA has said that the names were given to the organizations
as part of an effort to determine if the candidates had a history of
bias against women and minorities.
   Asked why Bush has not sent Fiske's name to the Senate, Runkel
said ``there have been questions raised by members of the Senate
concerning the ABA's role in the evaluating the professional
qualificiations'' of judicial candidates.
   ``Some discussions have been going on'' regarding Fiske's role at
the ABA, Runkel said.
   The Justice Department has said that Fiske, a partner in a large
New York law firm and who was once U.S. attorney there, would not be
involved in picking judges for the federal bench.
   Despite the conservative opposition, Bush has indicated he
planned to nominate Fiske. At a gathering of U.S. attorneys Friday
at the White House, Bush said a number of key officeholders in his
administration had been U.S. attorneys.
   ``We hope to see yet another _ Bob Fiske of New York _ joining
our ranks here soon,'' Bush said, without elaborating.
</TEXT>
