<FIRST>u a AM-FreedomCaravan 1stLd-Writethru a0714 06-21 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freedom Caravan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0714,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Gather To Remember Slain Civil Rights Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with later speeches, comments,
attendance 1,000, picking up at the 6th graf previous, ``The church.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XPHL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of civil rights veterans and
movement newcomers gathered outside a once-burned rural church
Wednesday to honor three young men who died 25 years ago in the
struggle to register black voters.
   ``We deeply regret what happened here 25 years ago,'' said
Secretary of State Dick Molpus, a Philadelphia native. ``We wish we
could bring them back. Every decent person in Philadelphia and
Neshoba County feels that way.''
   The event, held on the grounds of the Methodist church where
James Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner had been the
night they were killed by Ku Klux Klansmen, showed that
``Mississippi and America are far different places than they were 25
years ago,'' Gov. Ray Mabus said.
   More than 1,000 people sat in folding chairs placed in the
reddish dust on the church grounds with the hot June sun bearing
down on the nearly three-hour ceremony.
   Attending the ecumenical service at Mount Zion Methodist Church
were relatives of the three slain men and 470 people from
Philadelphia, Pa., and New York whose ``Philadelphia to Philadelphia
Project,'' bus caravan arrived Tuesday in nearby Meridian.
   ``This is a bittersweet moment for me,'' said Rita Schwerner
Bender, Schwerner's widow. ``Sad because it recalls personal pain,
but good because I have the opprtunity _ after all this time _ to
say hello again to many people whose kindess and courage were beyond
explaining.''
   The church has special significance for the civil rights struggle
in Mississippi because it is where Chaney, Goodman and Schwerner had
gone to investigate a fire the day they were killed by Ku Klux
Klansmen.
   The service was part of a daylong series of activities in rural
eastern Mississippi on Wednesday's 25th anniversary of the murders.
   A couple of hours before the service, about 200 people crowded
into tiny Okatibbee Baptist Cemetery near Meridian, where Chaney was
buried.
   Schwerner and Goodman were white civil rights volunteers from the
New York City area. Chaney was a young black man from Meridian.
   They were murdered by white racists in neighboring Neshoba
County. The slayings and attempted coverup by Neshoba County
officials outraged the nation.
   It also was a dramatic and tragic beginning to the so-called
``Mississippi Freedom Summer Project,'' which brought young people
from the North pouring into the state.
   An FBI investigation revealed Goodman, Schwerner and Chaney were
killed by members of the Klan. Their bodies were buried in an
earthen dam near Philadelphia, 40 miles north of Meridian.
   Molpus said state officials hoped to use the event to show the
world there have been many positive changes in Mississippi since the
bloody summer of 1964.
   ``We intend to send a message to the nation that the only thing
burning in Mississippi today is a desire for a better life for all
our people,'' Molpus said, in an oblique reference to the movie
``Mississippi Burning.''
   Mississippi did not bring murder charges in the case. However, 19
Mississipians, most from the Meridian and Philadelphia areas, were
prosecuted under federal statutes for violating the victims' civil
rights.
   Seven men eventually were convicted and an eighth pleaded guilty.
Their prison sentences ranged from three to 10 years prison but the
most any ever served was six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Slaying     06-21 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Slaying,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Federal Agent Says He Was in Team That Killed Journalist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal security agent and onetime
movie actor said Wednesday he was part of a team that killed
newspaper columnist Manuel Buendia in 1984, but he maintained he
does not know who ordered the killing.
   The Mexico City attorney general's office had police arrest
ex-agent Juan Rafael Mora Avila on Tuesday and produced him at a
news conference the next day.
   Mora said he was in a squad that killed Buendia, but said he did
not know what the operation was about.
   ``I'm a career policeman, not a criminal nor a killer,'' Mora,
36, a member of a prominent political family, told reporters.
   He said the triggerman was a police informer named Jose Luis
Ochoa Alonso, nicknamed ``El Chocorrol'' _ a type of chocolate _
because of his dark complexion. He said the man died two months ago.
   Buendia, whose front-page column in the newspaper Excelsior
exposed wrongdoing in high places, was fatally shot May 30, 1984, at
the entrance of a parking garage near his office.
   Mora said he, Ochoa and a police officer met at the now-dissolved
Federal Security Administration, similar to the FBI, the afternoon
Buendia was killed, and set out on motorcycles on a secret operation
to silence a troublemaker.
   He said he remembered hearing shots but did not witness the
killing. ``I didn't know what was happening,'' Mora told reporters.
   Assistant Attorney General Abraham Polo Uzcanga quoted Mora as
saying that after the shooting, Ochoa shouted to him, ``Let's go!''
and they rode away together.
   Ochoa then left Mora a few blocks later, Polo added.
   He quoted Mora as saying he saw Jose Antonio Zorrilla Perez,
director of security administration, when he returned to the scene
of the shooting a few minutes later.
   Mora insisted he did not know who ordered the killing.
   Zorrilla was first on the scene, minutes after Buendia was shot,
and conducted the first investigation into the case. He was arrested
June 13 in Mexico City and awaits trial on charges of homicide,
obstructing justice and abuse of authority.
   The attorney general's office called Zorrilla, 47, the mastermind
of the crime and said it is presenting evidence to prove Zorrilla
ordered the killing of Buendia _ his friend of 15 years _ when he
got wind of the columnist's intention to expose his links to
prominent drug traffickers.
   Zorrilla was director of the security administration from 1982
until the government dissolved it for widespread corruption in 1985.
   The government news agency Notimex said Mora is the grandson of
former Puebla state Gov. Maximino Avila Camacho, a onetime Secretary
of Communications and Transportation. It said he was also a
grandnephew of Manuel Avila Camacho, who was president of Mexico
from 1940 to 1946.
   Mora played piano for a rock music group and did bit parts as an
actor in at least four horror and crime B-movies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
