<FIRST>r a AM-FlagArt     06-21 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flag-On-The-Floor Activists Hail Supreme Court Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists who fought a clash between patriotism
and creativity stemming from an art student's floor display of the
U.S. flag hailed Wednesday's U.S. Supreme Court decision clearing a
flag-burning protester.
   Some Illinois lawmakers, however, said they'll fight on for a law
to punish improper displays of the flag.
   The high court, voting 5-4, threw out the conviction of a
protester sentenced to a year in jail and fined $2,000 for burning
the flag in Texas.
   The court said the flag-burning at a demonstration in Dallas
during the 1984 Republican National Convention was a form of
expression protected by the Constitution's guarantee of freedom of
speech.
   One Illinois activist said the ruling will discourage passage of
Illinois proposals to prohibit displaying the flag on the floor, but
a sponsor of such a proposal says the Texas case may have little
relevance to Illinois legislation.
   ``Hopefully, it (the ruling) will have some impact on the broader
questions of censorship so prevalent today,'' said Rich Hutchinson,
a member of the No-Mandatory Patriotism Organizing Committee in
Chicago.
   ``No doubt the reactionaries are not all going to go home,'' he
added. ``I think people really need to continue this fight.''
   The committee was formed in support of Scott Tyler, a student at
the School of the Art Institute of Chicago, who provoked angry
protests by displaying a U.S. flag in a work that critics said
invited desecration by encouraging viewers to trample Old Glory.
   Tyler, 24, was less optimistic about the impact of the Supreme
Court ruling.
   ``All these laws are going to pass. In Chicago they already
have,'' Tyler said, referring to an ordinance, enacted the day the
exhibit that included his work was closed, making it illegal to
display a flag on the floor.
   State Sen. Walter Dudycz, sponsor of a state measure to make it a
felony to display the U.S. flag on the floor, said: ``I've spoken to
one attorney who says that the decision regarding the flag case in
Texas is quite different from the one in Chicago. ... We're not sure
yet at all if there is an impact.''
   The School of the Art Institute stood behind Tyler and his work
during its display in February and March, maintaining that First
Amendment rights were at stake.
   ``We weren't overly surprised at the (Supreme Court) decision,''
said Larry Ter Molen, vice president of development and affairs for
the Art Institute of Chicago. ``We certainly hope that people in
Springfield, especially, Senator Dudycz, take this into
consideration.''
   Tyler's work, titled ``What is the Proper Way to Display a U.S.
Flag,'' included a flag spread on the floor in front of a book
soliciting comments from viewers. Also part of the work was a
montage of photographs, some showing flag-draped coffins and South
Koreans burning the flag.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
