<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Lukens-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0624,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Ask Ethics Probe of Lukens, One of Their Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 14: ``Meanwhile, Lukens,'' with Lukens polyp diagnosed
benign.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans, seeking to keep the ethics
high ground against the Democrats, took the unprecedented step
Wednesday of triggering an investigation of one of their own: Rep.
Donald E. Lukens of Ohio.
   The action on Lukens, who was convicted last month on charges
involving sex with a 16-year-old girl, came on a show of hands in a
closed-door meeting of the Republican Conference, the organization
of all GOP House members.
   Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., sought in a statement to
portray the move as part of a Republican ``total commitment to
standards of behavior for members of Congress which reflect
honorably on the institution and the nation.''
   However, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said the
Republicans seemed to be trying to score ``a political point ...
apparently at the expense of one of their own members.'' He said any
GOP attempt to make ethics a partisan issue was ``absolute nonsense
and the public knows it.''
   The House ethic committee, formally the Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct, had been expected to investigate Lukens anyway. If
the committee finds him to have violated House rules it could
recommend penalties ranging from a reprimand to expulsion.
   Republicans have set ethics reform in the House among their top
priorities for the 101st Congress. And their political operatives
hope to capitalize in the next elections by pointing to the
resignations of Democratic House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and
Whip Tony Coelho of California in the face of ethics allegations.
   But Lukens' conviction on May 30 in Franklin County, Ohio, of
contributing to the unruliness or delinquency of a minor, has been
an embarrassment to his own party. A jury found Lukens guilty of the
misdemeanor charge based on its conclusion that he had sex with the
girl at his Columbus apartment last November. Lukens, 58 and
divorced, is appealing the conviction.
   One member of the GOP leadership, Rep. Robert Walker of
Pennsylvania, sought to use Wednesday's move to turn up the heat on
Democrats, suggesting they might do well to put the ethics spotlight
on their own bad apples.
   ``We have taken that step of asking for an investigation,''
Walker said. ``I think it's an appropriate kind of step to suggest
that the other caucus ought to also be willing to do the kind of
tough thing that is involved in what our conference did today.''
   Newly elected Democratic Caucus Chairman Steny Hoyer of Maryland
retorted when told of Walker's comment: ``I'm sure Democrats are
prepared to kick out their own members who are convicted of sexually
abusing children.''
   Although Lukens has announced he will seek re-election, Ohio
state GOP chairman Robert Bennett has said he will not be on the
party's ticket in 1990, and the senior member of the state's GOP
House delegation, Rep. Chalmers Wylie, has said Lukens ``should do
the gentlemanly thing and resign.''
   Lukens has vowed to fight, and his spokesman said Wednesday's
action was welcome because an ethics probe could ``once and for all
bring forth the truth about this entire episode.''
   The spokesman, William Jarrell, said Lukens was hampered in court
because he was not permitted to cast doubt on the motives and
credibility of the girl and her mother, who were Lukens' accusers.
``Now we'll be able to bring forth the background and the motives,''
he said.
   Meanwhile, Lukens learned Wednesday that a polyp removed from his
colon was benign. Spokesman Jarrell said Lukens was in good health
and the throat cancer diagnosed in 1984 remains in remission.
   In presenting the Republican resolution, Michel said it was
unprecedented for the conference to call for an ethics probe of one
of its own members.
   The document asks the ethics panel to ``determine whether Rep.
Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens failed to conduct himself at all times in a
manner which reflects creditably on the House of Representatives.''
   It notes that House members, ``in order to perform their
constitutional duties, must conduct themselves with integrity'' and
that House rules require conduct which will not bring disrepute on
the institution.
   Michel said the GOP will live up to its constitutional obligation
to police its own members ``no matter how distasteful or painful.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
