<FIRST>u w AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 06-21 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Seeks Volunteers to Help Protect Parks, Praises Coleman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 5-6 bgng: ``After speaking,'' to update with Dukakis
quip; one graf edited for transition and picks up graf 6 1st Ld: `Coleman
won,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, continuing to trumpet his
theme of volunteerism, called Wednesday for more Americans to donate
time to help protect national parks and other natural resources.
   ``It is time to renew our commitments, both to nature and to our
fellow man,'' Bush said at a convention of recreational vehicle
owners. He spoke to a crowd of several thousand people.
   Bush, offering no new specifics, outlined to the Family Motor
Coach Association the environmental proposals he has submitted to
Congress.
   ``We need to get the word out, that our national parks and other
federal land management agencies depend on volunteers,'' Bush said.
``This is just the kind of voluntary, local effort it will take to
bring us into a better partnership with nature.''
   After speaking at a muddy fairgrounds, the president addressed a
crowd of some 2,000 Republicans at a $100-a-plate unity banquet.
Praising Republican Marshall Coleman for his gubernatorial primary
victory, Bush jokingly offered Coleman some ``free advice.''
   ``Don't film your TV ads riding around in a tank,'' said Bush,
referring to an ad made by Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis that Bush frequently made fun of during his election
campaign last year.
   The president said Virginia would be ``a battleground between the
parties in the 1990s'' and called Coleman ``a trailblazer.''
   Coleman won a hard-fought GOP primary last week by defeating
former Sen. Paul Trible and Rep. Stan Paris. He will face Democratic
Lt. Gov. Douglas Wilder in November.
   Bush called the GOP primary a ``rough and tumble competition,''
but said ``now that the dust has settled, we are all still
Republicans.''
   ``We will take our Republican message _ a message of hope and
opportunity _ to the black and other minority voters of Virginia,''
Bush said in comments apparently designed to undercut support for
Wilder, who could become the nation's first elected black governor.
   In his speech to the motor coach group, Bush sought support for
his environmental proposals to increase federal spending on
recreational land acquisition by $200 million in 27 states, and for
a like amount in new funding for wetlands acquisition.
   On another program, Bush said his administration would identify
by the end of the week 25 new ``back-country byways'' for federal
protection to add to the existing 43 National Forest Scenic Byways.
   ``I want to preserve ... those picturesque roads that offer power
views of the nation's natural splendor,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
