<FIRST>r a AM-TokenSuit     06-21 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Token Suit,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sues for $20.35 Because Discount Tokens Unavailable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter is suing the New Jersey Highway
Authority for $20.35 because its discount tokens were always sold
out, and when he did manage to buy some, they sold him a slug.
   ``If you've got a mule, the only way you can get it to do
something is to get its attention first,'' Paul Schlichtman said
Wednesday. ``I'm filing the suit to get their attention, then I'm
going to get them to do something _ give me the money they owe me.''
   Five times last week he tried to buy rolls of tokens for the
Garden State Parkway at the Essex toll plaza, and every time he was
told they were sold out, he said. A roll of 40 tokens costs $10, a
savings of $4. Beginning next month $10 will buy only 30 tokens.
   The 35 cents demanded in the suit is for a slug Schlichtman says
the Highway Authority sold him in a roll of tokens he was able to
buy. A toll collector refused to reimburse him for the slug, he said.
   Schlichtman's says his case is solid. He collected receipts every
time he was told there were no tokens and he has the names of the
toll booth employees.
   Schlichtman, a South Orange resident who works in New York City,
said he spends about $1,000 a year on highway tolls.
   ``Toll booths are a major part of my life,'' he said. ``I spend
more time sitting at toll booths than I do with any other part of my
day. They're ridiculous and obnoxious.''
   Highway Authority spokesman Dennis Ingoglia said the agency would
not comment on the case because it was in litigation.
   But he said motorists who are sold slugs can either mail the
slugs to the Highway Authority for a refund, or get a refund at a
toll plaza administration building. Toll collectors are not
permitted to make refunds, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
