<DOCNO> AP890621-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Market     06-21 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Market,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Liquidates Five Brokerages In Wake of Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday closed five
stock brokerages caught in the biggest scandal in the Brazilian
market's history.
   Among the houses liquidated was Capitanea Distribuidora, owned by
Elmo Camoes, who Monday quit as president of the Central Bank,
Brazil's equivalent to the U.S. Federal Reserve.
   Camoes owns 99 percent of the brokerage, which was caught short
in the unprecedented scandal allegedly caused by the speculation of
a single investor, multimillionaire businessman Naji Nahas.
   The liquidations, signed by acting Bank president Wadico Bucchi,
also included the brokerages Ney Carvalho, Celton, Titular and Beta.
The five houses ran up a debt equivalent to $64 million.
   Nahas, 42, the No. 1 investor in Brazil's $30 billion stock
market, bounced checks worth $31 million to several brokerages used
to purchase stock futures, said the Brazilian Securities Commission.
   Nahas had borrowed heavily to invest in blue-chip stocks, taking
advantage of a rule that allowed him to pay five days later, said
the commission, which is the rough equivalent to the U.S. Securities
and Exchange Commission.
   Meanwhile, he pumped up the stock's price by buying large amounts
of common stock, meaning the shares he received later were worth
more. When banks restricted credit for that type of operation,
Nahas' checks to several brokerages were returned for lack of funds.
   A judge in Sao Paulo, the nation's financial center, on Tuesday
rejected a request by a prosecutor for the arrest of Nahas, ruling
there was not enough evidence to show he was responsible for stock
manipulation. But the Justice Ministry has barred Nahas from leaving
the country.
   There are nine stock exchanges in Brazil, and Nahas had been
playing principally on the Rio market. Rio and Sao Paulo are the
principal exchanges.
   The Monday after the scandal broke on June 9th, the commission
declared a one-day stock market holiday to prevent panic among
investors, but the government refused to bail out the brokerages or
the Rio Exchange.
   On Saturday, Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange President Sergio
Barcellos announced he was taking an indefinite leave of absence.
   The scandal prompted an investigation of 29 brokerages by the
commission.
   The markets began to recover Tuesday from a week-long tailspin
that saw share prices plunge by more than 34 percent. The Rio Stock
Exchange rose 10.5 percent and the Sao Paulo exchanges closed up
15.3 percent.
   On Wednesday, the Rio exchange fell by 0.1 percent, while in Sao
Paulo the market closed up 3.9 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
