<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0699,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Questions Whether Council Will Be Fair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 13-15 bgng: ``Margarita Suarez,'' with embassy
comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A privately financed group studying
preparations for the Nicaraguan election questioned Wednesday
whether the council appointed by the Sandinista government to
oversee the campaign and balloting will be fair.
   The Bipartisan Commission on Free and Fair Elections said the
appointment of Mariano Faillos, a member of the ruling party, as
president of the Supreme Electoral Council ``raises questions about
the independence'' of the five-member panel.
   In addition, the group said, it ``would have improved the
composition'' of the body if both of the two members representing
the political opposition had been drawn from Nicaragua's ``Group of
14'' opposition parties.
   Instead, President Daniel Ortega nominated and the Nicaraguan
National Assembly appointed Aman Sandino, a member of the Democratic
Conservative Party, to one of the two slots.
   Leaders of the ``Group of 14'' do not recognize the Democratic
Conservatives as an opposition party, but consider them allied with
the governing Sandinistas.
   Nevertheless, the commission said, Sandino is considered a
dissident in his own party and ``some say this proves Sandino's
sufficient independence'' from the Sandinistas.
   ``Given these perspectives, it is uncertain at this point whether
the five appointments are balanced and fair,'' the commission said.
   Curtin Winsor Jr., co-chairman of the commission, who was
ambassador to Costa Rica during the Reagan administration, said the
commission hopes to meet with the electoral council soon and has
applied for visas to enter Nicaragua sometime this summer.
   On June 12, the State Department accused Nicaragua of trying to
restrict foreign monitoring of the balloting by requiring Americans
_ for the first time _ to acquire entry visas as of July 1.
   The commission released letters it has written to President Bush
and Secretary of State James A. Baker III asking for an opportunity
to brief them on its work.
   Former Sen. Gaylord Nelson, D-Wis., the other co-chairman of the
commission, said the group would request a meeting with Ortega and
had begun efforts to meet with other Central American presidents.
   Nelson said a number of trips to Nicaragua were planned,
beginning in late July or early August and continuing through the
elections that are to be held in February under an agreement between
Ortega and the governments of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and
Honduras.
   Margarita Suarez, press officer for the Nicaraguan Embassy, said
she assumed the visas would be granted, but ``the official position
is that the only people who will be allowed to be observers are
those that have been invited to be observers by the government.''
   ``There is really no restrictions on the visas, unless someone is
really undesirable,'' Ms. Suarez said. ``There is no new
qualification that people must go through simply because they are
Americans.''
   Ms. Suarez said the embassy had not yet received a copy of the
commission's report.
   The commission said its proposals were ``but the minimal
requirements for a free and fair electoral campaign and election.''
   ``They are consistent with Central American practices and are by
no means ideal standards or an attempt to impose U.S. practices on
Nicaragua,'' the panel said.
   The commission, which held hearings here May 9-11, is sponsored
by the conservative World Freedom Foundation.
   The group said that ``international observers, press, and
broadcast media must have the right to travel throughout the country
during the campaign to monitor the electoral process.''
   It said polling must be permitted, there must be ``reasonable
opposition access'' to press, radio and television, and laws giving
the government censorship and control over media outlets must be
suspended during the campaign.
   It proposed that Nicaragua, which has no voter registration
system, establish one by the beginning of the campaign on Sept. 1.
   Although few countries in Latin America allow absentee voting,
the commission said a significant number of Nicaraguans now live
abroad in exile and ``fairness calls for some form of participation
by these people in deciding their homeland's future.''
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
