<DOCNO> AP890621-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Dance     06-21 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dance Theater of Harlem Celebrates 20th Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of touring the world, winning rave
reviews in dozens of languages and being the first major American
ballet company to tour the Soviet Union, the Dance Theater of Harlem
opened its 20th anniversary season Wednesday night with a
performance of ``Giselle.''
   Arthur Mitchell, executive director and co-founder of the
company, spoke before the start of the perfomance, thanking the City
Center audience for its support and the city of New York for a $2.5
million grant that will be used to renovate the Harlem facility and
other properties.
   ``The fact that we have survived and gotten here in 20 years is a
miracle,'' Mitchell said.
   Dancer-choreographer-actor-designer Geoffrey Holder and his wife,
the dancer Carmen DeLavallade, congratulated Mitchell and the
company during opening ceremonies to celebrate the anniversary.
   Holder said the company was ``an inspired idea'' and that
Mitchell had a lot of courage.
   ``Arthur is a gem cutter,'' said Miss DeLavallade. ``He went into
a Harlem garage with all these wonderful jewels and formed a crown
and placed it in Harlem.''
   Two decades ago, the talented and brash principal dancer from the
New York City Ballet sliced through the racial barriers that had
kept blacks from succeeding in classical ballet and founded the
vibrant and youthful company. Mitchell, who retired from the City
Ballet in 1970, has led the troupe to international renown, but has
kept its roots firmly planted in Harlem.
   The original dance school remains in the primarily black uptown
Manhattan neighborhood, and many of this season's New York
performances will be held in Aaron Davis Hall at City College.
   The Dance Theater of Harlem prides itself on preserving American
dance repertory, and does an excellent job of presenting works that
otherwise would disappear because they are not performed. The
company also demonstrates a variety of styles and moods, from the
classical ``Swan Lake'' to the neoclassical ``Serenade'' to the
contemporary and ethnic ``Dougla'' to the folk ballet ``John Henry.''
   Last year, the troupe captivated audiences in the Soviet Union
with its magical retelling of John Taras' stunning ``Firebird,'' set
to the original Igor Stravinsky score.
   The company's ``Giselle,'' which had its New York premiere in
1984 after a London debut, is a departure from the traditional work
set in Austria. This ``Giselle'' takes place in Louisiana in the
years following the Civil War. It is as creole as crawfish and
gumbo, and just as luscious with its mossy sets and pastel costumes.
   Frederic Franklin, who danced with the Ballet Russe de Monte
Carlo from the 1930s-'50s, staged the ballet for the company without
departing too much from the choreography by Jean Coralli and Jules
Perrot.
   The lithe Virginia Johnson, the company's prima ballerina, danced
the title role of the young woman who dies of unrequited love. She
was partnered with Eddie J. Shellman, who is paired with her in many
of the company's works. Shellman, whose barrel turns and leaps have
made him a stand-out in the troupe, portrayed the callous suitor,
Albert.
   Miss Johnson displayed a wonderful technical astuteness en
pointe. And Judy Tyrus, who will dance the lead on June 25, was
perky and refreshing in her pas de deux with Augustus van Heerden.
   During its New York run through July 2, the Dance Theater of
Harlem will perform works from its repertoire, including
Balanchine's ``Allegro Brillante,'' Mitchell's ``Holberg Suite'' and
Glen Tetley's ``Voluntaries.'' The company also will premiere works
by Nijinska.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Secchia     06-21 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Secchia,1st Ld-Writethru,a0757,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secchia Confirmed As Ambassador to Italy</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS 4 grafs to include three additional ambassador confirmations.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Wednesday confirmed Michigan
Republican activist Peter Secchia as ambassador to Italy despite
concerns by some that his penchant for vulgar language might lead
him into diplomatic hot water.
   Secchia, dubbed by some Italian publications as ``the ambassador
of dirty words,'' pledged during confirmation hearings before the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee that he would clean up his
language while serving as a diplomat.
   But Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., expressed concern that
Secchia would be unable to do that, saying he feared the nominee
would embarrass President Bush and the United States.
   Pell abstained on the vote.
   Secchia, a multimillionaire timber executive who served as a GOP
national committeeman, is credited by Bush loyalists for engineering
Bush's victory in the Michigan 1988 caucuses over the Rev. Pat
Robertson.
   Others confirmed later in the day were:
   _Former Indiana Gov. Robert D. Orr as ambassador to Singapore.
   _Morton Abramowitz of Washington, a career Foreign Service
officer, as ambassador to Turkey.
   _ Edward N. Ney of New York as ambassador to Canada.
