<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Who'sDebut     06-21 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Who's Debut,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Who Opens Tour in Glens Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GLF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENS FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock 'n' roll relics are dusting off
their guitars and banging their drums quickly for a spate of reunion
tours this summer, starting with Wednesday's debut of The Who
talking 'bout their generation.
   The Who, which splintered after a ``farewell tour'' in 1982,
reassembled at the small Glen Falls Civic Center in upstate New York
arena with a series of songs from the nearly two-decade-old rock
opera, ``Tommy.''
   The Who is just one group planning a revival in the coming
months. The Rolling Stones will be touring this fall and former
Beatle Ringo Starr is going on his first solo tour, as will veterans
like Billy Preston, Joe Walsh, Clarence Clemons and former Band
members.
   Other bands from the 1970s that had long since broken up, such as
the Doobie Brothers and the Allman Brothers, are planning reunion
tours.
   The Who have scheduled concerts in 36 stadiums across the country
this summer in a tour marking the band's 25th anniversary. They'll
also do two special charity performances of ``Tommy'' at indoor
venues in New York and Los Angeles.
   It all started Wednesday when Pete Townshend, dressed in a baggy
gray suit with his hair swept back in a ponytail, grimaced as he
sang a high note in ``1921,'' one of ``Tommy's'' opening songs.
   A crowd of slightly more than 5,000 roared when singer Roger
Daltrey shattered one pair of tambourines and then tossed it aside.
   A giant video screen designed for stadiums beamed close-ups of
the band and a series of colorful flags stitched together served as
a stage backdrop.
   In a three-hour show, The Who performed their classics ``Who Are
You,'' ``Substitute,'' ``My Generation,'' ``Won't Get Fooled
Again,'' and ``Baba O'Riley.'' They played 38 songs and two acts.
   A June 23 show in Toronto, the city where the band played its
last show in 1982, was originally scheduled to be the tour opener.
But the band added Wednesday night's performance as a warm up.
   The band's tour has been criticized by some in the music
community, who note that members Townshend, John Entwistle and
Daltrey haven't had nearly the same financial success with
individual tours and records as they did with The Who.
   The cover of the current Musician magazine, for instance, shows a
drawing of the three band members as the centerpiece of a large
dollar bill.
   Tickets sales have indeed been brisk. Tickets here sold out
within 82 minutes of being offered for sale.
   The three remaining original members of the band were
supplemented by drummer Simon Phillips, keyboard player John
Bundrick and guitarist Steve Bolton.
   The band has no new album out but they plan to release the record
``The Iron Man'' next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0203 </DOCNO>
