<FIRST>r a AM-China-StudentLetter     06-21 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Student Letter,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students Call For Economic Sanctions Against China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese students across the nation have sent a
letter to Congress urging stricter sanctions against their homeland,
and to express their impatience with the Bush Administration's
response to the Beijing killings.
   ``What bothers me is not what is being done, but what is being
said,'' said Pei Min Xin, a graduate student at Harvard University
who helped draft the letter.
   ``Secretary of State (James A.) Baker says we should treat this
relationship as a very important one to preserve. But for all
intents and purposes, the relationship is dead and gone,'' he said
Wednesday.
   The letter, co-signed by Chinese student organizations from 68
American universities _ including Harvard and Yale University,
Bush's alma mater _ and Scotland's University of Edinburgh, says
economic and diplomatic sanctions against the hard-line Chinese
government can be as effective as U.S. sanctions were against
Poland's communist regime.
   ``(Congress) should now take the lead in promoting `universal
respect for and observance of human rights and fundamental freedoms'
by themselves imposing sanctions against the goverment of Deng
Xiaoping and by urging America's allies to do the same,'' the letter
said.
   The organizations that signed it represent more than 7,000
Chinese students, said Pei, who Tuesday appeared before U.S. House's
subcommittee on international banking and outlined the letter's
proposed economic sanctions.
   Pei, a 31-year-old political science student, said the United
States' relationship with China is outdated despite Bush's personal
interest in the country where he formerly served as ambassador.
   ``The relationship was built on a common fear of the Soviet
Union,'' said Pei. ``The threat from the Soviet Union has diminished
a great deal toward the West and the United States, and has
disappeared against China.''
   The letter calls for the following steps if the Chinese
government does not ``cease and desist from further atrocities'':
   _The removal of China's ``Most Favored Nation'' trade status.
   _Freezing all credit to China from the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund, and the Asian Development Bank.
   _Reimposing restrictions on exports to China regulated by the
Commerce Department.
   ``These sanctions must remain in place until martial law is
lifted and all reprisals against the leaders and supporters of the
pro-democracy moveent are terminated,'' the letter said.
   If China continues to arrest the demonstrators and does not
commute the death sentences imposed on some, the Chinese students
propose:
   _The U.S. ambassador to the United Nations should call for
emergency sessions of the U.N. Security Council and General Assembly.
   _Ending all credit guarantees against China.
   _Suspension of the procession of China's application to
membership in the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the
intertional trade body.
   On Wednesday, the Chinese government executed three men for their
roles in the student-led protests that ended when the army moved
against students and supporters in Beijing on June 3-4, killing up
to 3,000 people, according to some estimates.
</TEXT>
