<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 2ndLd-Writethru a0800 06-21 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0800,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf of Calhoun item to CORRECT to 110-meter hurdles.
Separate on Bevilacqua moved as a0686; separate on Calhoun moved on sports
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Joseph Bevilacqua</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph A. Bevilacqua, whose lifelong
friendships with reputed mobsters tarnished and eventually ended his
career as Rhode Island's top legislator and top judge, died
Wednesday. He was 70.
   Bevilacqua was elected to the Rhode Island House in 1954 and
maintained a successful criminal law practice while he rose through
the ranks to become majority leader in 1966 and speaker in 1969.
   Questions about his ties to criminals came into the open when the
General Assembly elected him chief justice of the state Supreme
Court in 1976. Investigations were conducted, and in 1985 Bevilacqua
was censured by the Commission on Judicial Tenure and Discipline for
associating with known criminals. In 1986, after the General
Assembly launched impeachment proceedings, Bevilacqua resigned.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lee Calhoun</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two-time Olympic gold medalist Lee Calhoun, who
won the 110-meter hurdles with dramatic victories in Melbourne and
Rome, died Wednesday of complications related to a stroke. He was 56.
   Calhoun was the head track and field coach at Western Illinois
University since 1980.
   He was the first man to win successive Olympic hurdle titles. His
first came in the 110-meter hurdles at the 1956 Games at Melbourne,
when as a virtual unknown he slipped past heavily favored teammate
Jack Davis in a photo finish and his time of 13.5 seconds
established an Olympic record.
   Four years later at Rome, Calhoun again needed a photo finish to
nip teammate Willie May by one one-hundreth of a second for his
second gold medal.
   The Laurel, Miss. native was a seven-time national champion and
also held world records in the 110-, 50-, 60- and 70-meter hurdles.
</TEXT>
