<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     06-21 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Arrested as Police Break up Student Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas and beat
protesters with truncheons to break up a rally Wednesday by hundreds
of students demanding that private tuition fees be rolled back,
witnesses said. At least 11 students were arrested.
   Witnesses said they saw scores of protesters hit in the head and
other parts of the body during the baton charge, but there were no
immediate reports of serious injuries.
   Police charged the demonstrators, who numbered about 2,000, when
they ignored repeated warnings to disperse peacefully after their
permit to hold a rally in front of the Department of Education
expired at 6 p.m., the witnesses said.
   Police said they planned to release the 11 arrested students
after an investigation to determine if they should be charged with
illegal assembly, a misdemeanor.
   The students were protesting a 15 percent tuition increase at
private schools this month, the beginning of the school year. With
the increase, annual tuition runs $95 on average for private
elementary and high schools and about $145 at colleges.
   Per capita income in the Philippines is about $600 a year.
</TEXT>
