<FIRST>r a AM-CargoDoorSearch     06-21 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cargo Door Search,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Investigators Want To Retrieve Cargo Door That Blew Off United
Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators have asked the Navy to
retrieve a cargo door that tore off a Boeing 747 jet over the
Pacific Ocean nearly four months ago, sending nine passengers to
their deaths.
   The door is believed to be resting on the ocean floor more than
three miles underwater and about 85 miles southwest of Honolulu.
United and Boeing, which would share in the cost, said they support
the recovery effort.
   The National Transportation Safety Board asked the Navy to search
for the door, NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said Tuesday. The Navy
said Wednesday it has not received a formal request.
   United has encouraged the NTSB to look for the door, said
spokesman Rob Doughty.
   ``We're glad they've made that decision,'' Doughty said. ``It may
answer some questions that may be lingering.''
   Doughty said he didn't know when the search would be made, but
ABC said Tuesday it's scheduled for October.
   NTSB investigators have said retrieving the door would help
determine what caused it to pop open at an altitude of 22,000 feet
on Feb. 24, ripping a 10-by-20-foot hole in the fuselage. But
recovering it is not considered essential, Lopatkiewicz said.
   The jumbo jet was flying from Honolulu to Auckland, New Zealand,
when the accident occurred. The pilots managed to return to Honolulu
with the 345 people still aboard.
</TEXT>
