<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-Wetlands-Marmande Adv26   06-21 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wetlands-Marmande, Adv 26,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, June 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Landowner: `Our Way of Life Is Going With It'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Disappearing Wetlands I</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THERIOT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To Marvin Marmande Jr., the dying oak is a
symbol.
   ``It was a beautiful, full-grown tree when my great-grandfather
first saw it 140 years ago. I remember when I was 7 or 8 years old,
having picnics with my mama and the family here, and the branches
spread way over there,'' Marmande, 31, said, sweeping his arm toward
a point 30 feet away.
   ``Now, it's dying. Its roots are in salt water.''
   The plight of the 200-year-old live oak mirrors what's happening
to all marshland in coastal Louisiana. Erosion and subsidence claim
30-50 square miles of wetland each year.
   ``Our way of life is going with it,'' Marmande said. ``There used
to be 70 families making a living on this land. This was all
farmland, sugar cane and potatoes, mostly, and cattle. ...
   ``This land used to support seven families just for trapping _
muskrat, otter, mink. Now there's just one. We used to catch worlds
of crawfish here, but it's salt water now.''
   The Marmande land is on a finger of high ground built by 700
years of spring floods on the Mississippi River. The fresh water
marshes that surrounded the peninsula were nourished by bayous and
streams running from the river to the Gulf of Mexico.
   The river is trapped by levees now, and the bayous and streams no
longer carry fresh water to the marshes.
   The 8-mile-long Marmande peninsula, about a half-mile wide at its
landward base, ends at a 60-acre plateau that stands a dizzying 7
feet above sea level _ really high ground in these parts.
   ``You can't get there, except by boat,'' Marmande said. ``The
road's under water in a couple of spots _ used to be 3 or 4 feet
above sea level.`'
   Much of the damage has been done by the Houma Navigation Canal, a
straight-shot channel dredged 30 years ago to provide quicker access
to the Gulf of Mexico. Some of the salt water comes up through Cades
Lake and Minors Canal.
   Marmande believes in levees and pumps to isolate the sources of
salt water and hold back erosion.
   ``Look at what they've done in Holland. They've reclaimed land
from the sea,'' he said.
   He points to a neighbor's land where a distinct line shows the
intrusion of salt water _ a vigorous green stand of cypress on one
side of the line, naked brown stumps on the other side.
   ``He built his own levee and put in his own pumps,'' Marmande
said. ``But you can't get permits to do that anymore. We can't even
get permits to raise a levee that's been there 14 years, and it's
sinking.''
   ``I consider it my obligation to try to do something about it.
Maybe we can never put it back the way it was, but we can stop it
from getting worse.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
