<DOCNO> AP890621-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-Wetlands-Authement Adv26   06-21 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wetlands-Authement, Adv 26,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, June 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>In One Generation, Water Line Moved 150 Yards</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Disappearing Wetlands I</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND CAILLOU, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Addie Authement tied his square-bowed
work boat to a piling 150 yards out from the shore of Lake Boudreaux.
   ``Me and my boy stuck this piling here on dry ground when he was
about 15 years old. He's 34 now, and there's about 5 feet of water
here. We trawl for shrimp all around that piling,'' Authement said.
   The piling is painted red. A red reflector is fixed to its top.
It used to mark the entrance to a narrow channel that Authement and
his brother dug to get their pirogues to the lake.
   ``It was just wide enough to push-pole our pirogues, a
little-bitty canal. Not even a canal, a ditch,'' he said.
   It became a canal about 20 years ago when Terrebonne Parish
widened it to about 10 feet, installed a pumping station and began
using it to drain rain water flooding into Lake Boudreaux.
   The canal is 20-30 feet wide now and getting wider, its banks
crumbling with every storm wind.
   Salt water from the Gulf of Mexico killed groves of tall cypress
trees and old oaks, leaving stark, dead stumps. Salt water also
killed the marsh grass that fed muskrat and nutria.
   A dank salt water bay covers land that was a garden patch when
Authement's son was born.
   ``Who'd have told me 30 years ago that I'd be catching crabs
there some day? I'd have told them they were lying,'' Authement
said. ``The son of a gun stinks, too.''
   Much of the land loss became inevitable 50 years ago when the
Corps of Engineers completed flood control projects on the
Mississippi River. Levees trapped the river, robbing the marshes of
fresh water and silt, and the spongy wetlands began contracting and
sinking beneath the water.
   ``That used to be a big coteau _ real high ground,'' he said,
pointing to an oak stump jutting out of the water, its trunk about 4
feet in diameter. ``I used to shoot squirrels there.''
   Authement and his wife celebrated their 45th wedding anniversary
in April. In the early years of their marriage, they shelled shrimp
for 12{ cents an hour, shucked oysters for 50 cents a gallon, fished
and sold sun-dried shrimp.
   ``It was hard, but it was a good life,'' he said.
   He blames the Houma Navigation Canal for most of the problems.
Dredged to provide straight-line access from Houma shipyards to
oilfields in the Gulf, the canal also gives salt water access to the
marshes.
   ``Forty years for all of this to go from fresh water to salt. I
don't believe we have 30 years left, unless somebody does
something,'' Authement said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-DisappearingWetlandsII Adv27-2Takes   06-21 1219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disappearing Wetlands II, Adv 27-2 Takes,1247</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, June 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part II: Searching for Ways to Turn the Tide</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   It took 700 years for the Mississippi River to
build the marshes near its mouth, but half of them have disappeared
in the last 30 years. Is there any way to stop the loss, any way to
restore what's gone? This second segment in a series, ``Disappearing
Wetlands,'' considers what can be done.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By AUSTIN WILSON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mississippi River built Louisiana's
wetlands, and only the Mississippi can restore them.
   Louisiana loses an acre of its productive wetlands every 15
minutes. At that rate, Washington, D.C., would be swallowed up in
about 14 months.
   An estimated 10 percent to 20 percent of Louisiana's loss is due
to exploration, drilling and production of oil and gas in the
marshes and offshore. The main reason for the rest of the loss is
that man, in taming the Mississippi with dams and levees, cut off
the supply of fresh water and silt that kept the wetlands green and
growing.
   Any plans for rebuilding marshes involve getting Mississippi
River water back where it used to flow naturally, but that calls for
big-ticket items. The Army Corps of Engineers is committed to
spending $130 million for just three freshwater diversion projects,
one under construction at Caernarvon, about 15 miles downriver from
New Orleans, the others in final planning stages.
   This is an impoverished state with no money to spare: its
teachers are among the nation's lowest paid, its police and fire
departments are cut back to the bone, its roads are crumbling and
its universities are underfunded. Unemployment is at 11.7 percent.
   The cheaper, less dramatic route would be to save what's left, if
possible, or delay its loss. There are plenty of proposals, from
planting trees to tearing down the levees.
   The U.S. Soil Conservation Service is testing marsh grass and
mangroves to find the toughest strains to help defeat wave action
and tie down fragile soil.
   State and federal agencies are issuing fewer permits for wetlands
activities.
   Some ideas seem too small to have any impact. Bill Good and Vance
Edwards spread discarded Christmas trees in shallow coastal waters.
Henry J. Rodriguez Jr. plants trees on marshland hummocks. Roland
Thomas sets out sprigs of marsh grass. Piles of old Christmas trees
might trap sediment and slow erosion, restoring and protecting the
marsh. Roots from new vegetation might also hold sediment.
   ``Usually, thinking big is the way to go, but we may have to
think small on this problem,'' said Dave Carney of the Army Corps of
Engineers, the first biologist to be named manager of a wetlands
restoration project by the Corps.
   Louisiana Land and Exploration Co. thinks small in a big way _
400 water-control weirs on the 600,000-plus acres it owns in the
coastal marshes. The land, the largest private holding of coastal
wetlands in the country, is dotted with LL&amp;E's oil wells.
   Starting in 1956, long before the plight of the wetlands was
obvious, LL&amp;E began building weirs across inlets and bayous that ebb
and flow with the tides. The low dams, their tops below water level,
are designed to break the force of waves on their way in and slow
their retreat until they have dropped their load of sediment.
   The weirs' effects have never been scientifically measured, but
comparisons with unprotected marshes show they work, asserts H.
Leighton Steward, chief executive officer and president of LL&amp;E.
   ``If there are two little natural channels going back into the
marsh, both about 30 feet wide, and you put a little weir on one and
not on the other, we can see that after a time, one is still 30 feet
wide, and the other has eroded on back into the marshes,'' Steward
said.
   ``We have areas where we have the weirs in place, and another
land owner, maybe a mile over, has never had them, and our guys can
demonstrate that our land is in better shape than theirs is,'' he
said.
   Dag Nummendal of Louisiana State University's geology department
believes such efforts are a losing fight, and the focus should be on
cutting losses, rather than spending billions of dollars trying to
win.
   He advocates a retreat from everything south of Highway 90, the
old east-west route along a natural ridge from New Orleans, down
through Morgan City, then up to Lafayette and westward to Lake
Charles.
   The Louisiana Geological Survey estimates Highway 90 will be an
oceanfront road by 2083, if nothing is done to reverse coastal
erosion.
   Nummendal recommends a rear-guard action of weirs, pumps and dams
_ anything to slow the creeping sea _ while the residents of three
dozen coastal communities head for higher ground over the next 50
years.
   ``That's ludicrous. That's too ridiculous even to consider,''
said Marvin Marmande Jr., a Houma businessman and farmer. To leave
would mean abandoning land his French-born great-grandfather bought
in 1840. ``I would be abandoning everything my father, my
grandfather and my great-grandfather worked for, if I left.''
   Carney and his fellow project manager at the Corps of Engineers,
Jay Warren, say rudimentary studies have looked at turning the river
loose below New Orleans.
   One proposal involved dredging a new navigation channel to
connect with the Mississippi River Gulf Outlet Canal, tearing down
levees and taking ship traffic out of the Mississippi.
   ``Essentially, (it would) abandon navigation in the Mississippi
River channel, let the channel silt up to whatever depth it wanted
to _ about 17 feet _ and put a lock in the river,'' Warren said.
   The Gulf Outlet Canal is an underused backdoor path from the Gulf
of Mexico to New Orleans, deemed an economic godsend when it was
dredged through the marshes 30 years ago. A major source of flooding
in Hurricane Betsy in 1965, it introduced salt water into previously
fresh marshes in St. Bernard Parish, helping to accelerate the death
of miles of cypress swamps.
   Manny Fernandez, spokesman for Gov. Buddy Roemer on environmental
matters, said letting the Mississippi go wild below New Orleans was
not realistic.
   ``There are tremendous downsides to that,'' Fernandez said. ``No.
1 is the cost. No. 2 is that you're going through a tremendous
amount of wetlands doing that excavation of a new channel.
   ``Growing up in St. Bernard Parish and seeing the tremendous loss
and devastation from the Gulf Outlet, I don't believe we ought to be
looking at dredging another channel to solve environmental
problems.''
   Carney favors building big sluices to let controlled amounts of
river water flow through the levees and dump replenishing sediment
through the marshes. The freshwater diversion project at Caernarvon,
when completed in two years, will dump 8,000 cubic feet of water
into the marshes each second.
   Fernandez said he and the head of the state Department of
Environmental Quality, Paul Templet, believe freshwater and sediment
diversion structures hold the answer to restoring the marshes.
   ``Paul Templet has said we may need as many as 20 of these
structures, rather than the one being built and the two or three
being contemplated,'' Fernandez said. ``It will take that many to
get the silt back in the marshes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-Wetlands-BarrierIslands Adv27   06-21 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wetlands-Barrier Islands, Adv 27,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, June 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`First Line of Defense' for Wetlands Is Also Vanishing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Disappearing Wetlands II</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chains of islands are strung like beads along
America's coasts _ a barrier that absorbs the force of storms and
shields the mainland.
   But the islands are disappearing. At least 50 barrier islands off
Louisiana have washed away over 30 years, exposing delicate marshes
and wetlands to direct assault by the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``Barrier islands are like your skin, the first line of defense
against infection,'' said Robert E. Stewart Jr., director of the
National Wetlands Research Center, a branch of the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service.
   However, he said, ``It would be enormously expensive to restore
them.''
   ``Something can be done, but it would be very, very expensive,''
echoed Jay Warren, a project engineer with the Army Corps of
Engineers. ``Not only would you have to restore them, but then you
have to maintain them.
   ``We had a study just last year that looked at barrier island
maintenance as a way to protect marsh behind the barrier islands and
also as a means to reduce storm surge and hurricane damage inland.
Even picking up those benefits, the cost was just prohibitive.''
   Almost 2,700 miles of barrier islands protect the coasts of 18
states along the Atlantic and the Gulf of Mexico, and all of the
islands are threatened. The West Coast has fewer barrier islands,
but they are also eroding and drifting inland.
   Fire Island, a sliver of sand and expensive cottages just east of
New York's Long Island, is losing beaches on both the seaward and
landward sides despite groins and jetties built to save them. A
million cubic yards of sand shift along the coasts of both Cape
Hatteras and Cape Cod each year.
   Texas' Galveston Island has been protected by seawalls since a
hurricane killed 6,000 people in 1900. But its beach eroded after
the wall was built _ the sort of tradeoff made wherever man has
moved onto the islands.
   Seawalls, jetties, groins and rocks all produce the same result:
they direct wave action elsewhere, and the beaches wash away.
   Andy Valence is mayor of Grand Isle, Louisiana's only developed
barrier island. A 2,000-foot section of its beach is under a state
of emergency as Gulf waters lap at a motel's pilings and close in on
state Highway 1, the only route onto the island. Valence wants to
build protective rock jetties and estimates the project will cost
about $422,000.
   Robert Jones, parish engineer and civil defense director for
nearby Terrebonne Parish, predicted the project would cost 10 times
that much and would fail unless the rocks were given a sound
foundation and provisions were made to get fresh sand to the beach.
   ``Unless it's done right, those rocks are just going to eat
themselves into the sand and disappear,'' he said.
   Jones has earned his air of authority. Five years ago, he defied
conventional advice and saved the eastern tip of Isle Derniere,
where pounding waves were threatening to cut off two-thirds of a
mile.
   Isle Derniere, French for Last Island, is the largest of
Louisiana's barrier islands at 1,800 acres. Jones' repairs have
withstood eight hurricanes, absorbing the force of tidal surges that
otherwise would have hit coastal communities unchecked.
   Jones used all natural materials. Near the area being washed over
by waves, he found deposits of especially coarse sand. His crews
scooped that sand into a protective dune that topped out at 8 feet
above sea level, then filled the holes with the finer sand off the
Gulf floor.
   Next he hired students to plant seagrass to anchor the sand.
``The key to keeping what you've got pumped up on the island is
vegetation,'' he said.
   ``In the first year of its existence, it faced three hurricane
surges, and it was completely overtopped by Hurricane Juan,'' Jones
said. ``We had a number of hurricanes every year since then.
   ``Hurricane Gilbert (last fall,) even though it hit 500 miles
away, sent a storm surge here that overtopped every levee in
southern Terrebonne Parish. ... The vegetation held up fine.''
   Jones said the best way to save the barrier islands would be to
put $10 million in trust for 10 islands, then use the interest each
year to restore one. ``At the end of 10 years, you'd go back and
start over again,'' he said.
   ``You can't think of it as a one-shot civil engineering problem.
That was my major problem to begin with,'' Jones said. ``I'm used to
putting something up in concrete and five years later having it look
the same way.
   ``The first time I went out there after a hurricane, I was very
disappointed. The geologists were ecstatic that it survived as well
as it did.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
