<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Kowanko Adv22   06-21 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Kowanko, Adv 22,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday June 22 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pete Kowanko Stars as Man of Future in `Gifted One'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of June 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pete Kowanko plays the latest in a long line
of television heroes on the run in his role as the title character
in the NBC Sunday movie ``The Gifted One.''
   Kowanko plays Michael Grant, a man of special mystical powers,
pursued by Dr. Boardman (John Rhys-Davies), an opportunistic
scientist who can hardly wait to experiment on Grant to see what
makes him tick.
   ``Michael Grant's mind uses the full potential that man's capable
of,'' said Kowanko. ``He's gifted. He can direct the electrical
power of his body like a laser to heal. He can place himself in
synch with any living thing or lock into someone else's subconscious.
   ``That gift can also be painful. He has an acute sense of right
and wrong. He doesn't want to take advantage of it in a dark way.
Nor does he want to be exploited by the military or anyone else.''
   The ``chase'' story is a favorite television premise. The most
popular was ``The Fugitive,'' which ran on ABC in 1963-67 and
starred David Janssen as a man wrongly accused of killing his wife
and was pursued by law enforcement authorities while searching for
her killer.
   In ``The Immortal,'' on ABC during 1970-71, the lead character
was a man immune to disease who was on the run because a ruthless
billionaire wanted his special antibodies. The short-lived ``Hot
Pursuit'' on NBC in 1984 focused on a young couple fleeing a false
charge of murder, and a space alien and his son were chased by
government scientists in ABC's ``Starman'' in 1986-87.
   The form even inspired a CBS sitcom parody in 1966-67, ``Run
Buddy Run,'' in which a hapless man was on the run from gangsters.
   In ``The Gifted One,'' as in ``The Fugitive,'' the hero is on a
quest of his own while being pursued. He's looking for his real
mother after learning he is not the son of the couple who raised
him; he's running from the people who want to exploit his powers.
   ``The Gifted One'' is not as mystical as ``Kung Fu,'' about a
Eurasian monk wandering the Old West while being pursued by agents
of the Chinese imperial family and American bounty hunters. But,
like ``Kung Fu,'' ``The Gifted One'' features flashbacks to the
hero's childhood.
   The movie was to have been the pilot for a possible series, but
the show is not on NBC's fall schedule.
   ``I thought we'd get picked up for a series right away,'' Kowanko
said. ``I still think we have a chance for a backup order. I think
it's a good alternative. It's not a cop show. It's a fantasy. He has
powers but he's not a super human being. He's not a space alien.''
   Kowanko's own background sounds like the concept for a series
about a man on the move.
   He was born in Australia but was raised in California and
Minnesota after his parents divorced. He returned to Australia at 15
to mine sapphires with his stepfather. He worked in construction,
was a deck hand on a Mississippi River towboat, waited tables and
was a ski bum in Colorado when he was ``discovered'' and asked to
audition for a commercial.
   ``I was an adventurous soul,'' he said. ``I worked on the
Mississippi River during my Huck Finn fantasy. I worked from St.
Paul, Minn., to Ste. Genevieve, Mo., all 27 locks and dams, pushing
15 barges. My job as deck hand was to take the barges apart because
only half could go through the locks at a time.''
   He went to New York in 1980 and was signed to a development deal
by ABC. Later, he was in the NBC series ``For Love and Honor.'' He
played Willie Wolf in the movie ``Patty,'' about the kidnaping of
Patricia Hearst by the Symbionese Liberation Army.
   In the last five years he has moved back and forth between here
and Australia, where he and his mother own a fruit farm and vineyard
in the Outback along the Tropic of Capricorn.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   KOJAK RETURNS _ Telly Savalas will revive his role as New York
detective Theo Kojak on the ABC Saturday Night Mystery Movie.
``Kojak'' was on CBS during 1973-78. ABC also is adding a segment
starring Jaclyn Smith as ``Amanda Vanderbilt,'' a financial adviser
to the wealthy. Peter Falk as ``Columbo'' and Burt Reynolds as
``B.J. Stryker'' will return to the ``Mystery Movie,'' but ABC has
dropped the ``Gideon Oliver'' segment starring Louis Gossett Jr.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs June 22</NOTE>
