<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach-Chronology Adv24-25   06-21 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach-Chronology, Adv 24-25,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Whom Do You Believe? Rhetoric As Muddled As Alaska Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spill's Reach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rhetoric surrounding the nation's
worst oil spill sometimes has grown as muddled as the North Slope
crude fouling Alaska's southern coast.
   Just how bad is the spill? How is the cleanup going? Here's a
look at three months of changing pronouncements, promises and
predictions offered by Exxon and other officials.
   _MARCH 24. The Exxon Valdez rams a reef, spilling nearly 11
million gallons of oil.
   _MARCH 25. State environmental officials call the initial
response by Exxon and Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. ``inadequate and
unacceptable.'' Alyeska spokesman Chuck O'Donnel says, ``I think our
people did an excellent job.'' The slick covers 28 square miles.
   _MARCH 30. ``We're going to pick up _ one way or the other _ all
the oil that's out there,'' Exxon spokesman Don Cornett tells
reporters in Valdez.
   _MARCH 31. The slick now covers 600 square miles. ``Absolutely
not, it has not gotten away from us,'' Cornett says. ``We are making
good progress on this cleanup.''
   _APRIL 18. Oil has killed at least 1,850 birds and 328 sea
otters. The slick has spread over 3,000 square miles. Exxon Chairman
L.G. Rawl says he's confident most beaches will be clean by
mid-September.
   ``Now I'm not going to tell you that if you go up there a year
from now you won't find some black places on some rocks, but we're
going to make every effort to get it off,'' Rawl says.
   _MAY 2. In Alaska, Exxon officials say they now plan to leave
nearly 200 miles of oiled coastline to be cleaned by nature. In
Houston, Exxon President William D. Stevens says, ``I believe we in
Exxon have shown our commitment and our determination to deal
responsibly with the spill and all its effects.''
   Oil shows up in Katmai National Park, 300 miles from where the
tanker grounded.
   _MAY 5. Exxon spokesman Joe Tucker says cleanup is ``progressing
on schedule.'' Oil is sighted 450 miles from where the tanker
grounded.
   _MAY 9. Coast Guard Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins says Exxon is as
concerned with public relations as with cleaning up oil. ``They have
sent PR people into the field instead of operators,'' he says.
   _MAY 10. Exxon President Stevens tells a congressional committee
the company ``fully expects to clean up'' by mid-September. The
wildlife death toll climbs to 9,900 birds and 613 sea otters.
   _MAY 24. ``I don't think that we would portray to you that we're
going to take every stain out of all the rocks that are out there,''
says Exxon official Otto Harrison in Valdez. ``Nor do I want to
portray to you that I think that's necessary to be environmentally
clean.''
   _JUNE 1. Coast Guard Commandant Adm. Paul Yost says he sees
progress but predicts that Exxon almost certainly will miss its
mid-September deadline. ``I think there was too much optimism,'' he
says. ``I think reality has set in.''
   _JUNE 14. Exxon officials hedge on their September deadline.
``It's always a hope,'' says Exxon spokesman Amos Plante in Seward.
``But it's tougher to predict whether we'll do it by then. That's
our plan. We've always said we will not leave it uncleaned, and if
that means coming back, so be it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
