<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach-OilRegulation Adv24-25   06-21 1067</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach-Oil Regulation, Adv 24-25,1095</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Oil Faces More Regulation in Alaska as Result of Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spill's Reach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's sense of betrayal by Big Oil is
leading to stronger regulation of the state's most profitable
industry in the long wake of the Exxon Valdez oil spill.
   It was 12 years ago this week that oil began flowing through the
800-mile trans-Alaska pipeline. Since then, the state has used its
oil wealth to build roads and schools, boost its economy and keep
its taxes low.
   But in the 12 weeks since the spill fouled Prince William Sound,
Alaskans have expressed anger over the industry's broken promise
that it could protect the environment from such a disaster.
   ``Now that we've seen the down side we're going to be much more
cautious about our relationship with the industry,'' said state
Senate President Tim Kelly, a longtime industry supporter.
   ``The message I get from my constituents is the state's going to
have to be more vigilant in its own regulation of the industry, and
we can't depend on the industry or other government entities to do
that for us,'' Kelly said.
   State legislators last month passed an initial package of bills
aimed at preventing future spills and narrowly approved a measure to
cut an oil-industry tax break. The change will cost the oil
companies operating on Alaska's North Slope an estimated $2 billion
over the next 20 years.
   Bill Webb, head of an Anchorage-based group that represents
oil-support businesses, is one of the few industry officials who has
spoken publicly against what they see as political overreaction.
   ``I guess I'm shocked, confused and extremely concerned about
where the state's relationship with its biggest industry is and
where it's heading,'' Webb said last week. ``This is the worst I've
ever seen it.''
   The tax changes and additional restrictions on the industry sent
an anti-development message about Alaska to the Lower 48, Webb
asserted.
   ``I've never seen any state that's turned and tried to do damage
to their industry like Alaska has tried to do now,'' Webb said.
``Can you imagine Michigan trying to do to the auto industry what
we're trying to do to oil?''
   Kelly said he has seen no signs that Alaska's pro-development
image has been tarnished by its recent actions against Big Oil.
   ``They're not happy, but I think that we're playing under a
different set of rules,'' he said. ``As the new rules are understood
and stability again returns to the Alaska economy, I think they're
going to work out.
   ``There may be some short-range exploration and production
losses, but in the long range the fact remains that the industry has
to go where the oil is. The oil doesn't go to them.''
   Republican Kelly voted to maintain the oil tax break, but he has
helped lead the post-spill campaign for more regulation.
   He and other legislators acknowledge that industry, state and
federal officials became complacent about the risks involved in
transporting oil across Alaska.
   ``I think after a decade of no serious and major accidents, that
we assumed that was the norm,'' the Anchorage lawmaker said. ``There
was a tendency of urban-area legislators to accept at face value
what the industry told us, because a lot of us felt what was good
for the oil industry was good for Alaska.''
   Money helped lawmakers forget the state's watchdog role, said
Sen. Pat Pourchot, an Anchorage Democrat.
   ``When everybody's making money and everybody's feeling good
about the economy, it's natural to think of yourself in partnership
with the industry. You're making money, they're making money _ it's
sort of a `we' kind of thing,'' Pourchot said.
   Many recall 1981 as a watershed year for the Legislature, a year
in which oil and development concerns began to outweigh
environmental concerns. The Republican-led Senate especially became
dominated by industry defenders.
   The Legislature, like the state, was infused with new Alaskans,
many of whom had benefitted financially from the oil boom and wanted
to see it last, Pourchot said.
   ``The whole view of boom, boom, boom and growth sort of swept the
state at that point,'' he said.
   In 1981 the Legislature restructured the way state oil taxes are
calculated and passed the tax break that remained untouched until
this year. Proponents of the changes said the cost to the state
would be negligible.
   ``In fact, it was a billion-dollar-plus loss to the state'' after
just five years, said Rep. Sam Cotten, speaker of the Democratic-led
House.
   Although Alaska has spent and saved billions of oil dollars, some
argue that its primary failure in the past decade was not getting
more money from its oil to secure the state's future when the
pipeline runs dry.
   Sen. Jay Kerttula, a Democrat who has served in the Legislature
since 1960, said lawmakers lost sight of their role as stewards of
the oil for future generations.
   ``The wrinkles were out of the bellies of Alaskans, they were
sitting there watching TV and not paying attention to their public
ownership responsibilities,'' he said. ``We weren't paying attention
to the bottom line.''
   Throughout the past decade, development-oriented legislators
opposed increased funding for the Department of Environmental
Conservation. At times the agency was given additional
responsibilities without additional funding.
   When Commissioner Dennis Kelso took over the department two years
ago, its employees were working a four-day week because of budget
cuts. He estimated then that the agency was $10 million short of the
budget it needed to meet the minimum requirements of state and
federal laws.
   But Kelso insists the cuts did not create the conditions that led
to the Valdez spill and the slow cleanup. He blames Exxon and
Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., the consortium of oil companies that
runs the pipeline, for failing to follow their own policies and the
state-approved spill-cleanup plan.
   Next year, when most legislators face re-election and a new
governor will be elected, oil industry influence will be a major
campaign issue, Cotten says.
   But Kerttula doubts concern over Big Oil's influence will last
long in a state that gets 85 percent of its revenues from the oil
industry.
   ``The industry always wins,'' he said. ``They've got very strong
economic clout and they're very firmly in control.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 24-25</NOTE>
