<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach-Psychology Adv24-25   06-21 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach-Psychology, Adv 24-25,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Alaskans Seek Ways To Lessen Emotional Impact Of Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spill's Reach</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEWARD, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chris Campabello once made $10 an hour as a
clerk in a Prudhoe Bay oilfield camp. Now she is working for free,
helping to rescue sea otters caught in the nation's biggest oil
spill.
   Each day from 6 a.m. to noon, she cracks clams and slices fish to
feed ailing otters. Each day, she feels a little better about
herself and a little worse about Big Oil.
   ``I used to believe in the oil companies. It was my job, and I
didn't want things to go badly for them,'' she says. ``I've changed
a lot.''
   So have many Alaskans in the last three months.
   The wreck of the Exxon Valdez unleashed a flood of emotion across
the nation as people mourned a pristine environment's lost innocence
and voiced anger at those who let it happen. For many Alaskans, the
anger and grief were compounded by the sense of personal
responsibility that comes from living in a state heavily dependent
on oil money.
   ``The relationship of Alaskans and oil development has always
been one of uncomfortable resignation,'' says Richard Gist, a
community psychologist from Overland Park, Kan., who helped Alaska
officials respond to the disaster.
   While some have likened the spill to a death in the family, Gist
says it's more like a messy divorce. ``In the end, you're always
telling yourself that you should have known better, that you
shouldn't have trusted the other so much,'' he says.
   Exxon accepted the blame for the accident, but many Alaskans
couldn't help but internalize the guilt, Gist says.
``Intellectually, folks know better. But emotionally, lots of people
feel it. They say, `I must have sold out.'''
   A good way to heal such emotional wounds, Gist says, is to regain
control by doing something _ anything _ to set things right. Many
Alaskans are following that advice.
   Cleanup officials and environmental groups have been flooded with
calls from Alaskans wanting to know what they can do to help. Otter
and bird rescue centers have more volunteers than they can use.
   ``When the spill hit, I got really upset,'' says Campabello, 29,
who is camping in a tent-trailer while volunteering at the Seward
otter rescue center. ``I felt it was really important not to sit
back and not do anything.''
   Reaction to the spill has evolved since March 24. ``The anger has
turned more to soul-searching, I think,'' says Dan Henry, a
schoolteacher in the southeastern Alaska town of Haines.
   ``Exxon and (tanker Capt. Joseph) Hazelwood are easy to blame.
But we are all to blame,'' Henry says. ``The people who are outraged
are the very same people who moved to Alaska because they loved the
pristine environment, and then supported the oil industry. They love
the world around them, but they brought their selfishness up with
them.''
   He admits he was among them, each year eagerly collecting his
dividend check from the Alaska Permanent Fund, a state savings
account fueled by oil revenues. Last year, the fund distributed $826
to every Alaskan.
   ``My dividend check is blood money,'' Henry says. ``I cannot hold
it in good conscience to accept that money anymore.'' He plans to
send this year's check to an environmental group and is urging
others to do the same.
   Gist says volunteering or getting politically active is valuable,
even if it accomplishes nothing but peace of mind. The key is doing
something that gives hope.
   Henry tells of some school kids in Homer who seemed to know that
without being told. As adults frantically built log booms to guard
the Kenai Peninsula town from drifting oil, the children were on the
beach, scratching messages in the sand. They wrote things like
``Ocean, we love you,'' and ``We're sorry, Mr. Sea.''
   They called them prayers to the ocean, and when one of the
children returned later to the beach, she ran to the same spot. The
tide, of course, had wiped the beach clean, but the little girl was
not disappointed.
   ``Look!'' she said. ``The ocean got our prayers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 24-25</NOTE>
