<FIRST>s w AM-TeacherPresident-Rival Adv25   06-21 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher President-Rival, Adv 25,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Futrell-Shanker Rivalry Ends Amicably</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teacher President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Mary Hatwood Futrell became president of
the National Education Association, she often found herself
overshadowed by Albert Shanker, the longtime president of the rival
American Federation of Teachers.
   ``I would make a statement and it was like you made a statement.
Half an hour later, Shanker would come back and say the same thing
and people acted like he was a guru,'' she said. ``He is the AFT. It
is like a cult.''
   Futrell says she learned not to compete with Shanker, a
philosopher and provocateur with a knack for grabbing headlines, and
instead to talk and react from a teacher's perspective. ``Now a lot
of those people have come to respect and appreciate me,'' she said.
   The AFT, which claims about 700,000 members to the NEA's 2
million, embraced the education reform movement from the start,
while the lumbering NEA edged onto the bandwagon late and largely
due to prodding by Futrell.
   The two union leaders ``had some really bad clashes at the
beginning,'' Futrell said. Shanker, the AFT president since 1974,
now calls them ``the usual clashes of two rival organizations trying
to pick up members.''
   Now, Futrell says, ``we get along fine.'' Both insist the other
has changed.
   ``He has promoted himself to the position of statesperson so he
can't fight like he used to. It would not be becoming to him,'' says
Futrell, referring to Shanker's heavy involvement with the business
community and the political establishment.
   Shanker contends that Futrell started off with the typical NEA
view of reform _ ``Why are these people criticizing the schools?
Make them go away. Everything is pretty good.'' Unlike many, he
said, Futrell eventually became convinced that improvements were
needed.
   ``She underwent a change, a growth,'' Shanker said. ``She's a
different person today ... than she was three years ago. She's been
the best spokesperson for the NEA that I've ever known.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
