<FIRST>s w AM-TeacherPresident-Secretaries Adv25   06-21 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher President-Secretaries, Adv 25,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Departing NEA Chief Gives Bennett Worst Marks as Education Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teacher President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three education secretaries of the last
nine years would get grades ranging from A-minus to D from Mary
Hatwood Futrell, the outgoing president of the National Education
Association.
   Futrell gives her lowest mark of D to former secretary William
Bennett, who made repeated assaults on her organization during her
six-year tenure.
   ``Bill didn't know how to get people to work with him,'' she said
in an interview. ``He reminds me of the person who desperately wants
people to work with them and like them but doesn't know how to do
it. He knew how to give the speech but he didn't know how to get the
people to follow him.''
   Futrell reserves her highest mark of A-minus for Terrel Bell,
President Reagan's first education secretary. ``Bell was the leader,
the one who had the vision, the substance. He understood
education,'' she said.
   Futrell noted that Bell instituted the annual ``wall chart,'' a
state-by-state comparison of education indicators, and commissioned
the ``Nation at Risk'' report that fueled the education reform
movement. ``He saved the department,'' she said, alluding to
Reagan's campaign pledges to abolish it.
   The current secretary, Lauro Cavazos, receives a C-plus or
B-minus from Futrell. ``He's not being allowed to do well,'' she
said. ``Like Bell, Cavazos understands the issues. But he does not
have the kind of support he needs to do the job. He's being
hamstrung right now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 25</NOTE>
