<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0943</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has approved an unprecedented
civil securities fraud settlement between the government and Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack on Tuesday placed the Wall
Street firm under strict supervision and barred it from dealing with
its former junk bond financier, Michael Milken.
   The decision cleared the way for Drexel to plead guilty to six
felonies and pay a record $650 million in order to settle separate
criminal charges with the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major oil companies have announced plans to
create a nationwide network of oil-spill response teams capable of
handling an accident as large as the Exxon Valdez disaster anywhere
on U.S. coastal waters.
   The companies, including Exxon, also proposed measures Tuesday
designed to prevent future spills and to establish clearer lines of
government authority for reacting to tanker accidents.
   Environmental groups called the program a step in the right
direction. The new system is expected to be in full operation within
one year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. has rejected as inadequate
a $5.85 billion takeover bid from McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
and said it was exploring alternatives.
   Lin, which has interests in cellular telephones, television and
publishing, said its alternatives include staying independent,
recapitalizing or selling itself to other potential buyers.
   McCaw has offered $120 a share for all of LIN's shares. It said
it was disappointed that the board had not accepted the offer, but
added it was willing to discuss it with LIN executives.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co. says it plans to fund
projects to recycle the plastic from disposable diapers into such
things as flower pots, garbage bags and park benches.
   The pulp of the diapers will be used in cardboard boxes, building
insulation and wallboard liner, the company said at a news
conference Tuesday. About 16 billion disposable diapers are used and
discarded in the United States each year.
   Environmentalists warn that the plastic-coated disposable diapers
don't decompose. That, they say, could provide breeding grounds for
dangerous viruses and bacteria.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has become
the first company to announce a personal computer containing the
next-generation microchip from Intel Corp.
   The computer will not be entirely new, and it will not be
available until the end of the year, but analysts saw it as a
psychological victory for IBM, which has been upstaged repeatedly by
rival Compaq Computer Corp.
   IBM said it will sell a $3,995 circuit board containing Intel's
new i486 chip. The board will replace the microprocessor in one of
IBM's Personal System-2 Model 70-A21 computers, making it run twice
as fast as the fastest personal computers available today, IBM said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Princeton-Newport Partners LP and
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. illegally bought and sold stocks in a
widespread tax fraud scheme amounting to ``plain, old-fashioned
cheating,'' a government prosecutor has charged.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Hansen made the remarks in opening
arguments Tuesday in the first racketeering case ever involving
securities trading.
   On trial are five officials of the defunct investment partnership
and former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg. The case overlaps the
government's indictment of former Drexel financier Michael Milken.
Neither of the firms is on trial.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc., the nation's largest
poultry processor, has raised its hostile offer for Holly Farms
Corp. to $70 a share, a bid worth more than $1.2 billion.
   Tyson of Springdale, Ark., has been trying to take over Holly
Farms since October, and the Memphis-based Holly has been struggling
since November to merge with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   Holly Farms lawyer Kenneth Nachbar said the company's board is
expected to meet within the next five business days to consider the
proposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernest and Julio Gallo, owners of the
world's largest winery, have won the right to keep younger brother,
Joseph, from using his name as a trademark for cheese.
   A federal judge concluded Tuesday that use of the name Joseph
Gallo on retail cheese is misleading because many consumers assume
the brand is connected with E.&amp;J. Gallo winery.
   However, the judge's permanent injunction permits Joseph Gallo to
use his name as a signature or in block letters below the words
designating the variety of cheese if the label also includes a
prominent trademark above that does not include the word Gallo.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. put its four
Sea World parks and two other attractions on the market to help rid
itself of $2.5 billion in debt brought on by a 1987 hostile takeover
attempt.
   The company said Tuesday that selling the marine parks in
Florida, Texas, Ohio and California and Boardwalk &amp; Baseball and
Cypress Gardens in central Florida was the best way to meet debt
obligations and concentrate on its publishing and insurance
divisions.
   Estimates of the value of the properties ranged from $1 billion
to $2.5 billion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished lower in uneventful trading, while the
dollar rose in domestic dealings, giving a lift to bond prices. The
Dow Jones industrial average slipped 7.01 points to close at
2,472.88 Tuesday.
   Gold prices declined and silver futures slid.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures fell, energy futures
were mixed, and livestock and meat prices were mixed.
