<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CaribbeanTrade     06-21 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Caribbean Trade,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Favors More Trade Benefits To Caribbean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee has voted in
favor of making permanent a system of U.S. trade preferences for
Caribbean nations and to extend the program to textiles.
   The liberalization of the Reagan-era Caribbean Basin Initiative
also would establish a guaranteed minimum floor for U.S. imports of
sugar from the region at present quota levels.
   Some committee members expressed concern Tuesday that the bill
could work to the disadvantage of Australia and other
sugar-exporting nations. Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., chairman of the
Ways and Means trade subcommittee, said nothing in the measure would
alter present sugar quotas from countries outside the Caribbean.
   Since the Caribbean Basin Initiative was enacted in 1983 to help
lift the economy of the region, it has allowed duty-free import of a
variety of Caribbean exports. But it specifically exempts several
major categories, especially textiles.
   The Caribbean Basin Initiative expansion approved by the
committee removes the exception for textiles and apparel. It would
permit duty-free imports of fabric and clothing made from materials
deemed to be in short supply in the United States, and of textiles
from U.S.-made and -cut fabrics that are sewn in the Caribbean.
   The new legislation would mean U.S. buyers would no longer have
to pay an 8.1 percent tariff on clothes imported from the Caribbean.
   Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., sought unsuccessfully to eliminate from
the bill most of the concessions toward Caribbean apparel. ``This
bill is a direct attack on the textile workers,'' he said.
   Jenkins' amendment would have required that any increase in
Caribbean textiles be offset by reductions in imports allowed from
Asia.
</TEXT>
