<FIRST>r f PM-GATT-WorldTrade     06-21 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GATT-World Trade,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tensions In International Trade Increasing, Says Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tensions have increased in international trade and
the commitment of governments to free trade talks is facing its
``sternest test,'' says the organization sponsoring the talks.
   The 1988 U.S. Trade Act could have the greatest short-term
adverse impact on the world trading system, the secretariat of the
96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade said Tuesday in a
six-month review.
   The so-called Section 301 of the U.S. law could lead to moves
aimed at pressuring countries into bilateral trade accords outside
GATT's international trade rules, the review said.
   The United States last month singled out Japan, India and Brazil
for priority action under the law that calls for penalties against
countries deemed to be especially protectionist.
   Brazil and India will raise the issue at the two-day council
meeting beginning Wednesday, which is part of the latest four-year
GATT talks known as the Uruguay Round, a GATT source said on
condition of anonymity.
   The review said although much progress had been made in the
Uruguay Round, there had been ``a further increase in the
uncertainties and tensions affecting trade policies'' in the period
reviewed, the six months until last February.
</TEXT>
