<FIRST>r f PM-FloridaGrapefruit     06-21 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Grapefruit,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grapefruit Exports Set Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida exported a record 23.5 million
cartons of grapefruit this year, up 14 percent from the 1987-88
season, citrus officials said.
   Arthur Chadwell, general manager of the Citrus Administrative
Committee, attributed the sharp rise to favorable currency exchange
rates and increased spending on foreign promotions by the state
Department of Citrus.
   He said Japan remained the biggest importer, buying 12 million
cartons, up 10 percent from a year ago, followed by Europe, which
bought 8.8 million cartons, up 4 percent.
   The fastest-growing market was South Korea, whose imports of
609,000 were 306 percent higher than the previous year, Chadwell
said Monday.
   A grapefruit carton holds four-fifths of a bushel of fruit, or
about half of an 85-pound box.
   Fresh orange exports totaled 154,000 cartons, down from about
200,000 last season. Total fresh citrus shipments of all varieties
through early June, both domestic and offshore, fell 3.2 percent to
68.9 million cartons.
</TEXT>
