<FIRST>r f PM-AbortionShow Bjt   06-21 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Show, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Radio to Run Abortion Special Despite Lack Of Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC Radio Network officials say a special program
on abortion hosted by Barbara Walters will run today even though
national advertisers refused to buy time on the program.
   The 54-minute special airs starting at 2:06 p.m. EDT on about 144
radio stations across the country, ABC said.
   Lou Severine, senior vice president of sales for the network,
said Tuesday that he was able to find only one buyer _ ABC's
``20-20'' television show, which also features Ms. Walters _ for one
minute of the six minutes that were allocated for national ads.
   He said advertisers ``are scared to death of the abortion topic.
... They just don't want to be involved with any controversy.''
   But Philip Giordano, senior vice president at the radio network,
said the program was so important to the network's objectives of
providing timely programs on compelling topics that ABC was prepared
to absorb all of the costs of producing the show. The costs can run
to $12,000, he said.
   It is the latest example of advertisers backing way from programs
that have either offended or risk offending individuals or groups
who have become increasingly vocal in complaining about
controversial subjects on radio and TV.
   The NBC television network, for instance, had to cut prices to
find buyers for ad time on the made-for-TV movie ``Roe Vs. Wade,''
which ran last month and dealt with the case that led to the Supreme
Court's 1973 decision that legalized abortion.
   Advertisers have backed out of shows such as NBC's ``Saturday
Night Live'' and the Fox television network's ``Married ... with
Children'' after individuals or groups complained that they were
offended by sexual references or profanity in the shows.
   The ABC television network cancelled two reality-based shows
earlier this year because no advertisers signed up.
   But Jim Farley, executive producer of today's radio special on
abortion, said no one has called for a boycott because of the topic.
   ``This is different. This is the news. It will be a
straightforward, fair and balanced discussion of the issues,''
Farley said.
   The show will feature Ms. Walters as moderator of a panel that
will include two people from each side of the abortion question.
Listeners can call in with comments.
   Severine would not identify any of the national sponsors refusing
to buy time. He said the unfilled national ad time will be used for
public service announcements such as anti-drug or anti-crime
messages.
   The time was being offered at a rate of $6,000 per minute, he
said. No effort was made to reduce the price to attract sponsors.
``It was never really the money,'' Severine said.
   Giordano said stations in 21 of the nation's 25 biggest radio
markets have agreed to carry the special, which should attract an
audience of 1.1 million adults.
   He said there were some local stations that were reluctant about
carrying the program because of the topic and others didn't like
giving up midday programming time, although they get to sell eight
minutes of local ad time in the show.
   One of the stations planning to carry it is KOA in Denver, whose
manager of operations, Larry Crandall, applauded ABC's efforts and
said his station plans its own two-hour discussion on the issue
moderated by a prominent psychologist immediately after the ABC
special.
   He said KOA expects to fill its ad time on the special with
previously-purchased advertising commitments.
   The show is the first in what ABC Radio says will be a series of
American Agenda Radio Specials hosted by ABC's top TV news figures,
including ABC anchorman Peter Jennings and newsman Ted Koppel.
   ``I'm certain that as we continue this series that it will get
wider acceptance,'' Giordano said. The next program is tentatively
set for August and will deal with juvenile crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890621-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LIN-McCaw     06-21 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LIN-McCaw,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN's Board Rejects McCaw's Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. said it was
disappointed that the LIN Broadcasting Corp. board rejected as
inadequate its $5.85 billion takeover bid, but said it is willing to
discuss the offer.
   ``We remain confident that our $120-per-share price is full and
fair,'' Wayne M. Perry, McCaw's vice chairman, said in a letter
Tuesday to Donald A. Pels, chairman and president of LIN
Broadcasting of New York.
   The deal would be the biggest to date in the emerging cellular
telephone business and would extend McCaw's reach as the industry
leader.
   Cellular franchises have become increasingly lucrative as
improvements in technology have boosted customer demand for mobile
phones.
   LIN, which has interests in cellular telephones, television and
publishing, said in disclosing its board's decision Tuesday that it
was exploring alternatives including staying independent,
recapitalizing or selling itself to other potential buyers.
   McCaw's Perry, noting LIN's apparent willingness to talk to
potential suitors, said he hoped LIN would make available to McCaw
any non-public information that it shares with others.
   ``As we have previously stated, we are genuinely ready and
willing to meet with you to discuss our offer,'' he wrote.
   In national over-the-counter trading, LIN rose $2.62{ a share to
$125.62{ on Tuesday while McCaw rose 75 cents a share to $41.50.
   Analysts said they suspected Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw would
eventually sweeten its bid.
   ``McCaw wants LIN badly and will make counteroffers,'' said
Kenneth Leon, a telecommunications analyst for the investment firm
Bear Stearns &amp; Co.
   Among those rumored to be interested in LIN have been the
regional Bell telephone companies, although some analysts have said
it is unlikely any one of them could afford the earnings dilution
that would result from buying LIN.
   ``For any one Bell company to buy all of LIN would be
considerable dilution and these companies have promised 6 percent to
7 percent to 8 percent earnings growth,'' said Geoffrey Johnson,
telecomunications analyst for Argus Research.
   A bid for LIN could drag down earnings for years as the debt
associated with making the acquisition would have to be repaid, he
said.
   If a Bell company were to get involved with LIN, Johnson said, it
was more likely that the Bell company would buy a partial stake in
LIN.
   LIN said its board decided unanimously that the unsolicited offer
from McCaw was inadequate and not in the best interests of the
company or its stockholders.
   In an effort to increase share value, LIN said, the company
intends to pursue its previously announced plan to spin off its
seven TV broadcasting stations into a new subsidiary.
   It also said it was studying steps to make sure its shareholders
would realize the extra value that would be created if LIN prevails
in its legal fight with Metromedia Inc. over the right to buy
Metromedia's interests in cellular systems in Philadelphia and New
York.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, LIN said
some industry analysts have estimated a victory for LIN in that case
would boost its stock value by $40 a share.
   LIN also said in the SEC filing that it had contacted potential
buyers and had met with them. It did not identify any of the
potential buyers but said they included some that have ``initiated
preliminary contacts in the past.''
   Bear Stearns' Leon said LIN and its financial advisers had done
``a brilliant job of getting investors excited and confusing them on
what they are offering'' in the latest filings.
   ``There is very slim chance that anyone would top McCaw,'' he
said.
   Analysts have valued McCaw's bid at as much as $290 per potential
cellular phone customer, or twice the $145 per potential customer
price that British Telecommunications PLC agreed to pay earlier this
year for a 20 percent stake in McCaw.
   McCaw and British Telecom announced separately Tuesday that they
had concluded the deal under which a British Telecom subsidiary paid
$1.37 billion for the stake in McCaw.
   LIN's interests include cellular systems serving New York, Los
Angeles, Philadelphia, Dallas and Houston. Its seven TV stations are
network-affiliates and it owns a specialty publishing house that
provides hardcover tourist guides often available in hotel rooms.
   McCaw has major cellular franchises serving customers in Seattle,
San Francisco, Miami, Denver, Minneapolis and Portland, Ore.
</TEXT>
