<DOCNO> AP890621-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest Bjt   06-21 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, Bjt,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checchi Says Questions About Debt In NWA Deal Are `Laughable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred Checchi, who expects to meet this week
with Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner about his proposed $4
billion acquisition of Northwest Airlines, says fears about debt in
the deal are ``almost laughable.''
   ``The amount of debt in this proposal is not the least bit
excessive,'' Checchi said Tuesday. ``The hardest part of my day was
turning down all the banks that want to be part of this credit.''
   Checchi's investment group, Wings Holdings Inc., signed a deal
Monday to acquire Northwest parent NWA Inc. for $121 a share in
cash. The financing includes $700 million in equity and $3.35
billion borrowed from a syndicate of commercial banks.
   Skinner wrote a letter May 15 to NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier
saying the department was concerned about any acquisition that would
have a ``substantial adverse impact'' on the company's financial
structure. Checchi said he expects to meet with Skinner today or
Thursday in Washington, D.C.
   To complete a transaction by the Sept. 18 deadline imposed by
NWA, Wings needs a license from the Transportation Department, which
will examine the financial package to determine whether the group is
financially fit to safely operate the nation's fourth-largest
airline.
   Similar reviews have ranged in length from two months for an
extensive fitness check last year of Eastern and Continental
airlines to a six-month examination of Trans World Airlines that
ended earlier this year, a department spokesman said.
   ``People who are sophisticated in the area of corporate finance,
they're going to find that it's almost laughable that people are
bringing this up as a concern,'' Checchi said, ``but certainly it's
understandable.''
   But concern about debt in the Checchi deal prompted Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp. to annouce Tuesday that the buyout would likely result
in a lower rating on NWA's senior debt.
   The acquisition would raise total debt at NWA to $3.7 billion
from $945 million, second only to Texas Air Corp. among airlines,
Standard &amp; Poor's said. The added annual interest expense of about
$300 million would consume most pre-tax earnings and almost cut
operating cash flow in half, the credit-rating agency said.
   It also said NWA's ``weakened financial strength'' would make the
carrier's plans for fleet modernization more expensive under the Los
Angeles investor.
   Checchi said Standard &amp; Poor's has not seen the details of his
group's deal. What's more important, he said, is that bankers are
lining up to get a piece of it.
   Despite skepticism, Guy Cook, president of the Machinists union
District Lodge 143, emerged Tuesday from a meeting with Checchi
confident that the airline could carry through its plan to double in
size in the next five years.
   ``I think it's probable at this point that we can establish
that,'' said Cook, who heads a 20,000-member union, the airline's
largest.
   Not as confident were leaders of the 5,000-member Northwest
pilots union, who also met with Checchi on Tuesday.
   ``Basically he said he feels that debt is his expertise and he
only talked about it in general terms,'' said Jim Halvorson, a
spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association unit. ``He said all
the things you'd expect him to say. He told us not to worry.''
   The pilots, who have an open contract and have threatened to
strike if they don't receive competitive wages and job security,
have said Checchi's deal would add debt that would be troublesome in
an economic downturn and possibly lead to layoffs.
   But Checchi said his group's financing package is strong enough
to carry the company through a recession as severe as the 1980-81
downturn.
   ``I would not enter any kind of transaction where the downside
was not provided for,'' he said.
   Checchi promised to provide pilots with details of his financing
package later in the week, Halvorson said.
   Halvorson said Checchi made a friendly gesture by saying he would
consider giving Northwest employees a stake in the company.
   Checchi, 41, said the concept proved popular at other companies
where he has worked, including Marriott Corp. But he said he won't
discuss the measure until the pilots settle on a contract because it
may be viewed as an attempt at gaining employee concessions.
   Cheechi said he hopes to close the deal within about four weeks
after the $121-a-share tender offer is launched Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
