<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   06-21 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Greets New Pilots, Says He's Confident About Rebuilding Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo spoke with
confidence about Eastern Airlines' future as he personally assured
new pilots of a deep commitment to see the carrier succeed, despite
a crippling 3-month-old strike.
   ``Every day that goes by, you see more and more realization of
what we're doing,'' Lorenzo told reporters Tuesday following
graduation ceremonies for a group of Eastern recruits.
   ``An airline can be rebuilt, particularly an airline like
Eastern, because of the tremendous strengths and the tremendous
assets that the company has. I've been very encouraged by what I've
seen.''
   While Eastern, a unit of Texas Air, is selling assets to reduce
its debt, Lorenzo said the carrier is moving ahead with rebuilding
and has begun discussions with aircraft manufacturers on buying new
aircraft for the 1990s.
   Lorenzo said he thought the federal bankruptcy court overseeing
Eastern's reorganization will approve the airline's plan to rebuild
at two-thirds its prestrike size.
   He called the plan ``very, very reasonable ... a much more
practical solution'' than the unions' call for a new owner or the
leanings of some creditors toward complete liquidation.
   ``You do have creditors who are frustrated and they'd like to get
their money,'' Lorenzo said. ``We intend to make sure the company
honors its contracts and provides the creditors what they're due.''
   He called the union-backed buyout effort by Chicago commodities
trader Joseph Ritchie ``a joke'' and said there were no legitimate
buyers for Eastern as a whole.
   Eastern has ``been overwhelmed by the interest in most of these
assets'' it's offering for sale, but he declined to discuss pending
transactions.
   Earlier, Lorenzo, Eastern President Phil Bakes and other
executives were all smiles as they handed out diplomas and
congratulations to 18 Eastern pilot recruits who completed training.
   ``We are very, very committed to the success of Eastern
Airlines,'' Lorenzo told them.
   Company spokesman Robin Matell said Eastern has graduated 108 new
pilots since it began seeking recruits about a month after the
strike began March 4. He said there were 259 pilots who crossed the
picket lines, not including 17 more veteran pilots who have told the
company in the past week that they wish to return to work. There are
527 recruits in training, he said.
   Matell said Eastern is well on track toward having enough pilots
to carry out the airline's planned schedule expansion this summer.
   A spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association disputed that
claim.
   ``We're not contradicting the statement in itself,'' said the
spokesman, who asked not to be identified. ``But by numbers and by
their own information, they are going to be able to fly the first
days of the schedule, but they're not going to be able to continue
to fly it'' due to lack of pilots.
   Eastern also announced Tuesday it will lease an A-300 Airbus jet
to VIASA, Venezuelan International Airways, for $1.4 million over
four months.
   ``It's consistent with our announced business plan to make $1.8
billion in assets transactions and use more than $900 million to pay
down debt,'' Matell said.
   Eastern is about $2.5 billion in debt. Earlier this month, its
Northeastern Shuttle service was handed over to New York developer
Donald Trump for $365 million.
   Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization five days
after its pilots and flight attendants unions joined a Machinists
union strike that crippled the airline.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland in New York must approve
any asset sales. He approved the shuttle deal and the $277.5 million
sale last week of 15 planes and six aircraft engines to a company
that buys and resells airplane equipment.
   Eastern last week announced a deal to sell eight Philadelphia
airport gates, 16 jets and other assets to Midway Airlines for
$206.5 million. Lifland must approve that transaction, and Eastern
unions say they will challenge it.
</TEXT>
