<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-21 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Fluctuates in Narrow Range, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ebbed and flowed in a narrow range
today, gaining against European currencies.
   Gold was down.
   Traders in Italy said the dollar's most significant movements in
the past few days came in Asian trading, while European trading was
calm.
   In London, the central bank intervened as the pound sterling
dropped as low as $1.5297 in the morning. The British currency also
slipped to 3.0498 West German marks, but rallied to 3.0531 after the
Bank of England stepped in.
   One dealer in London said the pound may have been hurt by strikes
that shut down rail, subway and bus service in the capital. ``If
one's got to hitchhike to work, it doesn't put sterling in good
grace,'' the dealer said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before the European markets open,
the dollar closed at 144.95, up 1.15 yen from Tuesday's close.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.9915 West German marks, up from
1.9775; 1.7278 Swiss francs, up from 1.7110; 6.7530 French francs,
up from 6.7025; 2.2446 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2255; 1,443.00
Italian lire, up from 1.431.75; and 1.1977 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2000.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5320, down from $1.5553 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $364.75, down from Tuesday's closing
price of $366.50. At mid-morning, the city's five major gold dealers
fixed a recommended price of $365.70.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $366.57, down from $366.95
late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.26 bid a troy ounce,
from $5.34.
</TEXT>
