<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-21 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Higher, Dollar Up 1.15 Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index closed higher
today after early declines, while the U.S. dollar gained against the
Japanese yen.
   The doller closed at 144.95 yen, up 1.15 yen from Tuesday's
143.80-yen close. It opened at 144.85 yen and fluctuated from 144.73
yen to 145.03 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's strength followed its higher trend in
New York overnight.
   Yutaka Nakamura, a Daiwa Bank trader, said the currency stayed
just below 145 yen most of the day.
   ``Selling for profit-taking also helped to halt the dollar's
further rise,'' he said.
   ``Toward the end of the day, the dollar moved slightly up against
the yen as it rose against the major European currencies,'' Nakamura
added.
   The Bank of Japan sold an estimated $200 million in efforts to
curb the U.S. currency's rise, but it did not have much impact on
trading, Nakamura said. The central bank does not comment on its
foreign exchange market activities.
   Trading was inactive mainly because of uncertainties, he added.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which
gained 220.29 points the previous day, added another 111.81 points,
or 0.34 percent, closing at 33,345.28.
   After early losses, the index reversed the trend and rose in the
afternoon.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said the
index began to climb when institutional investors bought ``a
substantial amount'' of cheaper issues.
   In addition, he said, foreign investors were buying in arbitrage
deals between the spot and futures markets.
   The dollar's rebound had no negative impact on Wednesday's stock
trading, but trading was thin, Nomura said.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 600 million
shares, down from Tuesday's 700 million.
   ``Investors would not panic over dollar-yen fluctuations between
143 and 146 yen. But they are little motivated in buying at the
moment since last week's wild fluctuations,'' Nomura added.
   Last week, the dollar closed at 151.30 yen on Thursday, its
highest level in almost two years. It then lost 6.25 yen on Friday.
Meanwhile, the Nikkei lost more than 1,100 points during the week.
   Among today's gainers were steel and shipbuilding issues.
</TEXT>
