<FIRST>r f PM-UAWConvention 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAW Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Directions Loses Third Issue, But Leader's Happy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS typo in `feel' in final graf; convention convenes at
noon EDT; PMs lead unlikely.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ANS1 of June 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Auto Workers dissident group lost
a third, key battle at the union's constitutional convention, but
despite the outcome, the group's leader says he is happy with the
way it went.
   About 2,000 delegates to the UAW's constitutional convention
turned back an attempt Tuesday by the New Directions movement to
limit Japanese-style labor-management programs on factory floors.
   The decision came on two show-of-hands votes in which no more
than 20 percent of the delegates supported the New Directions effort.
   Today, delegates are scheduled elect top national and regional
officers. UAW President Owen Bieber faces no opposition to a third,
three-year term. The convention also will elect two vice presidents
to replace retiring vice presidents Donald Ephlin and Marc Stepp.
   Later, Bieber will assign the vice presidents to head the union's
various departments, including one for each of the Big Three
automakers and another with administrative responsibility for
agricultural implement and aerospace workers covered by the union.
   Despite the overwhelming loss Tuesday, New Directions leader
Jerry Tucker of St. Louis said he was happy with his troops and
their reception.
   ``I think it was a good debate,'' he said. ``Debate on the floor
today was healthy.''
   Tucker held out the possibility that there would be more from New
Directions forces, especially next year when the UAW plots its
strategies for negotiations with the Big Three automakers. Contracts
between the UAW and General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. expire Sept. 14, 1990.
   Tucker said he was pleased with the way Bieber handled the
debate, which sometimes got a little rowdy, and hoped that delegates
would take the New Directions message back to their locals.
   ``The rank and file will ultimately find ways to express
themselves,'' he said.
   The loss Tuesday was the third by New Directions forces since the
convention opened Sunday. It winds up Friday.
   During the first two days of the convention, New Directions
backers failed in an attempt to require rank-and-file referendum
voting for top national officers, instead of a vote by convention
delegates, and lost a credentials fight for seating some delegations.
   Members of the movement made a loud entrance to the convention
hall Tuesday. About 250 delegates and alternates paraded in carrying
signs and shouting: ``What do we need? New Directions. When do we
want it? Right now.''
   Bieber ignored the parade as it passed in front of the stage.
   Delegate Tony Torres of Local 653 in Pontiac, Mich., stood on a
chair in front of Bieber, waved a New Directions placard and
shouted, ``We don't have to go to China; Injustice is right here.''
   Tucker watched the demonstration from the stage. When asked how
it made him feel, he said, ``Bigger.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
