<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 0939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;LsBureaucracy 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls Bureaucracy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC Chief Considers Seeking More Power Over S&amp;L Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS last graf with 5 new grafs to include Treasury Department
comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. William Seidman, who would become the new
deposit insurance czar under legislation moving through Congress, is
conferring with the Bush administration about an idea that would
enhance his power over the savings and loan bailout.
   Under the plan, Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., would have greater authority than originally
envisioned by the administration within the Resolution Trust Corp.,
a new agency being created to oversee the closing or sale of
insolvent thrift institutions and of real estate repossessed by the
S&amp;Ls.
   Under bills passed by the House and Senate, the RTC will be run
by a board headed by the Treasury secretary. It would have an
oversight staff, headed by an executive director. But, as the
administration envisions the structure, most of the work would be
contracted out, presumably to the FDIC.
   According to an industry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, Seidman wants the FDIC to report directly to the RTC
oversight board rather than through a staff working for the board.
   Ultimate authority would still rest with the RTC board, but
without the separate staff there would be less opportunity for
administration second-guessing of Seidman's agency. Also, the FDIC _
not the RTC board _ in practice would choose which private firms are
hired for the lucrative job of assisting the government in the huge
undertaking.
   Seidman, in a telephone interview Tuesday, declined to say his
agency is advocating the idea, but he described it as ``worth
exploring'' and ``feasible.''
   ``It's not our idea. It came from a suggestion that the GAO (the
congressional General Accounting Office) made. We have been talking
to Treasury about it,'' he said.
   The RTC, under legislation that passed the House last week and
the Senate in April, will have the mammoth task of spending $50
billion in new bailout funds and of handling $300 billion to $500
billion of bad loans and property. That would make it, if it were
private, the largest corporation in the United States.
   The legislation does not spell out how the RTC will be structured
beyond the composition of its board and the fact that it must hire a
chief executive officer. It does not define the relationship between
the FDIC and RTC.
   However, Seidman has said he does not want his agency to get
expanded responsibility without added authority to control the
conditions and terms under which it does the additional work.
   Seidman said if the FDIC were not given the added authority, and
were simply a contractor of the RTC, it would want to pick and
choose what S&amp;L liquidation work it wanted.
   Assistant Treasury Secretary David W. Mullins said the
administration has planned all along for the FDIC to take the lead
role in disposing of failed S&amp;Ls. At issue, he said, is the vigor of
administration oversight.
   ``No one likes the idea of a full-time person overseeing them.
But our view is we're required to have oversight,'' he said. The
FDIC ``wants as much independence as (it) can get, but there's a
limit as to what can be done on that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
