<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 1023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-21 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0285</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today as
traders awaited new indications of the future course of the Federal
Reserve's credit policy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 2.09 to 2,470.79
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 469 up, 398 down and
536 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.61 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Interest rates moved slightly lower in the government securities
market today.
   Analysts said traders were expecting new evidence of a slowing
economy when the Federal Reserve issued a periodic report, known as
the ``beige book,'' later today on the state of the economy.
   But that failed to stir up much enthusiasm for stocks. Many Wall
Streeters lately have voiced concerns that stock prices might be due
for a pause or pullback after their strong advance since late last
year.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down \ at
40]; McDonald's, down ] at 29{; Eastman Kodak, down [ at 47~, and
Alcoa, down [ at 65~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .03 to 179.46. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .24 at 361.48.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 7.01 points
to 2,472.88.
   Declining issues edged out advances on the NYSE, with 758 down,
651 up and 533 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 167.65 million shares, up from 130.72
million in Monday's session.
