<HEAD>Crop Futures Continue Slide On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened slightly
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade, continuing a retreat
prompted by forecasts for scattered thunderstorms in the Midwest.
   Traders are keeping a close watch on weather conditions in
western Iowa and southwestern Minnesota, where rain was expected
today.
   The threat of precipitation _ with expected amounts ranging from
\ inch to 1{ inches _ is alleviating the drought fears that prompted
a strong rally in the crop markets during the past week. Prices
began falling on Tuesday.
   The showers are expected to move across the Corn Belt over the
next several days, with clearing skies and cooler temperatures
predicted for the weekend.
   The wheat market continued to be pressured by selling linked to
harvest activity in the Great Plains and uncertainty over U.S.-China
relations. Some experts fear tensions between the two countries may
impede sales of U.S. grain to China.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.94 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1{ cents lower with July at $2.65{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 2
cents lower with July at $1.67} a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents to
4\ cents lower with July at $7.33 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were little changed while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .22 cent lower with August at 70.45
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .13 cent higher
with August at 81.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .23 cent to .45
cent higher wiith July at 49.55 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .17 cent to .30 cent lower with July at 34.20 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Tuesday.
