<FIRST>r f BC-Scherer     06-21 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scherer,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Owners Cut Work Force, Subsidiaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new owners of R.P. Scherer Corp. have laid
off 50 to 60 workers and put five subsidiaries up for sale so the
company can concentrate on its basic capsule-making business,
Scherer President Alex Erdeljan said.
   Since its sale earlier this month to a New York investment group,
Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc., Scherer has closed a 21-person
Ann Arbor research and development office and laid off 27 of the 37
workers at its Troy headquarters, Erdeljan said Tuesday.
   The five subsidiaries, ranging from a New Jersey pharmaceutical
maker and packager to a chain of eyewear stores, employ about 1,900
of Scherer's 4,400 workers and accounted for about 30 percent of the
company's 1988 sales of $290.7 million.
   Paco Pharmaceutical Services Inc. of Lakewood, N.J.; Franz Pohl
GmbH in West Germany; Lorvic Corp. and Scientific Associates Inc. in
St. Louis; and Southern Optical Co. of Greensboro, N.C., will be
sold within 180 days, Erdeljan said.
   Scherer is the world's largest producer of gelatin capsules for
products such as vitamins, drugs and bath oil, with operations in 13
countries.
   ``The cuts are necessary to trim us down and turn us into a
stronger competitor,'' Erdeljan said.
   The company was sold after a proxy battle between Karla Scherer,
daughter of Scherer's founder and the largest shareholder in the
company, who favored selling, and her estranged husband, Peter Fink.
   Fink, who opposed the sale, resigned in November as Scherer
president and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
