<FIRST>u f PM-Time 4thLd-Writethru   06-21 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, 4th Ld-Writethru,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Amends Suit, Time Stock Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 new grafs to move suit filing higher, UPDATE with
stock price movement. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Time stock ... Deleting grafs
13-15 bgng, Paramount today ... for transition.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. moved today to get
a court order blocking Time Inc.'s proposed $14 billion acquisition
of Warner Communications Inc.
   Paramount, an entertainment and publishing concern, has launched
its own $10.7 billion offer for Time, a leading magazine publisher
and cable operator.
   Time has rejected Paramount's bid.
   In trading today on the New York Stock Exchange, Time was up $3 a
share to $155.50. Time had fallen more than $18 a share over the
past three trading days since it launched its bid for Warner and
rejected Paramount's offer.
   Warner was down 12{ cents a share at $59.37{ at midday while
Paramount was down 75 cents a share at $58.62{.
   In a revision of an earlier suit filed in Delaware Chancery
Court, Paramount asked for an order voiding the Time tender offer
and merger agreement with Warner.
   It also asks for nullification of any vote to elect directors at
Time's annual meeting, which is scheduled for June 30. Among the
directors up for election are Time's chairman and chief executive,
J. Richard Munro, and its president, Nicholas J. Nicholas Jr.
   Time said Paramount's allegations in the new complaint were
``without merit'' and said the amended complaint ``appears to be
designed to provide copy for the press rather than to make a case
before a court.''
   Time stock, which was trading at $126 before Paramount announced
its bid June 6, has climbed as high as $182.75 during the past two
weeks.
   Peter Appert, an analyst with C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell
Inc., said Time's stock price could turn around again if the market
perceives that the advantage in the struggle for Time was shifting
toward Paramount.
   Time stock has fallen because investors believe ``the odds are
greater or improving that Time is going to succeed with its bid for
Warner'' and that Paramount's bid for Time will fail, Appert said.
   But, Appert said, the market had no concrete information or
developments to support its speculation, and it was still widely
expected that courts in Delaware _ where all three companies are
incorporated _ ultimately would decide the outcome of the takeover
fight.
   Paramount has bid $175 a share for Time, which rejected the offer
and said it would continue to pursue a merger with Warner. On
Friday, Time announced it was revising its earlier stock-swap merger
agreement with Warner and was launching a $70-a-share tender offer
for the company.
   Time contends the Paramount offer is uncertain because it is
dependent on obtaining financing and because Paramount must obtain
regulatory approval before it can acquire the franchises to about
800 cable television systems Time owns.
   Appert said the takeover fight could turn on whether Time, in
agreeing to the merger with Warner in March, effectively put itself
up for sale. If the courts decide that is the case, Time directors
could be forced to seek the highest price for the company's stock
and the Paramount bid might then succeed.
   Wall Street _ in depressing Time's stock _ is betting the courts
will side with Time and allow the directors to pursue an acquisition
of Warner.
   Meanwhile, in filings with the Federal Communications Commission
Tuesday, Warner charged that Paramount's bid for Time violates the
1984 Cable Act and FCC rules and Paramount told the commission it
should set aside a ruling allowing Time to transfer control of its
cable TV systems to Time-Warner.
   Paramount said Time had misrepresented to its stockholders the
nature of the transfer and that Time had written to state attorneys
general asking them to oppose Paramount's proposal without notifying
Paramount of the letters.
   These actions raise ``questions about Time's character
qualifications,'' Paramount said, asking the FCC to set aside its
approval of the license transfers pending an investigation.
   Paramount earlier this month asked the FCC for permission to give
control of Time to former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld pending
FCC approval of the transfer of 99 cable television franchises and
licenses held by Time's subsidiary, American Television and
Communications Corp.
   Art Harding, a lawyer for Warner, said Tuesday Paramount's
request ``would violate the recent Cable Act because Rumsfeld hasn't
gotten consent from any of these cities for the transfers.''
   Harding, echoing assertions Time made against Paramount in a June
13 FCC filing, said Paramount's plan would ``undermine the delicate
balance'' established in the 1984 Cable Act for regulation of cable
systems by local authorities.
   Warner asked the FCC late Monday to deny the application made by
Paramount and its subsidiary, KDS Acquisition Corp., for expedited
consent to transfer control of Time to Rumsfeld and then to
Paramount.
   In a separate development, Warner cancelled the June 23
shareholder's meeting it had scheduled for a vote on the original
merger plan with Time.
   Time earlier had rescheduled its June 23 shareholders' meeting
until June 30 and said it would deal with election of directers and
nothing related to the merger with Warner.
</TEXT>
