<FIRST>r f BC-Boesky 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boesky, 1st Ld-Writethru,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Boesky Pumping Iron, Growing Beard in Federal Pen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to clarify that $100 million represented alleged
illegal profits and penalties; subs 7th graf to fix spelling of jogs.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Manhattan inc. is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ivan F. Boesky, the one-time stock baron at the
center of Wall Street's fraud scandals, is pumping iron and growing
a beard at a California prison, a published report says.
   Boesky also is deeply tanned and jogs daily on the outdoor track
at the minimum-security federal prison camp in Lompoc, Calif.,
Manhattan inc. magazine reports in its July issue.
   The 52-year-old former speculator in April completed one year of
a three-year sentence for pleading guilty of conspiracy to lie to
the Securities and Exchange Commission in connection with
allegations of insider trading.
   Boesky paid the SEC $100 million in alleged ill-gotten profits
and penalties in late 1986 to settle charges he used illegal inside
information to profit on securities deals.
   He was eligible for parole in March, but declined to apply. A
federal judge recently rejected his appeal for a reduced sentence,
and his earliest possible release date based on good behavior is
April 4, 1990.
   Quoting unidentified visitors to Boesky, Manhattan inc. said the
convicted arbitrager whose confessions have spawned several other
Wall Street fraud prosecutions has grown a full white beard and is
``impressively muscled.''
   ``Boesky works out every day at the outdoor weight area Lompoc
provides inmates, and he has built himself up substantially,'' the
magazine said. ``He jogs daily on Lompoc's makeshift track.''
   The magazine said that Boesky's bodybuilding ``is probably in
part to insure that he is able to defend himself'' because he feared
for his safety when he entered the prison 15 months ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
