<DOCNO> AP890621-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-ChinaBusiness     06-21 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-China Business,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Business Returning to China; Unlikely To Exploit Any U.S.
Void</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese businessmen cautiously are returning to
China, hoping to resume the business that they long have conducted
in that market while remaining wary of another outbreak of unrest.
   Foreign Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka has criticized businessmen for
returning too quickly _ saying they invited charges that they are
``trying to make money like a thief at a fire'' _ but the government
has not formally asked firms to refrain from business.
   Japan has been more cautious in its criticism of China than the
United States, which is pushing for the suspension of all new World
Bank loans to protest the Chinese government's bloody suppression of
pro-democracy demonstrations two weeks ago.
   ``For the time being the Japanese government is not considering
sanctions,'' but is continuing to gather information, Chief Cabinet
Secretary Masajuro Shiokawa told a news conference Wednesday.
   Nevertheless, on Tuesday Foreign Ministry officials said
negotiations on a new five-year, $5.6 billion loan package to China
were not being conducted, but Japan would decide whether to resume
talks after watching the situation in China.
   Sanctions by Japan could be more serious than sanctions by the
United States because Japan's trade with China is larger _ $19.3
billion last year _ and because Japan provides 80 percent of China's
foreign loans.
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno has expressed regret at the Chinese
crackdown but so far has stressed maintaining good long-term ties
with China. He and other officials have cited Japan's pre-World War
II invasion of China as a major reason for reluctance to criticize
the Chinese government.
   The government's cautious attitude has been criticized as too
weak by some of the Japanese press and some business leaders.
   But many businessmen want the government to help smooth
resumption of business. They fear that U.S. economic sanctions could
harm the general business environment and the suspension of World
Bank loans could hurt China's ability to conduct trade with Japan.
   If the United States cut trade ties with China, ``some Japanese
companies might take up the slack,'' said Jan VanDenBerg, an
economist at Merrill Lynch Securities in Tokyo. ``However, it's
unlikely they would take up the slack in U.S. direct investment in
China. U.S. sanctions would be a disincentive for anyone else to
invest,'' she said.
   The Chinese government has been trying to woo foreign businessmen
back with reassurances that its economic open-door policy remains
intact. Some traders say China even has speeded up the normally
glacial paperwork required to do business.
   Japanese traders view these assurances with skepticism, but like
many Americans are trying to maintain business ties while carefully
watching the situation, said Hiroaki Kasahara, general manager of
the China department at Marubeni Corporation.
   Major trading houses have sent limited numbers of staff back to
China to carry out existing contracts and monitor the situation,
said a trader who declined to be named.
   Trading houses said that even at the height of the unrest,
shipments in and out of China did not stop, although there were some
slowdowns. Production at a number of joint-venture factories far
from Beijing and Shanghai were undisturbed by events in the capital.
   Japanese banks and securities houses do not plan to send staff
back to China for now, while a number of manufacturers plan to
proceed with plans for joint ventures, Japan Broadcasting
Corporation reported.
   Kumagai Gumi, a major construction company, said it has not
resumed work on a 51-story Beijing building stopped during the
unrest.
   ``We're not sure yet if there are workers and materials
available,'' said Makoto Sasaki, a company spokesman. None of the
company employees who were evacuated have returned to Beijing and it
is unclear if they will, he said.
   But Yokogawa Electric Company, a major electrical machinery
manufacturer, said its joint venture factory in Xian resumed
production last week following a temporary shutdown during the
unrest.
   Half of the Japanese China-based staff have returned to China and
the company hopes to send the rest back later, said Tatsuya Ando of
Yokogawa's public relations office.
   ``We have a very long history in China, and we are not
considering fundamentally rethinking our plans in China just because
of recent events,'' Ando said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
