<FIRST>u f PM-FedResignation     06-21 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed Resignation,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heller Resigns from Federal Reserve Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H. Robert Heller, a member of the Federal
Reserve Board, announced today that he was resigning to become an
executive with VISA International, the giant credit card company.
   Heller cited his government salary of $82,500 as a primary reason
for his departure, saying it had represented a significant financial
sacrifice to him during his three years on the seven-member board.
   Heller said he would serve as executive vice president at VISA,
based in San Francisco, where he had lived previously. Before
joining the Fed, Heller was a senior vice president and director of
international economic research at Bank of America.
   Heller refused to disclose his exact salary at VISA, saying only
that it would be a ``pretty sizable'' increase.
   Heller's resignation will provide President Bush with the
opportunity to make his first appointment to the Fed board, which is
currently composed entirely of officials appointed by former
President Ronald Reagan.
   Heller, 49, was generally recognized as the international expert
on the board and it was considered likely that Bush would pick
someone with international economic experience to replace him.
Heller's term was scheduled to have run until Jan. 31, 1996.
</TEXT>
