<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures End Mixed; Trade Fears, Rain Called Factors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed narrowly
mixed Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with rainy weather
helping to buoy up wheat prices and depress the corn and soybean
markets.
   Rain is slowing the winter wheat harvest in the Southeast but
aiding newly planted corn and soybeans in the Midwest. Scattered
showers were expected to spread eastward from western Iowa over the
next couple days, ending about a week of dry weather in the Corn
Belt.
   Wheat prices fell early in the session on rumors of a possible
embargo on grain to China, but closed higher after U.S. officials
said they did not plan to cut off grain sales to China to protest
the executions of pro-Democracy dissidents.
   But experts said recent Chinese purchases of U.S. wheat have
probably eliminated any immediate need.
   ``I think they can hold back and stay off the market for a few
months,'' said Susan Leighty, a grain-market analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 3\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.99 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 2 cents lower with July at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to
5\ cents lower with July at $1.63 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents
lower to 2} cents higher with July at $7.39 a bushel.
  
