<FIRST>u f AM-TokyoDelight 1stLdf-Writethru f0135 06-21 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tokyo Delight, 1st Ldf-Writethru, f0135,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Barbecue Makers Offering Japanese Food _ To Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, Nitto sent ..., with one graf to include
full first reference to Saga. SUBS 11th graf pvs, `We send ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia frozen food company known mainly
for its chicken and barbecue is selling its new Japanese food in a
crowded market _ Japan.
   But the overseas competition doesn't worry R&amp;H Food Enterprises
Inc., which is exploiting it's product's cost advantages to carve a
niche in the market.
   ``It's cheaper to produce in America,'' said Don Hall, president
of Savannah-based R&amp;H Food. ``Our labor is cheaper. Our costs of
goods are cheaper. And even if you add in the shipping charges, it's
still cheaper.''
   Since Hall's company was established in 1981, it has produced
chicken and dumplings, chicken pot pies, pork barbecue and such
frozen rice dishes such as seafood and catfish gumbos.
   In 1987, R&amp;H joined Nitto Food Products Ltd., a leading Japanese
food manufacturer, and Nozaki America Inc., a Japanese trading
company, in forming Georgia Pro Foods Inc.
   Nitto sent Hideo Saga, a consultant for a Japanese company with
which R&amp;H markets the U.S.-made frozen dinners, to Savannah to
develop test products, including ``beef-rice,'' a popular Japanese
dish of rice, beef and vegetables.
   Hall's 50 employees ship 80,000 pounds of cooked beef a month to
Japan, the maximum allowed under a government-set quota. The beef,
cooked and packed in six-pound pouches, is used in various Nitto
products.
   Pro Foods also ships 40,000 pounds of frozen beef-rice a month,
packed in plastic pouches that can be heated in boiling water or
microwave ovens.
   To assure the authenticity of the dish, the rice is steamed in a
Japanese rice cooker resembling a large safe, complete with a wheel
to bolt it shut. Another Japanese machine keeps the beef slices to a
thickness of between 1.5 and 2.5 millimeters, a tolerance specified
by Nitto.
   A third Japanese machine known as a nitrogen tunnel cools the
beef-rice pouches to minus-10 degrees Fahrenheit. The blast of
nitrogen keeps the rice from clumping when heated and served.
   ``We send it to small restaurants and cafeterias. The people in
the back know it was made in Savannah, Ga., but not the customers,''
said Saga.
   Saga, who spent six years developing frozen and canned foods in
Nitto's Yamagata headquarters, has been assigned permanently to
Savannah. He is one of two Japanese quality control consultants at
Pro Foods. Nitto sends a new assistant every three months.
   Japanese consumers eat rice about three times a day, but have to
pay about five times more than their American counterparts, said
Saga. To protect growers, the Japanese government bars imports of
cheaper foreign rice but permits foods containing rice.
   Beef, the second-most popular meat in Japan after fish, must be
imported because the Japanese cannot produce enough to meet demand,
said Hall. As a result, the wholesale price of beef is $8 to $12 a
pound in Japan, compared to about $3.50 a pound for prime filet
mignon at American grocery stores, he said.
   Saga is developing additional products for Pro Foods to export.
His countrymen like Italian food, but probably would not enjoy chili
and tacos, he said.
   Saga also doesn't see a future for Hall's catfish gumbo, because
in Japanese mythology catfish are thought to cause earthquakes.
   ``There are many catfish in Japan, but they are never eaten,''
Saga said.
   Hall believes there are many untapped opportunities for small
companies such as R&amp;H that want to sell to the Japanese. But the
firms will have to supply products that meet their needs and
specifications.
   ``The future is in small ventures,'' Hall said. ``There are 124
million Japanese living in an area the size of California. They all
eat, they all sleep and they all drink ... The items that can be
manufactured here to Japanese specifications are just unlimited.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
