<FIRST>r f AM-RobinsBuyout     06-21 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robins Buyout,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robins, American Home Move Back Deadline for Buy Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Robins Co. and American Home Products Corp.
announced Wednesday that they have moved back to Dec. 31 the
deadline for American Home Products to buy the Richmond-based
pharmaceutical company.
   Under the orginal purchase agreement, American Home Products
could terminate the purchase and withdraw from the Chapter 11
reorganization of Robins if all appeals of the plan were not cleared
up by July 26. American Home Products is purchasing Robins through a
$700 million stock swap.
   Last week, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond
affirmed a lower court ruling approving the reorganization plan.
Part of the plan includes a $2.5 billion trust fund to pay off the
claims of nearly 200,000 women who claimed physical injury from the
use of the Robins' Dalkon Shield intrauterine birth control device.
   Both American Home Products chairman John R. Stafford and E.
Claiborne Robins Jr., president and chief executive officer of the
pharmaceutical company, said the extension of the termination date
would allow sufficient time for any appeals of the appeals court
decision.
   ``We would like to get on with the completion of our acquisition
of A.H. Robins,'' Stafford said. ``We believe doing so promptly
would be in the best interests of all concerned. If no appeals of
the orders... are taken to the Supreme Court, our present
anticipation is that the transaction will be complete early in the
fourth quarter of this year.''
   Robins sought federal bankruptcy protection in 1985 in the wake
of mounting claims from the use of the Dalkon Shield, marketed by
the company in the mid-1970s. Women who used the IUD said they
suffered injuries ranging from internal bleeding to sterility.
   After three years of hearings, the reorganization plan was
approved by federal District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr., and later
by Robins' creditors. That approval was challenged by attorneys
representing some of the claimants, who argued votes from women who
claimed the greatest injury should be given a greater weight than
other claimants.
</TEXT>
