<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-21 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended lower against all major
currencies in thin, nervous trading Wednesday following a mixed
performance overseas.
   Gold prices rose sharply in reaction to the decline. Republic
National Bank of New York said the late bid for a troy ounce of gold
was $371.25 a troy ounce, up $6.25 from Monday.
   Currency dealers said the dollar started out stronger overseas
but slipped back after failing to sustain higher levels that are
important to chart-watching analysts. The decline accelerated
following reports of quiet dollar-selling intervention by the
Federal Reserve, they said.
   Ronald H. Holzer, chief dealer for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago,
said traders also were concerned that interest rates may soon rise
overseas, especially after the European parliamentary elections,
depressing the dollar's value.
   He said that feeling was underlined by remarks from West
Germany's central bank indicating dissatisfation with the recent
high dollar levels.
   Trading was particularly quiet in London, where markets were
affected by strikes on Britain's railways and London's buses and
subways. Some dealing rooms in London operated with skeleton staffs
and very little business was seen during the day.
   In London, the dollar rose against the pound. One British pound
cost $1.54675, down from $1.5553 Tuesday. Sterling fetched $1.5553
in New York, up from $1.5405.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before the European markets open,
the dollar closed at 144.95, up 1.15 yen from Tuesday. The dollar
traded slightly lower at 144.90 yen in London, and at 142.55 yen in
New York, down from 144.90.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9610 West German marks, down from 1.9870; 1.6905
Swiss francs, down from 1.7205; 1.19325 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19875; 6.6565 French francs, down from 6.7315; and 1,423.50
Italian lire, down from 1,440.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Tuesday's late
rates: 1.9680 West German marks, down from 1.9775; 1.7005 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7110; 6.6795 French francs, down from 6.7025;
2.2375 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2255; 1,439.50 Italian lire, up
from 1.431.75; and 1.19675 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2000.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $372.40 a troy ounce, up from $366.30. Gold sold
at a bid price of $366.75 a troy ounce in London, up from $366.50;
and at $366.40 an ounce in Zurich, up from $366.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $366.57 an ounce, down from
$366.95 late Tuesday.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery settled at $5.285 a troy ounce, up from $5.234 late
Monday. It fell to $5.28 an ounce in London from $5.34.
</TEXT>
