<HEAD>Shares Close Firmer Despite Signs of Weakness in Sterling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with volume figures.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
firmer on Wednesday despite further signs of weakness in sterling
and the disruption to trading caused by Britain's first national
rail strike since 1982.
   The major blue chip stocks continued their recent tendency to
drift upward in spite of negative economic news, dealers said. The
pound fell sharply overnight, though it recovered somewhat later in
the day, helped by modest intervention by the Bank of England.
   The Stock Exchange shortened the trading session about an hour
because of the chaotic traffic conditions in London as a result of
the strike.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 7.4
points, or 0.3 percent, higher at 2,172.2.
   Trading volume amounted to a slender 281.4 million shares by 1500
GMT, compared with 504.1 million shares traded by 1600 GMT on
Tuesday.
