<HEAD>For release Sunday June 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Ghost Won't Haunt Oil Market, Strategists Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Graphic in AP Access under IRANOIL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
triumphantly led Iran through a revolution a decade ago, oil output
tumbled, world prices soared and shock waves hurt the U.S. economy.
But analysts say that with the spiritual leader's death earlier this
month, history won't repeat itself.
   ``It's business as usual,'' said Peter Gignoux, director of the
international energy department at Shearson Lehman Hutton brokerage
in London.
   Fergus MacLeod, analyst at London's Barclays de Zoete Wedd, said,
``In the short-term, the impact will be extremely limited.''
   With the quick transfer of power to President ere
have so far been no reports of instability that would threaten the
flow of crude from one Ali Khamenei, thof the world's major producing nations.
   ``There doesn't appear to be any civil disruptions which could
unsettle the oil sector,'' said Paul Mlotok, head of energy research
at Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York.
   The 1979 revolution, which brought Khomeini to power and ended
the reign of Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was marked by unrest in the
oilfields and a sharp drop in production. World oil prices soared,
roiling the economies of the United States and other indus recently that
Iran could produce 3.5 million
barrels a day without any problem.
   ``We want to keep onshore and offshore production capacity for
the next five years at a level of 4 million barrels a day,'' he said.
   Repairing its damaged industry would boost the slumping economy.
   Iran earned an estimated $9 billion last year from oil revenues,
compared with $23.6 billion in 1977.
   With increased production and higher prices, 1989 earnings should
climb to about $12 billion, analysts predict.
