<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-21 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose Wednesday, led by a
rally in the heating oil market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July heating oil
contract jumped 2.29 cents to finish at 47.98 cents a gallon, while
the August contract closed 2 cents higher at 48.07 cents a gallon.
All other contracts posted healthy advances.
   Crude prices also made strong gains. The August contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 43
cents to close at $19.31 a barrel. Contracts for later delivery
showed similar increases.
   Among other refined oil products, meanwhile, unleaded gasoline
for July fell 0.7 cent to 59.10 cents a gallon, but other contracts
rose.
   Analysts said crude and heating oil prices got a strong boost
from weekly American Petroleum Institute statistics that showed a
sharp decline in stocks from last year's levels.
   Crude oil inventories plunged by 25.2 million barrels from 1988
and were off 1.2 million barrels for the week ended June 16, the API
said.
   Heating oil stocks fell 11.5 million barrels from last year and
1.6 million barrels for the week, according to the API report
released after the close of trading on Tuesday.
   ``After the APIs came out and people saw that heating oil was
running so far below last year, those who had been cutting back
started to look at buying it again,'' said Jack Unger, oil broker
with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Unleaded gasoline stocks, meanwhile, rose by about 63,000 barrels
last week and by 819,000 barrels from 1988 levels.
</TEXT>
