<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-21 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heller Resignation Sparks Rally In Precious Metals Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The resignation of Federal Reserve Board member H. Robert Heller
sparked strong rallies in the gold, silver and platinum markets
Wednesday amid uncertainty about his departure's impact on interest
rates and inflation.
   On other markets, copper futures plummeted, cotton and heating
oil surged, pork bellies plunged, and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Gold futures prices rose $6.10 to $6.90 on New York's Commodity
Exchange with the contract for delivery in August at $375.70 a troy
ounce; silver settled 4.7 cents to 5.1 cents higher with July at
$5.298 a troy ounce.
   Platinum finished $6.90 to $7.70 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with July at $501.80 a troy ounce, the
contract's first close above $500 since June 8.
   The news that Heller was leaving the Fed to join the credit-card
company Visa International triggered heavy buying during the last 10
minutes of trading on all the precious-metals markets, which benefit
from inflation worries.
   The Federal Reserve's attempts to fight inflation by raising
interest rates have generally been seen as effective. The propects
of a change in the board's composition sent a buying panic through
the precious-metals markets, which were already trading higher in
reaction to a continued weakening of the dollar's value against
other major currencies.
   Heller's resignation, while not likely to change the Fed's
course, adds to the murkiness of recent economic indicators.
   ``There are a lot of cross-currents out there and people are very
uncertain about what is being said by the markets,'' said Sharon
Ziemian, a precious-metals analyst with Citibank in New York.
   Analyst Nina Lipton of the Platinum Guild International, a
platinum trade association, said platinum's close above $500 an
ounce signaled ``a real turning point'' for all the precious metals,
which had been trending lower since late last year.
   But Stephen Platt of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago saw no
such signs in the gold market.
   ``The market is not showing any sort of independent strength,''
he said.
   Copper futures plummeted on the Commodity Exchange following news
that the Canadian copper refiner Noranda Minerals had reached a new
labor agreement with workers.
   Major U.S. copper producers are also negotiating new labor
contracts, and the Noranda settlement might portend easier going for
those talks, Platt said.
   Copper settled 6.2 cents to 8 cents lower with June at $1.077 a
pound.
   Some cotton futures soared the 2 cents-a-pound daily limit on the
New York Cotton Exchange amid fears that persistent rain in the
Southeast was hampering planting and care of the crop.
   Cotton settled .93 cent to 2 cents higher with July at 68.80
cents a pound.
   Heating oil futures skyrocketed on the New York Merc, partly on a
weekly American Petroleum Institute report that showed U.S. stocks
of petroleum distillates had dropped by 1.6 million barrels last
week.
   Heating oil settled 1.83 cents to 2.29 cents higher with July at
47.98 cents a gallon; West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 39 cents
to 45 cents higher with August at $19.31 a barrel; unleaded gasoline
was .07 cent lower to 1.06 cents higher with July at 59.10 cents a
gallon.
   Frozen pork belly futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in line with weaker cash prices, which helped to drag down
the related livestock markets.
   Frozen pork bellies settled .60 cent to .98 cent lower with July
at 33.52 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent lower to .17 cent higher
with July at 49.07 cents a pound; live cattle were .20 cent to .60
cent lower with August at 70.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.42 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August at 81 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Board of Trade, with rainy weather helping to support wheat prices
and depress the corn and soybean markets.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 3{ cents higher with July at $3.99\ a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 cents lower with July at $2.65{ a
bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 5\ cents lower with July at $1.63 a
bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents lower to 2\ cents higher with July at
$7.88{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
