<FIRST>u f AM-TrumpShuttle 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru,0810</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Two Weeks Later, Trump Shuttle Getting Down to Business</BYLINE>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new grafs 6-7 to UPDATE with market estimate, comment
from Trump Shuttle president; picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, On Wednesday,
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The champagne and string quartet are gone from
the busy terminal at LaGuardia Airport, and even Donald Trump can't
master the weather to make the flights run on time for his newly
acquired Northeast shuttle airline.
   But passengers say they like the service and the Trump Shuttle
meets their needs as business travelers _ for them, the frills are
secondary.
   The billionaire developer launched his new airline two weeks ago
with a blitz of trademark Trump glitz, soon after a federal
bankruptcy judge approved his $365 million purchase of the New
York-Washington-Boston shuttle from strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   Pan Am Corp., which operates a rival shuttle and gained a big
chunk of business from Eastern, concedes that curiosity about
Trump's new service has robbed it of some passengers _ at least for
a while.
   Pan Am's share of the shuttle market ``has definitely come down,
as we expected,'' said Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon. That share
was around 75 percent two weeks ago but has slipped since Trump's
startup to 65 percent to 70 percent, she estimated.
   But Trump Shuttle President Bruce Nobles claims a bigger share
for the new service, around 45 percent to 55 percent.
   ``I'm very pleased with the way the operation is running,'' he
said Wednesday. Nobles added that he has been disappointed by the
recent run of unseasonably stormy weather in the Northeast, which
has caused many delays and cancellations.
   On Wednesday, the Trump Shuttle terminal at New York's LaGuardia
Airport was back to normal. The red and white balloons,
Mozart-playing string quartet and buffet tables laden with champagne
and finger food present for its inaugural day were gone, although
new fresh plants and big red T's remained as permanent touches.
   Thunderstorms in the Northeast snarled the shuttle's hourly
schedule and shattered Trump's advertised claim for getting the
flights off precisely on time. The red neon advisory warned of
runway delays of up to 90 minutes.
   Passengers on the 7 a.m. EDT flight from Washington's National
Airport to LaGuardia didn't arrive until 10:40 a.m., after a detour
to Albany, N.Y., for refueling. Some of the travelers arriving at
LaGuardia were exasperated but conceded that the weather is beyond
even Trump's control.
   ``I don't know how Eastern would have handled it,'' said a young
woman traveling on business to Mt. Kisco, N.Y.
   On Tuesday, with good weather, flights were running closer to
schedule although still not always exactly on the hour as promised
by Trump.
   The 7:40 a.m. New York-to-Washington run left only five minutes
late and arrived 10 minutes early, while the 5 p.m. Washington-New
York flight left only a few minutes late and arrived on time at 6
p.m.
   ``The service was fine; it's like any other airline,'' one young
businessman said Wednesday. ``It didn't seem any different to me. It
got me here, that's the main thing.''
   Trump has promised his shuttle will be a ``diamond'' service, but
a number of passengers indicated they cared more about
transportation than about Trump's planned refurbishing of the jets
in burgundy and saddle-brown tones with chrome and maple wood veneer
accents.
   On the outside, only four of Trump Shuttle's fleet of 21 Boeing
727s have been repainted in the new color scheme: white fuselage
with red, black and gold stripes, the word ``Trump'' above the
stripes and a red `T' on the tail. Except for a ``Trump'' hastily
painted in red on the rest of the planes, they still sport the
familiar Eastern silver and blue.
   The food is pretty much the same, too. On a recent morning flight
the offering was a bagel, a dollop of cream cheese, a few grapes, a
strawberry, half-frozen orange juice that had to be eaten with a
spoon and coffee served in paper cups.
   Evening fare consisted of three pieces of barbecued chicken
breast, corn-tomato salad and a slice of rye bread in a plastic box,
along with free beer, wine and soft drinks.
   Most of the 1,000 or so Trump employees were formerly with
Eastern, and many of them are enthusiastic and visibly happy to be
working again after more than three months on the picket line.
   ``It's a world of difference,'' said first officer Bill Bowen, an
18-year Eastern pilot, comparing the two airlines. ``Better working
conditions, more flexible management.''
   A young woman selling tickets at LaGuardia, also a former Eastern
employee, said, ``Donald Trump is a perfectionist. And now we get
our paychecks on time!''
</TEXT>
