<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Time-Cable     06-21 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Cable,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time's Cable Unit Says Local Officials Clamor Against Paramount Cable
Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Time, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc.'s cable television arm said Wednesday
that local opposition is growing to Paramount Communications Inc.'s
plans for acquiring Time's cable franchises as part of its hostile
$10.7 billion offer for the media giant.
   American Television and Communications Corp., which is 82 percent
owned by Time, has said Paramount's acquisition of Time would be
illegal because the change in control would place ATC in violation
of many of its cable franchise agreements.
   It said officials from the states of Kansas and Hawaii and 16
cities, including Denver and Charlotte, N.C., have complained to
federal officials that Paramount's takeover plan would abrogate the
local right of prior approval for cable franchise ownership in their
areas.
   ATC said Indianapolis Mayor William Hudnut III, for instance,
told the Federal Communications Commission in a letter that the
Paramount's takeover plan ``is fundamentally at odds'' with ATC's
franchise and local laws as well as federal laws on cable regulation.
   It said Emanuel Cleaver II, the mayor pro tem of Kansas City,
told the FCC in another letter, ``This intended action by Paramount
unquestionably will violate the express terms of our cable
television franchise.''
   ATC also said that Paramount has indicated in a court filing in
Connecticut, where ATC is based, that it will be unable to meet the
July 5 deadline it set in its $175-a-share tender offer for Time.
   Time had said in rejecting Paramount's offer last week that the
bid was highly conditional and subject to delays.
   Asked for a response, Paramount said it intends to extend the
expiration date of its tender offer until after Delaware Chancery
Court issues a decision in a suit Paramount filed Wednesday against
Time. Both companies are incorporated in Delaware.
   On the issue of the cable franchises, Paramount said it expects
to get cable franchise approval ``where required by state and local
law in an orderly and expeditious way.''
   ATC, based in Stamford, Conn., is the nation's second-largest
cable operator. with about 4.1 million subscribers.
</TEXT>
