<FIRST>r f AM-ComputerKitchen 1stLd-Writethru f0291 06-21 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Kitchen, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0291,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Fried Chicken To Install Computers for `Smart Kitchens'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to add that KFC is a division of Pepsico.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentucky Fried Chicken Corp. announced its latest
recipe Wednesday in the fast-food competition: a ``smart kitchen''
built on personal computers from NCR Corp. and software from
Microsoft Corp.
   ``Kentucky Fried Chicken will not only be able to say, `We do
chicken right,' it will also be able to say `We do it
intelligently,''' said Tom Mays, head of NCR's personal computer
division.
   The $19.5 million system will use Microsoft's OS-2 software to
control data in virtually every operation of the 1,262 company-owned
stores, from the front counter and kitchen to inventory and sales.
   The system will also be offered to franchise holders who run
another 3,600 Kentucky Fried Chicken outlets.
   The first three installations in the $19.5 million contract will
be this summer in Louisville, with complete ``rollout'' to all
stores expected in early 1991, said Monte Jones, KFC's vice
president of information resources.
   As a management tool, the ``smart kitchen'' eliminates much of
the guesswork involved in the $5 billion annual sales based on
pressure-cooked fried chicken with ``11 secret herbs and spices.''
   Ultimately, the computer system will keep a minute-by-minute
record of sales, employee hours, a running inventory of all
supplies, and a 10-week sales history, among other things.
   It will also track the supply of cooked chicken and side dishes
on hand, tell management when to cook more and when to discard food
that is past its prime.
   For customers, the computerization will cut time spent in line
about 3 percent and make it easier to change orders, said the
company, a division of Pepsico Inc.
</TEXT>
