<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-89 2141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     06-21 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Share Prices Advance Moderately in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dropped sharply in early trading
against the Japanese yen Thursday, while stock prices advanced
moderately.
   The dollar opened at 141.75 yen, a drop of 3.20 yen from
Wednesday's close of 144.95 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's decline followed sharp reteats in New
York overnight and in the Sydney market, which opened earlier than
the Tokyo market. The currency closed at 142.75 yen Wednesday in New
York, down from 144.75 yen Tuesday.
   Naoto Kawamura, a senior dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, said the
dollar came under selling pressure after investors watched the
currency fall on overseas markets. But, he added, the early trading
volume was not large.
   In New York, the dollar fell in the face of dollar-selling by
institutional investors and the Federal Reserve Bank of New York,
dealers said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which gained 111.81 points Wednesday, added another 74.60 points, or
0.22 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 33,419.88
points.
</TEXT>
